<HEADLINE>S&amp;UN plansnew plant inLanarkshire</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979255428</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH &amp; Universal Newspapers, Scotland's largest weekly newspaper
group, is to invest #9.5m in centralising its printing operations in a
new full-colour printing facility together with two publishing lines to
be installed at Blantyre Park in Lanarkshire.
The move is seen at S&amp;UN as a ''tremendous vote of confidence'' by
parent company Trinity International Holdings, the regional newspapers
group which purchased it from Lonrho in 1993.
S&amp;UN's group financial director John Williams said: ''This is the
biggest investment in the history of Scottish &amp; Universal Newspapers and
is probably the biggest investment ever by a regional weekly newspaper
group in Scotland.''
The company has signed a letter of intent to purchase a MAN Uniset
high-volume, full-colour web-offset press with a speed of 60,000 copies
per hour. By late 1996, the group's 34 titles will be distributed from a
new hi-tech factory at the greenfield site between Hamilton and East
Kilbride.
S&amp;UN director Alex Lumsden said: ''Pagination restrictions and lack of
colour on our existing preses have meant we have been unable to maximise
the opportunities which would otherwise have been open to the group.
This investment will give us the capability to print all our titles at
one centre. We will have the capacity for producing 32 pages of full
colour in a 72-page paper. We will have maximum pagination of 160
tabloid pages. The new site gives us a quick and convenient access to
the motorway network for nationwide distribution purposes.''
It is intended that the new press will also be used to contract
printing by other newspaper companies.
There will be closures at present printing operations at Irvine,
Hamilton, and Perth but S&amp;UN but job losses could be minimal, as little
as single figures. A lot could depend on whether members of the
workforce would be prepared to travel and also embrace the new
technology. In the longer term, there should be a net gain in numbers
because of increased distribution.
Meanwhile Trinity International, which also owns the Liverpool Echo
and Daily Post and the Huddersfield Daily Examiner, has lifted overall
profits 15.2% for 1994 from #19.854m to a record #22.877m before tax.
The dividend total is lifted from 9.7p to 10.7p with a final of 7.4p on
earnings per share up from 20.2p to 24p. The shares closed 1p lower at
354p.
In Scotland, increased revenues from the growth in advertising
volumes, together with the continuing benefits of cost savings from the
pre-press rationalisation, resulted in improved operating margins.
Circulation revenues again held up well with some titles showing
year-on-year increases, and leaflet volumes continued to grow.
Elsewhere, Trinity reported that in Merseyside, North Wales, and
Cheshire, advertising revenue grew encouragingly and the year finished
with a strong performance in the last quarter, especially at the
Liverpool Echo.
</TEXT>
