<DOCNO>GH950323-000002</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000002</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Thistle helps push Bruntcliffe higher</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979255430</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A GOOD performance at Thistle Aggregates from the five former Tarmac
quarries in the north and east of Scotland provided the backbone of
Bruntcliffe Aggregates' 247% leap in pre-tax profits to #2.33m last
year.
This activity will perform a similar role in 1995. Chief executive
Mike Wallis is looking forward to an increase in road expenditure in the
medium-term in the north of Scotland after a hiatus in 1994 caused by
local government reorganisation. During that time, sales of the
company's coated stone fell 17%.
However, other products such as dry stone improved and particularly
agricultural limestone containing magnesium where prices rose by nearly
50% for the product quarried at Ullapool and transported to Inverness,
the Black Isle, and Aberdeenshire.
Profits for the current year should reach about #3m which would leave
the shares at 29p trading at about nine times likely earnings.
The dividend total has been raised 150% to 1.25p with a 0.85p final
for a 5.4% yield. One to follow.
</TEXT>
