<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000004</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000004</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>How not to win friends . . .</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>LEADER</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255432</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Kurds are an unfortunate people in that their habitat contradicts
one of the basic assumptions of modern times -- they live in no single
state but are parcelled out between several. Kurdish lands stretch form
south eastern Anatolia across Iraq into Iran. North and south of that
area there are other detachments in Syria and in what used to be Russian
Transcaucasia. With all of these state authorities the Kurds have come
into conflict, and their latest encounter with the Turkish army is
simply the most recent in a long series. They have always been a
difficult people -- a bitter Kurdish saying recounts much of their
history: ''A Kurd has no friends'' -- but that need not always be true
for, from time to time, the minority coexists quietly within a wider
authority, an experience which fits Iran, Iraq, and Turkey itself.
Kurdish consciousness makes for problems and, in a region not renowned
for tolerance, seems to provoke strong reactions, which in turn
stimulates Kurdish violence.
From outside the region the obvious solution is some degree of
autonomy, but that might cut across competing sovereignties, so the
local powers see things differently, preferring to try military
solutions. This latest effort deploys large numbers of Turkish troops
and air power (Iran's latest efforts, under the Shah, were very similar
and Iraq has deployed chemical weapons like the sarin at present in the
news in Japan). Such efforts do not seem to work. The terrain and the
way the Kurds flit across international frontiers make military
certainties impossible, hence the considerable Turkish penetration into
northern Iraq which ought to bring them up against the UN proclaimed
Kurdish safe haven (even though it was intended to afford protection
from Saddam Hussein). It seems safe to assume that the Turks will not
win, but in their case the Kurdish reaction already involves third
parties: Turkish workers in Germany are the targets of the Kurdish
expatriate terrorists. Like terrorists everywhere these are hard to
counter, especially in liberal societies. In Germany the strains are
already evident with militant Kurds, never mind actual terrorists, in
some lander facing deportation to Turkey which is not a prospect any
will relish.
If the present fighting is not popular among Turks living abroad, it
seems to be quite popular at home. Some observers even suspect that the
motives of the Ankara Government in launching its most recent Kurdish
operations include the hope that these will divert attention from
demands by Islamic extremists for changes in Turkey's secular
constitution which would defer to Muslim fundamentalism. The Government
is in much the same position as, say, Egypt or Algeria: it is fighting
back, but the balance of power is delicately poised. Popular diversions
are welcome. Maintaining them, however, does nothing to further the
country's main policy aim to join the European Union, which would
enhance both the economy and political stability. The methods used in
Kurdistan are excessive, while the need to restrain the fundamentalists
compromises the civil liberties dear to the hearts of the country's
would-be European partners. The West wants to help Turkey but finds it
very hard to do so for reasons which the Kurdish campaign merely
underline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
