<HEADLINE>Bid to fight the river floods</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255433</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MAJOR package of measures has been agreed to curb flooding on the
River Irvine, which caused widespread damage when it overflowed its
banks last December.
Irvine Development Corporation, in partnership with Strathclyde
Regional Council and Cunninghame District Council, is to spend #490,000
on remedial and refurbishment work.
The river bank will be raised at Waterside, where dozens of houses
were flooded for several days, and work will be carried out at Carson
Drive to prevent river erosion.
The corporation will also spend more than #350,000, with help from
Euro funds, on the reconstruction of the weir. Sheet piling and
reinforced concrete will strengthen the weir, while a combined canoe and
fish pass will be retained.
Canoe and small boat enthusiasts are also to be catered for with a
#50,000 injection from Enterprise Ayrshire to build an access road and
launching ramps on the west bank of the river alongside the Marress
sports ground.
</TEXT>
