<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000007</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000007</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>American Trust sees 10.7% dip</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255435</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH-based American Trust anticipates lower earnings per share in
the current financial year because of its decision to sacrifice some
short-term income for longer-term earnings growth.
Consequently, the investment trust held its final dividend at 3.6p,
with the total payout for the year to end-January only 0.1p higher at
5.5p.
Net asset value fell 10.7% to 275.8p during the 12 months. In the US,
where 88% of the #230m blue-chip focused fund was invested at January
31, the Standard &amp; Poor's index fell only 7.9% in sterling terms.
However, 8% of the Edinburgh Fund Managers-run trust was invested in
the UK, where the FTSE All-Share index suffered a 15.2% setback. The
trust's Latin American holdings took a battering from the Mexican
financial crisis, which began late last year.
Earnings per share were 9.1% higher at 5.99p, boosted by higher than
expected dividends, particularly from Edinburgh Fund Managers.
American Trust, which aims for long-term capital and income growth,
has switched from investments held for current income to US shares which
it expects to produce greater income growth in the future.
However, Colin Ross, chairman of Edinburgh Fund Managers, was ''99%
certain'' that the dividend would be at least maintained this year.
During the year, American Trust sold half of its interest in Edinburgh
Fund Managers for about #10m.
The trust's Latin American holdings, concentrated in Mexico, had
fallen about 40% from their year-highs by January 31, when they
accounted for 4% of the fund.
However, the trust is committed to retaining its holdings because of
the region's growth potential, pointing out that their relatively small
presence would not seriously affect the portfolio in the event of
another calamity.
This time last year, trust chairman Lord Macfarlane of Bearsden warned
about the effects of the turn in the interest rate cycle which began
last February.
Mulling over the current uncertainty surrounding the extent of further
US interest rate rises, he said: ''Equity valuations appear reasonable
against this scenario, with upward potential if overheating of the
economy is prevented whilst maintaining a sustainable level of economic
growth.''
Mr Ross said: ''On balance, I think we believe we are nearing the end
of the restrictive period, so we are probably near the top of short-term
interest rates.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
