<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000009</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000009</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Skye woman wins top diploma</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ZOE MACKENZIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255437</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SKYE mother-of-two is the first unemployed woman in Britain to
achieve the highest possible vocational qualification in management.
Audrey Parker, 37, of Achachork, by Portree on Skye, has achieved the
Scotvec-MCI (Management Charter Initiative) Diploma in Management Level
5. Earler this week she was presented with the certificate by Ross,
Cromarty and Skye MP Charles Kennedy at a ceremony at the Lochalsh Hotel
in Kyle.
Mr Kennedy said Mrs Parker achievement was ''tremendously
significant'' -- not only for herself but for other women eager to work
or get training in remote areas like Skye and Lochalsh.
Though Mrs Parker currently works as employment adviser and back to
work team leader at the Employment Services in Portree on Skye, she
completed the diploma in just three months last year while unemployed.
Scotvec director Margery Burdon who also attended the presentation
said Audrey's achievement marked a milestone in Scotvec's 10-year
history as no-one achieved this level in such a short time with her own
staff taking up to 18 months to complete it.
Glasgow-based Management Introductions, who conducted the course on
behalf of Skye and Lochalsh Local Enterprise said the diploma was the
highest vocational qualification attainable and that Henley College in
England had contacted it wanting to know how Mrs Parker had achieved it
so quickly.
To attain the diploma, managers are examined through an
''accreditation of prior to learning'' system whereby evidence of their
competence as a manager is provided by testimonies from people in their
previous employment which are set against a framework of national
standards. It also involves a hefty element of written work to show
competence in finance and personnel skills.
Management Introductions Business Development director Bill Gallaher
said that though the diploma had been in existence for two years only
employed people had achieved it until now.
''They go out and get a job then apply to do the diploma. Audrey was
different, she had to get her brain in gear and recall how she did these
things according to national standards,'' said Mr Gallaher.
Mrs Parker was a manager in both the public and private sector since
the age of 25 when she became office manager for RCA in Galloway. After
having her son Jason at 27 she became a youth leader for six months
before entering the employment service in 1986 and worked in their
Dumfries, Forfar, and Dundee offices.
But promotion for her husband Michael to the Scottish Office
Agriculture and Fisheries Department on Skye meant that Mrs Parker
experienced a two-year spell on the other side of the employment service
counter. ''Living on Skye and being out of work gives you a better
appreciation of what it's like to be unemployed in a remote area,'' she
said.
''Although Galloway is a rural area it is certainly not as isolated as
Skye where the geographical distances mean you can't attend a university
or college.''
Both Dr Burdon and chief executive Lorne MacLeod of Skye and Lochalsh
Local Enterprise -- which financed the course -- said Mrs Parker was an
excellent role model for others attempting to qualify for the diploma.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000010</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000010</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979255438</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MANAGEMENT group has bought New South Mills from Sidlaw Group, which
expects to realise over #2m from the transaction.
A new company, whose shareholders are a former director, members of
the management, and institutional and other investors, has agreed to pay
#1.318m for the Dundee-based business.
The initial payment is to be #243,000 on completion, with the balance
payable in two instalments of #500,000 and #575,000 respectively on
September 30, 1995 and 1996. Debtors less creditors, which are excluded
from the sale, are expected to realise #700,000.
New South Mills was formerly part of the face yarns division of Sidlaw
Textiles, and its disposal marks the final step in the group's decisions
to sell its textile interests.
Sidlaw's chief executive, Digby Morrow, said: ''We are pleased to have
completed the sale of the group's textile interests and to have
preserved the continuity of the face yarns business.
''We wish the new management and employees of the business every
success in the future.''
Bank borrowings are to be reduced as a result of the deal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000011</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000011</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>B&amp;Q to open giant store in Aberdeen</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL MAGEE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979255439</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MORE than 250 new jobs will be created in the Aberdeen area when
Britain's largest DIY store opens next week.
The warehouse-type store is a #6m B&amp;Q supercentre which represents the
most advanced of its kind to date, the home improvements retail giant
said yesterday.
It is the first in a new generation of DIY warehouses with four more
planned throughout the UK during 1995. One is due to open in Glasgow in
the second half of the year.
Aberdonian Ronnie Stephen is in charge of the new North-east store. He
has seven managers working with him. They head a total staff of 280, the
bulk of whom are new starts.
The Aberdeen development opens on March 31 and takes up 135,000 sq ft,
almost three times larger than the average DIY superstore.
Mr Stephen said his staff had merchandised and planned their store
layout themselves. ''They have undergone intensive training to develop
knowledge of 40,000 product lines.''
Bill Whiting, marketing director, with overall responsibility for B&amp;Q
warehouses throughout Britain, said economies of scale meant the
Aberdeen development would offer the lowest prices on all products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000012</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000012</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scottish Friendly opens HQ.  New office cost #5m</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255440</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Friendly Assurance, which has changed its name and become
incorporated within the last three years, yesterday officially opened
new #5m headquarters.
The society's move to new offices in Glasgow's Blythswood Square, home
to the major accountancy firm KPMG and the Royal Automobile Club, is
partly the result of the plethora of new financial services which the
1992 Friendly Societies Act allows it to offer.
Derek Lee, the London-based chairman of the Friendly Societies
Commission, declared Scottish Friendly House open yesterday, even though
staff transferred from 200 Bath Street in November.
Although 133 years old, Scottish Friendly, whose image transformation
encompassed its change of name from the City of Glasgow Friendly Society
in 1992, has undergone a process of dramatic change in recent times.
In the wake of the Act, it has augmented its traditional home
collection-orientated life insurance business with general
insurance-broking for clients.
Scottish Friendly, originally established by a group of workers who
wanted a friendly society of their own, this month launched its
unit-linked Scottish Investment Bond. This offers investors the fairly
unique option of a Scottish investment trust fund.
Chancellor Kenneth Clarke's increase in the limit for tax-free
investments in friendly societies in last November's Budget, to be
implemented in May, will provide another boost.
Scottish Friendly, which manages #130m of funds and has about 300,000
policyholders, is looking at the development of unit trusts and PEPs. It
could even move into residential care.
The society, incorporated in January 1994, spent about a year and
#2.5m on the refurbishment of its new headquarters, having bought the
23,000 sq ft building for #2.5m. It intends to lease half of it.
Scottish Friendly hopes the Blythswood Square building will have a
greater pull on independent financial advisers, as well as resulting in
improved customer service.
Chairman Ian Smail described the opening as a ''momentous stage in the
history of the Scottish Friendly Assurance Society Limited''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000013</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000013</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>General Cable not for investors in a hurry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<FLAG>COMMENT,SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979255441</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GENERAL Cable indicated in May last year its intention to come to the
stock market, and it has now fixed the date as April 27, when it will
aim to raise between #198m and #220m, the exact amount depending on the
price to be decided nearer the time.
General Cable will have a capitalisation of up to #646m, which
compares with the #1500m market value of TeleWest, the only UK-listed
cable operator so far. Other companies such as Nynex UK and Bell
Multimedia are likely to follow.
Attracted by the low regulatory requirements in the UK, American cable
companies dominate the industry here, though General Cable is an
exception, being owned by the diversified French utility Compagnie
Generale des Eaux, which also has a major slice of the French cable
market. Apart from the need to raise money to pay for cable
installation, floating the companies on the UK stock market gives them a
more local feel.
General Cable's franchises cover 1,700,000 homes in west London,
Yorkshire and Birmingham. But it has been no more successful than others
in persuading people to be connected. Along with associates, it has
124,000 TV subscribers, 106,000 residential phone lines installed and
15,900 business lines. British consumers have not exactly been falling
over themselves to sign up for cable networks, partly because existing
terrestrial programming is adequate for most people.
The company has 14% of UK cable TV subscribers, 16% of cable-connected
telephone lines for residential use and 22% for business use. So it has
a reasonable share of the overall market.
There is no doubt it is developing into a major industry, if not quite
as rapidly as enthusiasts thought it would. It expects to take on 6400
new employees this year bringing the total to more than 26,000. Spending
is running at some #2000m a year, and a third of the country should be
covered by the end of 1995. For once these are real jobs in engineering,
construction, sales and customer services, and many are occurring in the
inner cities where employment is so urgently required.
Cable TV is actually a misnomer, at least as far as General Cable is
concerned, because telephone services are more important than television
to its subscribers. TV customers provided an average gross margin
(revenues minus programming and telephone interconnect charges) of #118
per subscriber, compared with #182 per residential telephone line and
#526 per business exchange line.
It is not surprising that the company is concentrating on developing
business telecommunications services. This also makes sense given its
Birmingham and west London franchises. The latter includes Heathrow
Airport and surrounding business parks.
The cable TV operators have a price advantage of 10%-15% over BT which
explains why they are all selling telephone connections. But it is a
risky strategy given BT's proven ability to strike back as its costs
fall. Mercury has found this out to its cost.
TeleWest appears to have a better balanced business and its offer for
sale was six times over-subscribed. General Cable is unlikely to prove
as popular, but there is little doubt its share offer will be
comfortably subscribed given the perceived long-term growth prospects of
the developing multi-media world.
Worthwhile profits are years away yet. General Cable expects to be
cash positive by the end of the year, though it will pay no dividends
for the foreseeable future. The fact the cable TV companies can raise
money easily in the City is one in the eye for those who say financial
institutions can only think in the short term.
The industry is developing fast and is fragmented, with many
franchises split several ways between different companies, but in the
end there will inevitably be consolidation, as is now happening in the
US. When this occurs it will be useful for the dominant operators to mop
up others with equity rather than cash given their heavy capital
commitments.
General Cable intends to issue up to 90 million shares, with 45%
offered in the US, where cable TV companies carry high ratings, and 45%
in the UK. The sponsor is Lazard Brothers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000014</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000014</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Custom-made suits cut for that sinking feeling</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255442</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEIL MacMillan has been cutting suits for many years but you will not
find any of his customers walking down the High Street sporting their
made to measure garments.
You are more likely to find Neil's customers fully submerged in water
or at least up to their waist in it. Neil (pictured right) and his
partner Steve Curzon manufacture wet and dry suits for divers and breast
waders for anglers.
They launched their company Muir Deise a year ago, and since then have
found a big demand for their wet gear.
''We did not get any financial assistance from government grants,''
says Neil, ''there was too much hassle attached to getting the money and
we would have spent our time preparing reports rather than producing the
goods''.
The name Muir Deise is gaelic for ''ocean suits'', and the choice of
name is explained by the fact that Neil's father came from the Hebrides
and is a Gaelic speaker.
Although Muir Deise sells their various products to other specialist
outlets Neil says that many customers choose to come to their premises
in Robertson Street, Glasgow to be measured for their ''ocean suit''.
Muir Deise at presently concentrating on the Scottish market although
they have mail order customers from throughout the UK, and recently were
asked to supply sample suits to a store in Massachusetts.
In common with the more conventional suits Neil says water fashions
change and that more divers and surfers are opting for a dry rather than
a wet suit while the material commonly used is now neoprene.
''This material is a warmer fabric,'' explains Neil, who looks after
the production side of the business while his partner Steve takes care
of the finances.
</TEXT>
