<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Go to work on an OVUM if you want to make a stink</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANTHONY TROON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS,INNUMERATE NERD</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979255443</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT'S thoroughly depressing to hear that Kenneth Clarke has put the
''feelgood factor'' on hold for several years. Most of us are not
terribly sure what the ''feelgood factor'' is, exactly: now we have to
wait longer to find out. When it finally arrives, we may discover it
doesn't apply across the board. So instead of rich and poor, we are
divided into feelgoods and feelbads.
''At the moment,'' said The Braces, ''I have a feelconned factor. This
is what you get when a politician promises you something, isn't able to
explain precisely what it is, then tells you -- sorry -- it's a bit
behind schedule.'' He sipped greyish coffee from his Nerd House paper
cup.
I said: ''If feelgood finally materialises, there's a possibility that
Kenneth Clarke might not still be in office. Therefore he's hardly
likely to refer to it. Therefore we might never learn what it's supposed
to be.''
Grim but true, agreed The Braces. Even worse, we had many more hurdles
to jump before that. He listed them as follows:
The feeldumb factor, in which Kenneth Clarke assures us that while
feelgood has not actually manifested itself, all the factors leading to
it are working away invisibly, and especially in Consett. Just look
around you: use your imagination.
The feeltwitchy factor, in which Kenneth Clarke allows more than a
fortnight to pass without mentioning the feelgood factor, and you wonder
whether he has forgotten about it. You wonder whether it would be a good
idea to jog his memory.
The feelsick factor, in which Kenneth Clarke starts mentioning
feelgood once again, hand over fist, and you know the Cabinet has
secretly agreed on a date for the General Election.
Ms Angelica Banana-Skyne, the High Whitecraigs polymath, had another
theory. ''Clarke's 'feelgood factor' is simply a replacement for
Lamont's 'green shoots of the economy', she said. ''Every Chancellor has
to have a slogan. I call it the OVUM -- the Optimistically Vague
Unquantifiable Mantra. When we have a new Chancellor, we'll have a new
OVUM.''
But, I asked, didn't ovum mean egg? ''Exactly,'' she said. ''Until you
crack it, you don't know whether it stinks or not.'' Angelica is wasted.
She should be occupying the Chair of Cynicism at Strathclyde University.
* ''If you're going to dump, don't dump a financial journalist if
you're Deputy Governor of the Bank of England. That's dumb.'' (Aphorism
of the Week from Ms Mary Ellen Synon.)
Some of us at Nerd House have been thinking deeply about this new
wisdom. It has a certain sharp focus. It speaks of our times, our
experience in the Sleazy Nineties . . . It's a helluva lot better than
the catch-all ''Hell hath no fury . . .''etc.
Obviously, all those antediluvian aphorisms and superannuated sayings
are long overdue for an update. This thought caused a flurry of e-mail
around the office as we used crucial office time to compose some new and
more relevant maxims, reflecting the way we are now. Here are some of
the worse ones:
''A stitch in time is far too much trouble. Better to throw away the
shirt.''
''Look after the pennies and the bank will charge you a surprising
amount for looking after the pounds, and only tell you afterwards.''
''Absence from the office is the mother of invention.''
''Honesty is the best policy if you really want a hundred journalists
camping outside your door for three days.''
''Silence might be golden, but nobody ever made a living out of it, or
even got their own back.''
''Love makes the world go round the tabloid newspaper offices until,
wow, up comes the offer it can't refuse.''
I looked over this collection on my screen with a curling lip. Then I
keystroked ''exit''. Maybe they'll be out of date next week. Maybe the
world will be different.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
