<HEADLINE>The word is out about shirt tales</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HARRY CONROY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS,PEOPLE BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255444</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE is little chance of readers not spotting Eileen West's short
stories for she prints them on the back and front of T-shirts.
Appropriately enough her company, which Eileen (pictured left) formed
eighteen months ago, is called TopStory.
She decided to go up front with her stories after reading a report
about how little the younger generation read.
''I was appalled by the statistics, and decided to do something to
encourage youngsters to read, and as many of them wear T-shirts I
decided to encourage them to read by making writing fashionable,'' says
Eileen.
Kincardine and Deeside Enterprise Trust thought her idea was very
innovative, and helped Eileen with a grant.
The T-shirt tales are normally restricted to 650 words which takes up
the front and back of the garments which she admits gives people a
different reason for people asking you to ''turn round'' when they are
admiring your new clothes.
Among the writings to adorn TopStory apparel is Eileen's own
children's story A Tail Tale and James Thurber's story for adults The
Patient Bloodhound.
But, she says mainatains, there is no limit to the type of stories
used which to date have included horror material popular among
teenagers.
Eileen, however, admits that she is not much use at science fiction or
fantasy writing and would be grateful if anyone could supply her with
suitable material.
During the tourist season, Eileen is hopeful that her T-shirts will be
sold in heritage and craft centres, and she is prepared to custom design
her stories to suit a particular area or building.
''I have already been asked by one tourist board to write a story
about their particular area and a craft centre in Airdrie have also
asked me to prepare material on their locality,'' she says.
Molly Brown, a well know short story author from New York has also
told Eileen that TopStorey can use her material on T-shirts as long as
Eileen sends her a couple of T-shirts.
''I was really delighted with this response,'' says Eileen, ''as
obviously you have to be very careful about copyright''.
</TEXT>
