<HEADLINE>Performance Plus firmly under conductor's orders</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH DOUGHERTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255445</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IF ever there was a duo that knows the score, it's Marco Romano and
Alison Barton, partners in marriage and partners in Performance Plus.
For their new venture, an original composition in the music business
in Scotland, offers, for the first time, a one-stop-shop for musical
performance.
''Both of us have nearly 20 years each of making a living as
professional musicians,'' explains Marco, a conductor to trade.
''Alison is a singer, and, together, we've worked with orchestras
great and famous, as well as the lesser known. That way, we've picked up
all the pitfalls in the trade, and that's what gives us the 'plus' in
the title of the business.''
Performance Plus promises to bring customers, individual, business and
artistic, the best in musical performers. ''We can provide anything from
a single singer to a complete orchestra, complete with conductor, of
course,'' smiles Marco.
And the business is looking at gaps in the market, with an eye,
especially, to providing the full range of musical performance services
to remote areas outwith the central belt of the country.
''We plan to take the best of live, classical music to the highlands,
islands and to Galloway,'' enthuses Alison. ''But we're not an agency
for freelance musicians. We also perform ourselves and we are able to
advise customers on the musical technicalities of what they want. Our
job is to get our clients the best possible deal. That's why we're in
business.''
At 36 and 33 respectively, Marco and Alison decided that the time had
come to face the music.
''We met at the Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama,'' said
Marco. ''Now we're at the age when many Scottish musicians go south for
security and to take the next step in their career. Neither of us want
to do that, and, with a five-year-old daughter, we've decided to stick
to the quality of life that Glasgow offers, while we make music.''
Music is in Marco's blood, for his father, Giulio, was the Royal
Scottish National Orchestra's longest-serving celloist. ''But,'' he
readily admits, ''I did have to get down to reading a different sort of
musical score -- the rules of running a business.''
Marco spent six months with IMS Trust, learning about marketing, cash
flow and the complexities of taking a new stage, where economic reality,
rather than the conductor's baton, rules.
''I was very impressed by the concept form the start,'' comments John
Glen, IMS Trust business adviser, who took Marco and Alison's score to
the world of work with his own variation on a theme.
Now, with start-up funding from the East End Partnership, Performance
Plus is firmly under conductor's orders. The Dennistoun due are out, in
the best possible marketing taste, of course, to blow their own
trumpets, french horns, bassoons, or anything else the customer
requires, to bring classical music to anyone who wants it.
And their own favourite piece of music? ''Encores from customers,''
says Marco. ''That's what's really music to our ears!''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
