<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NFC on tough road</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979255446</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NFC shares initially lost ground on a disappointing results statement
but perked up afterwards on the appointment of Gerry Murphy, at present
chief executive of Greencore, an Irish food group, as chief executive
from June 1.
They ended 4p ahead at 169p even though the group indicated that it
would be several months before it would see an improvement in results
relative to 1994. Profits for the first quarter to January 21 were down
from #29.2m to #20.4 before exceptionals, though the first interim
dividend is pegged at 1.4p.
NFC is facing tough markets and sees major cost-cutting as essential.
A new chairman, Sir Christopher Bland, arrived in January, and a major
review of the activities has begun.
The first quarter saw reorganisation costs of #5m and further
provisions will be required for redundancies, site disposals and
withdrawal from unprofitable contracts. Over the past 18 months the
group has set aside some #40m for restructuring, of which about half has
been used.
On the transport side, UK operating profits were down 19% at #13.3m as
margins came under pressure. New business gains were below expectations
but NFC says prospects are looking better. In Europe losses rose to
#1.9m mainly due to problems at German Frigoscandia, which was acquired
last year. New management has been installed.
North American profits were slightly down at #6.8m due to the weak
dollar and lower margins.
</TEXT>
