<HEADLINE>Fear of hostile reaction was crucial factor in rate rise timing. Bank plays market tune</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>R E DUNDAS, CHIEF FINANCIAL EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979255447</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FEAR of a hostile reaction from financial markets was the crucial
factor in determining the timing of the February 2 rise in interest
rates, which was implemented immediately after the regular monthly
meeting between the Chancellor of the Exchequer, Kenneth Clarke, and the
Governor of the Bank of England, Eddie George.
Both men detected signs that the growth rate was moderating, but they
doubted if activity would slow sufficiently to prevent a pick-up in
underlying inflation, the minutes of the meeting showed.
There was agreement that interest rates would have to rise in either
February or March. The Governor said that financial markets were
''rather fragile, given the situation in Mexico, political concerns in
some countries in Europe, and the perception that interest rates more or
less everywhere had passed their trough''.
He believed that UK markets would be left vulnerable to an adverse
shift of sentiment if interest rates were not increased sooner rather
than later.
''To delay and then have to move under market pressure would be very
damaging to the whole approach to monetary management being pursued.''
Mr Clarke recognised the risks in the fragile market conditions. Since
the decision was essentially about timing it turned largely on market
tactics.
''If an interest rate rise were delayed market expectations of future
interest rates might be lowered. But against that the previous interest
rate rises had the effect of lowering the interest rate expectations
implicit in the futures markets, and long-term rates had fallen.''
Ironically, since base rates were raised by half-a-point to 6.75% in
response to these arguments, sterling has been in the toils, mainly
because of the battle royal between the weak US dollar and the strong
German mark. In addition, the Government's political problems have
undermined sentiment in the pound.
On the other hand, the outlook on interest rates has improved with
futures markets discounting smaller rises than previously, but this is
part of an international trend.
Since the February 2 meeting activity indicators have been relatively
subdued and inflation data no worse then expected. City pundits
generally reckon interest rate policy is currently on hold, though there
is concern that the decline in sterling's international value could
threaten a fresh bout of inflation.
Inflation figures later today are expected to show an unchanged
headline rate of 3.3% last month, with the underlying rate moderating
from 2.8% in January to 2.7% or 2.6%.
A new measure of inflation, RPIY, which excludes indirect and local
authority taxes as well as mortgage interest payments, is also expected
to retreat from an estimated 1.7% in January to about 1.5%.
The main feature of the February 2 minutes was the attention paid to
market expectations in determining monetary policy. Mr George emphasised
he was not arguing that ''we should always respond to market
sensitivity''.
But City analysts decided that the authorities were keen to stay ahead
of market expectations on future interest rate moves. This led some to
conclude that the next rise could be expected in May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Patience should pay off at Weir Group</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255448</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LORD Weir and Sir Ron Garrick may have to spend a little more time
educating the City about the merits of the core Weir Group businesses
and the #135m acquisition last year of EnviroTech if they want to
prevent further share price slides such as yesterday's 14p reverse to
226p.
That came after it was revealed that full-year pre-tax profits had
fallen 19% to #30.5m following some #7.8m of costs. These arose from the
reshaping of the group after the US takeover and reducing the activities
of the pumps business in Manchester because of depressed demand for
spares.
After allowing for these costs, the underlying business saw a profits
slip just 4%, while the dividend total has been raised 7% to 6.96p,
maintaining the unbroken growth pattern stretching back a dozen years
and putting the shares on a 3.8% yield.
Turnover from the continuing businesses slipped #9m to #440m with
another #35m attributable to EnviroTech.
In January, Weir issued a trading statement which knocked 42p off the
stock to 251p partly because it felt that some analysts' forecasts were
far too high. The reaction was exacerbated because in October, Weir had
launched a #96m rights issue at 252p.
The belief now is that the company is running a much stronger
business.
There is plenty of good news for the future. Although margins on
engineering products, basically pump manufacture, declined last year
from 7.5% to 6.8% and were as low as 6.6% in the second half, the
indications are that there is now stabilisation. The return on
engineering services improved from 8.6% to 9.1%, while that at
EnviroTech amounted to 9.2% in the first three months under Weir
ownership.
So as the benefits of the merger and the extension of the product
range into pumps capable of handling highly-abrasive liquids and
slurries such as those in the mining industry, where demand is currently
strong, filter through, there is potential for a substantial improvement
in group margins.
There was a highly-successful week-long sales seminar in February at
the headquarters in Cathcart, Glasgow, which has resulted in several
major management initiatives.
Rationalisation will reduce costs by #2m this year and #5m next. But
behind all this is the increasing order book in the fourth quarter. It
jumped from #91m to #133m in the core business including a #16m order
from Italian contractors for a Lebanese power station for pump equipment
to be delivered around the end of this year. The Italians were unable to
find full project finance off their own bat but Weir helped out with the
assistance of the ECGD which guaranteed #50m.
That order backlog seems set to continue as global economies begin to
recover although overall power station work is very low margin, with
main contractors apparently sometimes bidding at no better than cost.
Dollar devaluation has been something of a problem as a fair
proportion of the turnover is in that currency, rising with EnviroTech
which accumulated #32m of orders in the December quarter.
Weir in 1995 should have turnover well in excess of #600m but Sir Ron
indicated that it will be second six months before the initial benefits
of the integration of EnviroTech come through, with 1996 seeing their
full effects.
John Dean at broker Albert E Sharp is looking for profits of #46m this
year and reckons the shares are a buy on a medium-term basis for the
patient investor. They are selling at about 14 times likely earnings but
should show above average growth next year and beyond.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000021</DOCNO>
