<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>DTI launches biotech awareness initiative</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255449</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE biotechnology industry is estimated to have been worth #3800m last
year. However, it is developing rapidly and by the year 2000 could be
worth #60bn. The Department of Trade and Industry and particularly its
president, Michael Heseltine, is keen that British companies take
advantage of the potential of biotechnology, in a similar fashion to
information technology, to enhance their competitiveness.
''We are very concerned to ensure that British industry wakes up to
the importance of biotechnology,'' he said. Mr Heseltine firmly believes
that ''industry is on the threshold of a major bio-revolution''.
To this end the DTI has launched the Biotechnology Means Business
(BMB) initiative, aimed at raising awareness of biotechnology across
industry. A sum of #10m has been set aside to cover the four-year
programme. Its strong science and academic research base provides the UK
with an advantage over many of its European partners. There are already
160 biotechnology companies in the UK covering a broad spread of
activities.
Many people including those running businesses both large and small
currently have little idea how valuable biotechnology can be in
manufacturing and service industries. It is not just useful in
biomedical and pharmaceutical fields but across a wide sprectrum of
activities.
Research carried out by PA Consulting on behalf of the DTI has
identified 10 key industries where current awareness of biotechnology
applications is low but where its potential benefits may be high. Around
74,000 companies are thought to meet these criteria. They are in:
pharmaceuticals and diagnostics, agriculture and agrochemicals,
industrial and scientific equipment, chemicals and allied products, food
and drink, paper and pulp, textiles, leather and allied products,
petroleum refining and allied industries and, finally, water and waste
treatment.
The DTI has highlighted several of the benefits of using
biotechnology. These include increased profitability and efficiency,
simplified compliance with legislation, reduced environmental impact,
better quality assurance and improved consumer safety. It can also
facilitate the introduction of new products. For example, almost all
washing powders sold today are enzyme-based, genetic fingerprinting is
used to help solve crimes, and biotechnology has been used to produce
disease-resistant crops and new kinds of foodstuffs such as tomatoes
which make better sauce.
Those seeking information on how biotechnology may help their own
particular business can ring a free helpline backed by a technical
support service on 0800 432100 for general information. More detailed
information is available in a series of fact sheets. Seminars and
workshops are to be held at venues around the country during the course
of the year. Details of the Scottish ones have yet to be finalised.
Michael Heseltine
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000022</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000022</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Blast from Barratt</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255450</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SIR Lawrie Barratt launched into the Government's three increases in
interest rates as being one reason for his not expecting an improvement
in the number of houses to be built in 1995, writes ANDREW WILSON.
He said that its support had been disappointing compared with that
during the Thatcher period when 5[1/2] million people became
home-owners.
In the past three years, Government support had not been there and it
had breached the 1992 Conservative Manifesto in that mortgage tax relief
had been cut. He added that there had been disastrous action in November
when the Budget reduced the degree of housing income support.
Sir Lawrie was speaking after the Newcastle-based housebuilder had
emerged with half-time results 42% ahead at #16.1m -- bang in line with
the middle of City expectations.
Market men took the knife to the share price, slicing 14p off at 171p,
while Sir Lawrie day bought 100,000 shares at 179p for a family trust.
He added that UK national sales rose 4[1/2]% to 143,000 huses in 1994
rather than the 10% expected and that there would be no improvement in
1995.
Average prices rose from #74,600 to #77,900, reflecting the greater
concentration now on the south-east of England. Barratt has 33 sites
within the M25 orbit where prices are around 50% higher than the UK
average for the equivalent quality of property.
UK house margins improved from 8.9% to 9.6% -- well below the UK
average as Barratt is still working through uneconomic land bought at
the peak of the boom. It is perhaps a little worrying that Barratt
having spent #80m on land in the first half and plans to spend another
#100m in the current six months.
Full-year profits could rise from #35.2m to about #48m to leave the
shares trading at 9[1/2] times likely earnings. The interim dividend has
been raised 0.5p to 2.5p, pointing to a full-year payout of 7.5p for a
5.5% yield.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
