<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dewhurst owners call in the receivers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979255452</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNION International, controlled by the Vestey family and owners of
butchers' shop chain J H Dewhurst, yesterday called in administrative
receivers.
Receivers have also been appointed to Dewhurst which takes in the
Munro chain in Scotland, including 11 branches in Glasgow and seven in
Edinburgh.
However, it is the intention that all the shops continue to trade
until a buyer has been found, either for the whole lot or in parts.
Union said Alan Bloom, Gareth Hughes and Jason Elles of Ernst &amp; Young
have been appointed joint administrative receivers to Union.
The company said its bankers had on Tuesday required it to put
Dewhurst into receivership as a condition for continued lending.
Union's board met yesterday and decided that it could not continue
trading if Dewhurst was put into receivership and therefore applied for
the whole company to go into receivership.
The company nearly went into receivership in 1991 with debts of #430m
but was successfully restructured by former Lonrho director Terry
Robinson.
Union is controlled by the Vestey family whose fortune once topped
#1400m, but their financial position has taken a turn for the worse in
recent years.
The Vesteys ranked 17th -- at about #600m -- in The Sunday Times's
latest league table of Britain's richest people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000025</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000025</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Strachan's unique deal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255453</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GORDON Strachan walked out on Leeds yesterday to join Coventry as
their manager-elect.
In a unique deal, the Scot has been given a three-year contract which
includes a clause that he will be offered the team manager's job in two
years' time, in succession to Ron Atkinson.
Strachan, who had been offered a similar deal at Leeds, opted to turn
his back on Elland Road after six years to serve his managerial
apprenticeship under one of the game's top managers.
Atkinson, who referred to a possible link-up with the player when was
appointed Coventry manager four weeks ago, believes his decision to put
the proposal into a contract persuaded Strachan to leave Leeds.
Atkinson said: ''It makes sense for Gordon to learn the ropes for a
couple of years without having any of the pressures. He can learn all
about the administrative side, transfers and so on from me as we go
along from day to day, so that he can then make the step up.''
But Atkinson sidestepped questions on his own future at that time. It
has been suggested that he might join Coventry's board as director of
football, but he said: ''Who knows what might happen in two years'
time?''
Strachan, 38, has retained his playing registration, but said: ''I
don't expect to play first team football, unless we get a lot of
injuries. I am more interested in the coaching side at the moment, but I
would like to play in the reserves.''
Atkinson signed Strachan for Manchester United in 1984 and the
Scotland international won an FA Cup winners' medal the following year
but, after Atkinson's departure, found himself out of favour under his
old Aberdeen manager, Alex Ferguson, and moved to Leeds in March, 1989.
Strachan, who won 50 caps, skippered Leeds to the second division
championship in his first full year and to the League title two years
later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000026</DOCNO>
