<HEADLINE>Brain haemorrhage threat to former Scotland winger. Soccer unites to will Cooper through</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255454</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Pointing the way: Davie Cooper seen in action at an earlier television
coaching session, and the former Scotland winger still has much to offer
the sport.
SCOTTISH football was willing Davie Cooper to win his fight for life
last night after the former World Cup star had been rushed to the
Southern General Hospital after having suffered a brain haemorrhage.
The 39-year-old Clydebank player, who won 22 caps for Scotland, has
long been recognised as perhaps the last of the great Scottish wingers,
a throw-back to the glory days of the game. That was why he was involved
in a coaching video which was being filmed at Broadwood Stadium
yesterday when he collapsed.
Initially those working with him -- and the 14 schoolboys who were
taking part -- thought Cooper was joking when he slumped to the ground.
One of them shouted -- ''OK, Davie, the joke's over.''
Then Celtic's Charlie Nicholas, who was appearing with Cooper,
suddenly realised the seriousness of the situation.
''Davie had just asked me if I fancied going for a pint when we were
finished,'' said Nicholas, ''and I said that sounded like a good idea. I
turned away and then when I looked back he was on the ground.
''I think all of us thought he was kidding around, but then I saw some
blood coming from his mouth and I knew it was bad. The programme
director gave him mouth-to-mouth resuscitation until an ambulance
arrived. His pulse had actually stopped.
''Everyone is shattered and all we can do is hope that Coop pulls
through. That's what we all want. Everyone wants the same thing.''
That was the message from the sport last night as people remembered
Cooper's golden days at Ibrox -- and his marvellous performances at
Motherwell in the autumn of his career.
The chairman of the Fir Park club, John Chapman, recalled: ''On the
way to Easter Road for the game we heard on the radio that a Clydebank
player had been taken ill, and a minute or two later Dougie Arnott said
it was Davie Cooper.
''We were all very shocked, still are. Indeed, all of Motherwell will
be shocked. Davie was very fit, he trained hard, and his worth to us was
incalculable. When he joined us in l989, at the start of our Scottish
Cup winning season, the enthusiasm he generated was tremendous.''
And after the match in Edinburgh, Motherwell manager Alex McLeish, who
played in Scotland sides with Cooper, was too upset to talk to
reporters, leaving the ground close to tears, while Alex Miller, the
Hibs manager who played in the same Ibrox side with Cooper, said:
''Football pales into insignificance at times like this. Here we have a
man so young in a situation like this. It is tragic.''
At Ibrox, where Cooper spent 12 seasons, manager Walter Smith said
that everyone at the club wished him a speedy recovery, and captain
Richard Gough, who often shared a room with the winger when the team was
travelling, added his own personal memories.
''It's hard to believe that this has happened to Coop,'' said Gough.
''I was quite close to him when we were at Ibrox. He is not the easiest
guy to get to know, because he has always been a bit of a loner, but I
like to think I have been one of his mates.
''I played against him when I was with Dundee United and learned then
just how good a player he was. He was magnificent and I always felt a
sorrow that Graeme Souness had not arrived at Ibrox a few seasons
earlier and given Coop even better days.
''Let's face it, there were times in the early eighties when he
carried that Rangers team on his own. We all hope he pulls through
this.''
Former Celtic captain and manager, Billy McNeill, added: ''At his peak
Davie Cooper had an abundance of skill. It is to his eternal credit that
he always went out to display his undoubted talent. And it is an
indictment of our game that he did not win more honours during his
career.
''Like everyone else I hope he comes through this because he still has
so much to offer the game, either in coaching or in his role on
television, where he always talks sense.''
Cooper was discovered playing juvenile football for Hamilton Avondale
in 1974, and Clydebank's Jack Steedman persuaded him to join the
Kilbowie Park club. Three years later he was sold to Rangers for
#100,000. Today Cooper's wing wizardry would command a fee in millions.
Last night, Steedman, obviously distressed, said: ''Our thoughts are
with Davie and his family. We are concerned about his mum and dad at
this time and we know what they must be going through.
''All we want is for Davie to make a full recovery. He has a future
here at the club. He has always been the blue-eyed boy here and he
remains that . . .''
Before his club's vital Premiership clash with Arsenal, Manchester
United manager Alex Ferguson, who took Cooper to Mexico for the World
Cup finals there in 1986, told me: ''It is hard to grasp what has
happened to Davie. He played for Scotland when I was with the national
squad and all we can hope is that he comes through this ordeal.
''I have always kept in touch with him and when he was at his best I
was one of his greatest admirers. Just a marvellous, marvellous
player.''
His old Ibrox colleague, Derek Johnstone, echoed that -- ''I never
played with a greater player than Davie Cooper at any time in my
career,'' he insisted.
''The strength and determination he showed as a player are vital to
him in this fight.''
</TEXT>
