<TEXT>
THE continued downward trend in red meat consumption impacted Bernard
Matthews, the turkey and red meat producer last year.
However, it is attempting to boost its sales through the introduction
of new cooked meat ranges and lamb products from its subsidiary Advanced
Foods in New Zealand.
This together with its growing business on the Continent enabled it to
report higher-than-expected annual results in 1994. In the 52 weeks to
January 1, 1995, profit before tax rose to a record #18.6m, an increase
of 65% on the previous year. Overall, group sales were up 45% to
#145.5m. There is a final dividend of 1.82p making a total for the year
of 3.14p, an increase of over 25% on 1993's payout.
Sales in its UK turkey businesss rose more than 10% on the back of
strong demand for branded range products and further development of the
fresh turkey range. Although heavy price discounting by retailers of
oven ready turkeys before Christmas boosted consumption it menat that
Bernard Matthews could not increase its prices.
Demand for its range of cooked meats continued to expand. In addition,
new ranges of added value fresh and frozen products are to introduced in
the near future.
Its Hungarian subsidiary continued to make a significant contribution
to the group's profits. In France and Germany, increasing sales of
existing products and the introduction of new products helepd to improve
the trading position.
The group has a strong balance sheet and despite two acquisitions in
the year at a total cost of #13.7m, net geaing at the year-end was below
20%. This helathy financial position will enable the group to make
further acquisitions should a suitable opportunity arise.
Bernard Matthews
