<DOCID>GH950323-000028</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Winging into fans' hearts and minds</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR, CHIEF SPORTS WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>30</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255456</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SOME of us were assembling in Edinburgh to watch a football match
yesterday when tragedy struck Davie Cooper, and as we waited, mostly in
silence, for news of his condition, there was a powerful reluctance to
pay much attention to what the players of Hibernian and Motherwell were
up to on the Easter Road pitch.
There seemed little point in watching football when one of the people
who helped make it the beautiful game was engaged in the greatest
challenge of his life in the neurological unit of a Glasgow hospital.
In the quietness, memories of Cooper were replayed, and if there were
smiles on a few faces, they were not born of any disrespect. It was just
that Cooper in full flight was a joy to behold and perhaps it was
appropriate that the re-arranged premier division match should be
treated as a distant second to the memory of a player who belonged to
another era.
Although Cooper, who was 39 last month, was still turning out in the
first division for Clydebank, his first senior club, he was from
yesterday. He was a genuine Scottish winger and that made him a rarity.
When emotions are spilling over it is tempting to reach into the
realms of hyperbole, but it is almost impossible to exaggerate Cooper's
exploits on the wings for Rangers, Motherwell, and Scotland. He was in
possession of wondrous gifts which defied belief.
A few years ago a sports commentator asked Ruud Gullit, who was at the
height of his own remarkable powers and playing in Italy, if he had ever
been impressed by any Scottish footballers and, instead of offering up
the name of Kenny Dalglish or Graeme Souness, the Dutchman said simply:
''Davie Cooper.'' Gullit had seen him play for Rangers and was astounded
by his natural ability.
Uncomfortable in the heat of the spotlight Cooper was a bashful hero
who never enjoyed adulation, and throughout his career the feeling that
he had not made the most of his abilities persisted. It gnawed
constantly and one can only wonder what he might have achieved had he
been able to do more than than stand on his right leg.
Still, with one educated leg he gave us many moments to cherish and,
ironically, one of his most significant contributions will forever be
submerged in a profound sadness. His penalty against Wales in Cardiff in
1985 took Scotland into the Mexico World Cup finals, but while the fans
were celebrating the manager, Jock Stein, was dying of heart failure.
That goal was one of six Cooper scored in 22 appearances for Scotland,
a paltry total for someone so talented. Caps should have been spilling
from every drawer but errors of judgment by managers -- Ally MacLeod
admitted after the ill-fated event that he should have taken Cooper to
the World Cup finals in Argentina -- injury, which prevented him from
taking part in Italia '90, and his own often brooding reluctance to
perform denied him.
He played in Mexico in '86, but his best was restricted mainly to
domestic arenas and one of his finest moments was a goal scored against
Celtic in the Drybrough Cup final in 1979. He kept the ball up and
flicked it over several defenders with an arrogant nonchalance before
scoring a goal which is one of the first retrieved from the archives
whenever television presents programmes on football's greatest moments.
He took Dundee United apart in the Scottish Cup final replay of
1980-81 which Rangers won 4-1 and scored the winning goal against Celtic
in the 1986-87 league cup final which presented Souness with his first
trophy as Rangers' manager. The Hamilton-born winger made 377 league
appearances for Rangers and scored 49 times before moving to Motherwell
for #50,000 five years ago.
He won his fourth Scottish Cup winners' medal with the Fir Park side a
year later with the three other triumphs occurring in 1978, '79, and
'81. Cooper also owns three league championship badges (1978, '87, '89)
and seven League Cup winners' medals ('78, '79, '82, '84, '85, '87,
'88).
We can only hope he survives, but I fear Scottish football will never
see his equal. He was the last in a distinguished line of Scottish
wingers: Morton, Jackson, Delaney, Liddle, Smith, Ormond, Waddell,
Henderson, Johnstone, and Johnston. They are the stuff of legend.
Davie Cooper was the last of the greats. May he recover and enjoy the
memories with us.
</TEXT>
