<HEADLINE>Kingdom is back in the running</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255459</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COLIN Jackson's old Nemesis, double Olympic champion Roger Kingdom,
sounded a warning to his former arch rival yesterday with victory in the
110 metres hurdles at the Pan American Games in Mar del Plata.
Kingdom, who for years stood between Welshman Jackson and the sport's
highest honours, warned after his success in Argentina that he was ready
to challenge Jackson for his World crown in Gothenburg this summer.
Yet yesterday's win took more than three hours. That was how long it
took for a disqualification to be overturned and the appeals procedure
to restore Kingdom to his Pan-Am throne.
Kingdom, who first won the Pan American title in 1983, clocked 13.39,
one hundredth ahead of Cuban Emilio Valle. A judge ruled he had
deliberately knocked over the ninth hurdle, but a six-man jury of appeal
reinstated Kingdom.
The only athlete to have won titles at the Games 12 years apart, and a
long-time arthritis sufferer, Kingdom was motivated to attempt a
comeback after European promoters refused to find him a lane last year,
even though he was prepared to run for nothing.
Also behind Kingdom yesterday was Courtney Hawkins, one of the two
Americans to beat Britain's Tony Jarrett at the World Indoor
championships in Barcelona earlier this month.
''This is the first stage of a comeback,'' said the 32-year-old
Kingdom. ''If I can make the World championships . . . you know I am not
going over there without trying to win. That's the only title I do not
have on my shelf.''
</TEXT>
