<HEADLINE>Mark back in charge</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979255460</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE German mark reasserted its authority on the foreign exchanges and
left the pound and dollar floundering.
Sterling about lost 1[1/4] pfennigs to DM2.2295 but it rose almost a
fifth-of-a-cent against the weak dollar to $1.5863. This enabled
sterling's trade-weighted index managed to rise to 85.1, a gain of 0.3
on its overnight level.
However, City dealers suggest that underlying political worries and
the fragility of the UK economy need to be cured before sterling regains
confidence for any sustained length of time.
Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke said sterling's weakness
had nothing to do with economic fundamentals and said the recovery was
healthy. UK inflation data published today is expected to show an annual
inflation rate of 3.4%, up 0.1 on the previous month.
Mr Clarke refused to rule out intervention to prop up currencies. He
said there was a case for it when it went with the grain and reflected
economic reality. ''I do not rule it out in all circumstances,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
