<HEADLINE>Burns moves for McCann</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255462</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DUNDEE turned down a renewed bid from Luton Town manager David Pleat
yesterday for their Under-21 Scotland player Neil McCann -- and with the
English transfer deadline set for today a move south by the winger does
not look likely now.
But, as interest mounts, Celtic are back in the hunt. I understand
that Dens Park manager Jim Duffy and Celtic's Tommy Burns had transfer
talks about McCann yesterday.
The 21-year-old was high on Burns' shopping list when he arived at
Parkhead in the summer. The emergence of Brian McLaughlin -- coupled
with the price placed on McCann by Dundee -- saw Burns' interest wane.
Now, though, I understand that the Tayside club, which would welcome a
boost to their bank account, have come well below the #750,000 they were
looking for earlier in the season.
Luton's offer was in the form of a package -- a cash sum up front,
with additions made when McCann played a certain number of games in
England or won a full Scotland cap. There was also a clause allowing
Dundee further money if the player was transferred by the English side.
A similar deal has been suggested to Celtic and that is being
considered. I believe, though, that a straightforward fee of #500,000
would land the player. The transfer deadline in Scotland is one week
later than it is south of the Border.
McCann joined Dundee from Port Glasgow Boys' Club just short of three
years ago. Until now Duffy has insisted the player is not for sale, but
with the Tayside team struggling for money he is the one asset who could
stabilise their finances as they aim for a place in the premier division
and the massive financial boost that would provide.
</TEXT>
