<DOCNO>GH950323-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>'Well are left in the dark by Hibs</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255463</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Hibernian 2, Motherwell 0
WITH the stadium announcer offering regular bulletins on the condition
of former Motherwell player Davie Cooper, the match was never likely to
grab and hold the full attention of the Easter Road crowd of 5402, which
was not at all an embarrassing number given the ridiculous 3.30pm
kick-off time.
The clubs had to perform at such a strange midweek time because
reconstruction work has cut off supply to the floodlights but,
defensively, Motherwell were always in the dark.
Hibernian, or to be more accurate, Keith Wright, took full advantage
of the Fir Park side's dithering and scored both goals.
The striker wasted little time in declaring his intentions by putting
his side in front after only nine minutes and his second arrived nine
minutes after the interval.
Motherwell then tried to do something positive about their plight, but
found Hibs cruising comfortably back into third place in the premier
division.
Alex Miller's side are now two points behind second-placed Motherwell,
who were beaten in a league match for the first time since January when
they lost 6-1 to Dundee United.
''I think the goals will do a lot for Keith's confidence,'' said
Miller, who, like many people at the game, was more anxious of further
news of Cooper.
''Someone so young, too,'' he said more to himself than anyone else.
''Football pales into insignificance at times like this.''
Motherwell's assistant manager Andy Watson had to take the post-match
press conference because manager Alex McLeish, who played many times at
international level with Cooper, was too upset to talk.
The game plan for Motherwell was to keep things tight at the back and
play the ball forward out of defence, but the strategy had to be
reconsidered when Wright was perfectly placed to flick Kevin Harper's
delivery into the net using his left heel. The second goal, scored after
Harper and Darren Jackson had combined to set up Wright with an easy
tap-in, was confirmation of the Edinburgh side's superiority.
Hibs' new signing, Andy Millen, made his debut playing in midfield but
was taken off near the end when it was clear fatigue was setting in.
Mark McGraw was allowed to stretch his legs and Miller later said: ''I
thought Andy had a decent debut especially since he hadn't played in a
premier division match for something like nine months.''
Millen, who arrived at Easter Road after Hibs had agreed to pay
Kilmarnock a sum of money as well hand over Billy Findlay -- it is
understood the package was worth #300,000 -- had been out of favour at
Rugby Park since he had made it clear he wanted to leave around the time
Celtic were showing an interest. He has been given his move and looked
determined to make up for lost time.
Motherwell hope to complete the signing of Mitchel van der Gaag from
PSV Eindhoven this morning and he will make his debut against Celtic
next week. ''There is just some paperwork to be completed,'' said
Watson, who must hope the Dutchman can shore up the defence which was
extremely shaky.
Motherwell could not possibly hope to secure a European place let
alone do anything on foreign fields with so many defenders looking as
though they had little idea of their functions.
Even the normally reliable Brian Martin was beaten regularly and, had
Hibs' finishing been more accurate, the Edinburgh side would have won by
a wider margin.
Two players, Hibs' Joe Tortolano and Stephen McMillan, of Motherwell,
were booked, but in the main the game was a low-key affair. The thoughts
of too many people, on and off the pitch, may have been elsewhere.
HIBERNIAN -- Leighton, Miller, Millen, McGinlay, Tweed, Hunter,
Harper, Tortolano, Wright, Jackson, O'Neill. Substitutes -- Weir,
McGraw, Reid.
MOTHERWELL -- Woods, May, McMillan, Krivokapic, Martin, Philliben,
Lambert, Dolan, Burns, Arnott, Davies. Substitutes -- Coyne, Shannon,
Howie.
Referee -- J O'Hare (Glenboig).
</TEXT>
