<HEADLINE>Scots' Noble victory at Flanders</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255464</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ian McConnell reports on the Edinburgh-based merchant bank which is
showing no lack of bottle at Flanders, and making its presence felt in
the City.
EDINBURGH merchant bank Noble &amp; Company is keeping Scotland's historic
links with Flanders alive with major exports of corporate finance
expertise.
Although perhaps still saddled at home with the image of a financial
player almost exclusively involved in start-up deals, Noble has a much
higher profile south of the Border, on the Continent, and in the US.
In spite of doing a relatively small part of its business on its home
patch, however, Noble was crucial to the development of Waverley Mining
Finance, part of the Mining (Scotland) consortium which recently took
over the Scottish coalfields.
It is also a major player in the revitalisation of the ancient Lloyds
of London insurance market, offering people the chance to invest without
taking the horrendous risks which proved the undoing of the Names.
The unique Scottish touch which Noble has used in painstakingly
putting the commercial cogs in place for a #60m plastics factory in
Flanders has greatly impressed the business community there. So much so
that the Edinburgh merchant bank may be called upon by the government,
one of three federal ones in Belgium, to advise on privatisation issues.
PET, the much-in-demand preferred plastic for soft drinks bottles,
will be produced in the factory, which was the brainchild of two former
BP employees from the London area.
Initially somewhat bamboozled by the concept, which involves a
witches' brew of chemicals, Noble was impressed when it examined the
supply and demand conditions.
By a stroke of good fortune, Flanders, an ideal location for the
plant, was somewhere Noble could enlist the assistance of
well-established contacts.
For more than a year, Noble has been agonising over where exactly to
site the factory, the choice of several technologies.
What 51-year-old chief executive Tim Noble describes as an
''incredibly complex'' process has also involved attracting two trade
buyers as customers and investors, to reduce risk, and lining up finance
from banks and other investors.
However, the main pieces of the jigsaw are now in place and the
commercial, rather than purely financial, approach of Noble has gone
down well with the Flemish.
The Edinburgh merchant bank has received referrals from other
companies in Flanders and another Flemish firm. Word of mouth has also
put Noble in the frame for work in one or two upcoming privatisations.
Scotland's bonds with Flanders, famous for its poppies, are forged in
the blood of the Scottish soldiers who died in during the trench warfare
of the First World War. However, Mr Noble, a vehement nationalist with a
small ''n'', believes there is still a strong affinity between the
communities.
He said: ''The people there like the concept of Flanders and Scotland.
There have been a lot of historic links and there is also a feeling that
we have two communities that are the same size. Scotland has this
expertise in finance that Flanders doesn't have and Flanders has this
thriving industrial sector.''
In an industry in which the big London players tend to attract all the
media attention -- whether it be yet another wave of takeover rumours
surrounding SG Warburg or the stranger-than-fiction goings-on at Barings
-- Mr Noble delights in being the Scottish underdog.
He admits to having gleaned not a small amount of satisfaction when
his City peers were made to sit up and take notice at a recent dinner in
London.
Mr Noble explained: ''I mentioned my name to a group of people I had
never met before and those from London looked blank. However, the guy
who came from Belgium said, 'Oh, you must be from Noble &amp; Company. I
have heard a lot about them.' I felt very pleased about that.''
Those behind Noble have always fought hard for Scotland. Sir Iain
Noble, who founded the merchant bank with Tim and John Noble in 1980,
was at the forefront of the campaign to prevent The Royal Bank of
Scotland being swallowed up by Standard Chartered in the early-eighties.
Indeed, the merchant bank, which initially focused on the oil sector,
had its roots in the family's wish to redress the ''tragic'' lack of
Scottish companies reaping the benefits of the North Sea oil boom.
Noble has also been a key player in the re-birth of Scotland's coal
industry.
The merchant bank helped William McLucas fund Waverley Mining Finance,
which was floated on the stock market back in 1988 and more recently
took a 22% stake in Mining (Scotland).
As part of the consortium selected by the Government late last year as
the preferred bidder for the Scottish coalfields, Waverley had to put up
#6.3m.
With a very tight timetable having been set by the Government for the
sale of Scottish Coal by the end of the year, a #15m placing of shares,
underwritten by Noble and London stockbroker Williams de Broe, had to be
arranged swiftly.
Director Ben Thomson, 31, believes Noble has sponsored more vehicles
for Lloyds of London insurance market investors than any other merchant
bank.
It has set up four corporate capital vehicles, including Wellington
Underwriting and Premium Underwriting, which allow investors to
participate in a particular, or a range of, syndicates on a limited
liability basis.
After the devastation suffered by some Names, whose losses were as
deep as Pandora's Box, the vehicles set up by Noble allow investors to
switch from unlimited to limited liability.
Mr Thomson said: ''What we have been trying to do is bring in new
investors to help capitalise Lloyds for the future and get the format of
it right.
''Considering virtually all of the major banks have had a go, it is
certainly a surprise that a Scottish institution should be one of the
leading corporate finance houses of Lloyds of London.''
Another facet of the company is Noble Securities, which undertakes
portfolio management for individuals, charities and trusts.
Returning to corporate finance, Noble &amp; Company was, 18 months ago,
behind the first flotation of a general insurance company since the war.
Independent Insurance, formerly the UK subsidiary of US insurance
giant Allstate, was the subject of a management buy-in brokered by Noble
at the end of 1986.
Back then, Noble raised #15m, with Independent ultimately floated with
a market capitalisation of about #100m.
' It is certainly a surprise that a Scottish institution should be one
of the leading corporate finance houses of Lloyds of London '
Noble and Co. director, Ben Thomson
</TEXT>
