<HEADLINE>Teamwork proves the healthy route to staff empowerment</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS,TRAILBLAZERS,</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255465</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NOT allowing staff to sit down during meetings may not sound like a
recipe for success, but this week's Trailblazer demonstrates how
successful this, as part of ''people empowerment'', can be.
In an effort to turn the levels of business around, health insurance
company Cigna took the dramatic step of ripping out its management
structure to create multi-disciplinary teams based around customers'
needs rather than functions.
Operations director Ian Ferguson was instrumental in the development
and implementation of this re-engineering process.
''Change didn't take place overnight. A lot of work was done trying
first to convince management of the benefits of this change, and then
the staff themselves had to be committed to make it work.''
In a move that took almost three years to complete, Cigna relocated
its headquarters to Greenock, introduced the team structure and has
succeeded in going from a loss situation to a #1m profit.
The company specialises in providing corporate employee benefits,
including health care, life insurance, private dental insurance, and
individual health policies.
Multi-disciplinary teams offer a range of services built for each
customer ensuring efficient and accessible delivery of health care to
their employees. A team of experienced nurses are on call to listen and
answer queries, discuss treatments, and offer guidance to patients and
their families.
Customers such as Motorola Ltd, Stakis, and housebuilder Cala plc have
adopted this approach. However, as Ian Ferguson explains, the teams did
not always work so well. ''To begin with a pilot team was set up,
pulling together a cross-section of staff from the original departments.
''Basically we were asking them to live in one another's pockets and
learn to work together. Departments were brought into contact with one
another, which was the first step in opening up the system.''
The eight-strong team had to learn team dynamics -- both in theory and
practice. For example, how to gain consensus decisions and how to
resolve conflict.
The first team, Camp (Claims and Administration Medical Pilot),
survived the testing period and today there are eight teams handling
Cigna's business.
Clients are assigned to teams which are given the task of dealing with
all aspects of the client's business. The client company and all
employees covered by the plan are given a direct telephone number and a
named individual who deals with their case.
This effectively empowers staff, giving them ''ownership'' of clients
and their workload. It also provides every customer with access to
someone who understands the details and background of an inquiry and who
can then make informed, rapid, and reliable decisions -- a one-stop
shop.
Grainne Bain, one of the first staff to join Cigna at Greenock,
believes strongly in the team structure. ''There are no supervisors,
only team members and team facilitators who are mutually supportive and
adaptive to the needs of every customer.'' Each day team members meet to
set work targets and measure themselves against those targets. Every
member of the team will tell their colleagues what targets they are
setting themselves, for example how many claims they expect to process
that day. The next day they will report back what they actually
achieved.
Marie McGhee, team facilitator of Camp, says everyone in the team
knows what each other is doing. ''It's not a case of judging each other
but being aware of how the team is doing as a whole.
''For example, if someone is struggling one day because the phone has
been ringing non-stop, then some of their workload can be shared.''
All the team facilitators meet on a daily basis (this is where they
have chosen to stand in order to keep meetings short and efficient) to
hear how the company is performing and where the teams have contributed.
As a result of Cigna's restructuring, productivity has increased more
than 30%, running costs have fallen and staff retention is high -- about
95%, but it has brought new concerns on career development.
The award and
how to enter
* The scheme is a joint initiative of The Herald and Ernst &amp; Young
business and financial advisers, to recognise organisations which can
demonstrate innovation and ingenuity in their company operations and
procedures. Entries should be based on one, or a combination, of:
Innovation/ingenuity, Business performance, Product/service quality,
Management calibre, Marketing flair, Contribution to
local/Scottisheconomy.
Rewards: The monthly winner will be presented with an award
certificate and offered one half day's consultancy by Ernst &amp; Young's
business and financial advisers.
The overall TrailBlazer of the Year will be able to send a company
representative on an agreed specialist management training course at the
renowned Harvard Business School in Boston.
How to enter: Submit your entry on one A4 page to:
The Organiser, Ernst &amp; Young TrailBlazers Award scheme, 9 Lynedoch
Crescent, Glasgow, G3 6EQ.
(Tel: 041-333 0557).
* This month's closing date is Wednesday, April 5.
</TEXT>
