<HEADLINE>Preparing for more than small change</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN ROY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SOAPBOX,SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255466</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LAST MONTH'S publication of the final draft Statement of Recommended
Practice (Accounting by charities) has marked the beginning of the end
of what has been a nail-biting period of uncertainty for Scottish
charities.
The charities have been waiting patiently for details of new
accounting recommendations that many feared would be far-reaching and
could potentially have a significant impact on the way they operate.
Nothing could be closer to the truth!
That the new regulations are necessary and overdue is probably not in
doubt, particularly from the point of view of ensuring that charity
trustees meet their duties to the public in terms of stewardship and
financial accountability.
In addition, there is undoubtedly merit in bringing forward specific
recommendations concerning the form and content of charities' annual
report and accounts to ensure that readers of these documents can
understand the precise purpose of a charity's activities, its financial
transactions and its financial position.
However, from a practical point of view, for many charities these
recommendations may be a double-edged sword, the impact of which could
inflict serious wounds, especially on those whose procedures and
accounting and administrative systems are in need of modernisation.
In England and Wales, the Charity Commission is the regulatory body
for charities, all of whom operate under specific charity legislation.
In Scotland, though, there is no comparable Charities Act and it is the
Secretary of State who has responsibility for setting out the criteria
for charities' reporting, accounting and auditing.
With the plethora of regulation currently facing charities and
particularly in light of the changes in the financial reporting scene,
my message to Scottish charities is that they should start planning for
these changes now.
In one sense, these recommendations are nothing more than standards of
good practice of the kind that should already be in place in all
organisations, including charities. Charities without the necessary
standards and practices may find it difficult to cope with the new
recommendations, and this could inhibit their on-going development.
Without going into too much detail about the reporting criteria to be
used in, for example, the production of annual report and accounts,
suffice it to say that in the future accounts will become more
standardised under a fairly prescriptive approach to the reporting of
transactions.
This could be a culture shock for many charities. Some will
undoubtedly have to get rid of archaic practices and many more may have
to adopt a more business-like approach to what they do. I am not
advocating that charities should be profitable, but they will have to
manage their resources more effectively.
There is one further specific downside. Volunteers who advise and take
decisions on behalf of charities can be held personally liable if things
go wrong and it is a real concern that many volunteers may not be aware
of these responsibilities.
It is acknowledged that in drafting the revised regulations (known as
SORP 2), care has been taken to provide some specific Scottish input and
some concessions have been granted. That said, the vast majority of the
features of charity accounting introduced by SORP 2 are intended to
apply to all charities, including Scottish charities, regardless of
size, constitution or complexity.
Accordingly, whilst SORP 2 may be ''recommended practice'' and
therefore in theory not mandatory, charities are given clear guidance
that they will be expected to follow its recommendations.
The final version of SORP 2 is likely to be issued during the summer,
as soon as the English and Welsh regulations are finalised, and it is
estimated that full implemetation will be required later this year.
If the burden of additional regulation and responsibility will put
more pressure on charities, as the impact of increasing regulation
becomes more clear to volunteers, it will also put more pressure on
those people who have traditionally given voluntary service to charities
as their contribution to the community.
This added responsibility could turn people away from becoming
involved in charity work in the future.
Charities must therefore look at ways of supporting these people by
having internal procedures and policies in place; this will not only
protect the individuals but will also help protect the charity itself.
Against all of these problems, I am encouraged to see the formation of
joint ventures between the professional and charity sectors which are
aimed at addressing some of the issues.
The Institute of Chartered Accountants of Scotland and the Scottish
Council for Voluntary Organisations, supported by Brodies the
solicitors, have come together to set up the Scottish Charities Annual
Reports Awards, the objective of which is to improve the quality of
financial information produced by Scottish charities in their annual
reports.
In addition, a group known as the Scottish Charity Finance Directors
Group, has recently been formed. This will act as a forum through which
those involved in issues concerning Scottish charities can meet and
discuss problems.
These two developments are undoubtedly a step in the right direction.
It is a time of uncertainty and change for charities and the hope must
be that in tackling these issues, charities can rise to the challenges
they face and create a platform on which they can build for the future.
* Ian Roy, a partner with chartered accountants, Primrose McCabe &amp;
Co., and the Honorary Treasurer of the Guide Association in Scotland,
was talking to Yvonne Wightman.
</TEXT>
