<HEADLINE>Sir Colin focuses on sustainability</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAN BUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255468</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN increasingly hungry world in which stocks of food are steadily
declining needs both the technical skills of progressive farmers and the
expertise of agricultural science, according to one of the doyens of
farming research.
Delivering the annual Sir John Hammond Memorial Lecture in Scarborough
yesterday on the concluding day of the British Society of Animal
Science's winter meeting, Professor Sir Colin Spedding distanced himself
from many current ideas in a thought provoking speech entitled
Sustainability in Animal Production.
Sir Colin first pointed out that the very term sustainability means
different things to different people. ''What worries me is that people
are equating sustainable with good, and it isn't always.''
Neither did he agree that this type of farming was the same as
low-input systems. ''There is no particular value in leaving a resource
totally unused as some would wish with, say, chemicals. There are
problems in the way resources are used and certainly we do not want to
do anything which gives rise to pollution.''
However, it was when he approached the economics of low-input farming
that his message became crystal clear. ''Economic sustainability means
that you want to continue to make a profit -- so why not say so loud and
clear? But how do you design a system for the future unless we know what
the costs and prices will be? And that's one thing we know nothing
about.''
Advising the average British farmer how to plan for the future, Sir
Colin said: ''Each individual farmer has to decide for himself to what
extent sustainability is a relevant concept for him. Clearly he has to
look at the rate at which his resources are used, but that doesn't mean
he cannot use them. It does not follow that using resources at a low
rate will allow you to survive economically.''
Seizing on the international implications of less intensive farming,
he continued: ''The question that everyone wants to know is: could you
feed the world under such regimes? Even then the trouble with that
stragegy is that we are not feeding the world just now. What's more,
feeding the world has got nothing to do with producing food. People are
hungry because they are poor, that's the only reason. No-one who has
money goes hungry. The rich do not starve except after earthquakes or
something like that.
''The question of hunger is one of poverty -- if they had the money
the food would be provided for them.''
Continuing with his theme and developing it towards the ultimate
question of whether the starving millions even with enough money in
their pockets could be fed by the world's farmers adopting low-input
systems, he concluded pensively: ''The judgment at the moment is that in
the long term it would be difficult -- if everyone was to be
satisfactorily fed by using low-input methods.''
Sir Colin received wide acclaim for his speech, and many delegates
later made the point that it was time for the agricultural industry in
the broadest sense to go on the offensive, adding that the individuals
who criticise farmers and intensive methods are all too often the same
ones who plead for more aid for the Third World.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000041</DOCNO>
