<HEADLINE>A successful film industry, if we all pull together</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HARRY CONROY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255469</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Movie makers are coming to Scotland in increasing numbers, reports
Harry Conroy, thanks to local authority initiatives
JOHN DOWNIE is adamant. Despite all the hype surrounding the recent
production of several films in this country, Scotland does not have a
film industry. But the chairman of Scottish Screen Locations is equally
adamant that we could have one if everyone were to co-operate.
The recent success of Shallow Grave, the film backed by the Glasgow
Film Fund, is an indicator of what is possible even with a limited
amount of resources.
A number of initiatives are currently being undertaken to attract film
makers to Scotland. Scottish Screen Locations is talking to more than 30
feature film companies about using the country as a location, and film
makers from Italy, Japan, the US, and Germany are considering coming
here.
Lee Leckie, commissioner for Scottish Screen Locations, says: ''We are
very likely to get four of these productions, with three starting this
year. A couple of them are large productions but it can take three or
four years of talking before an agreement is reached.''
The economic rewards, not only in terms of employment for those in the
film industry but also for the localities where the filming actually
takes place, are high. Since 1991 an estimated #22m has been spent by
film production companies in Scotland in such basic services as local
shops, hotels, restaurants, and taxis. In the past two years six major
films have come here, including Brave Heart, Rob Roy, Mary Reilly, and
Glace Bay.
The latter is a reminder that we can attract films other than those
with a Scottish story. Glace Bay centres round a Canadian mining
disaster, and the facilities at the Scottish Mining Museum were used as
the setting for the film.
Film producers are attracted to Scotland for a number of reasons,
including our topography and the quality of light. We can also offer
them apparently remote locations within easy travelling distance of
urban towns where they can film without being troubled by aircraft
passing overhead.
Scotland is in competition with Ireland for film productions. Says
John Downie: ''Ireland can offer tax concessions, and throws all sorts
of goodies at the production companies. There is certainly not an even
playing field.''
Local authorities, however, have played an important part in boosting
Scotland's attraction for film companies.
John Downie is himself an executive of Strathclyde Business
Development, the economic arm of the region, which put #20,000 a year
into Scottish Screen Locations as well as the Glasgow Film Fund.
''Local authorities provide many of the facilities that a film company
needs, and the Scottish local authorities are very co-operative,'' he
explains. His own interest in the film industry extends beyond the
economic arena -- his wife Ann stars in Take the High Road.
The increasing interest in expanding the film industry in Scotland
dates back to 1988, when the Scottish Development Agency put together a
report suggesting that there was an economic case for attracting the
industry to Scotland.
In 1990, with the help of Glasgow District Council, Lothian Regional
Council, and Strathclyde Business Development, Scottish Screen Locations
was launched to market Scotland worldwide as a film location. This
initiative received a boost in 1990, when Glasgow was Europe's City of
Culture and hosted the European Film Awards.
Film making has been stimulated by the increasing number of television
channels and the growth of independent television production companies
as stations were encouraged to farm out 25% of their production to
independent producers.
John Downie points simply to the growing thickness of the ''Film
Bang'', the directory of the Scottish fledgling film industry, as an
indication of the expansion that has been taking place. ''The directory
is now three times the size it was four or five years ago,'' he says.
The establishment of the Glasgow Film Fund with money from the Glasgow
Development Agency, Glasgow City Council, and Strathclyde region as well
as the European Regional Development Fund, marked another step forward
for the industry, as has the commercial success of Shallow Grave, the
film the fund invested in along with Channel 4.
Shallow Grave was an immediate financial success, breaking box office
records at four London cinemas as well as at the Cameo in Edinburgh. It
drew #100,512 at eight London screens in one weekend before going on
general release throughout the UK.
The Glasgow Film Fund has now invested #150,000 in the #1m The Near
Room, which is being filmed in Glasgow. Other current productions
include the #1.5m Train Spotting, which is likely to be filmed in
Edinburgh, and the bigger budget #2m Easterhouse, which is likely to
provide work for a crew of 50 and 66 actors.
Early indications are that The Near Room, which involves 12 weeks of
shooting in the Townhead area of Glasgow, will be another commercial
success. A deal has already been struck with film distributor Smart Egg,
which has offices in the US and Australia as well as the UK.
Alan Shiach, chairman of the Scottish Film Production Fund, which
provides money to develop film scripts and ideas, is on record as
saying: ''The success of Shallow Grave and The Near Room proves that
here in Scotland we are no longer making films just for our television
consumption but films of real international standing.''
Lee Leckie is also confident about the future. ''All the strands are
starting to come together,'' she says.
One of the final strands, John Downie believes, is a ''bigger,
Scotland-wide film fund''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
