<HEADLINE>Fledgling airline to link Derry with mainland UK Stepping out into the slipstream</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN GULLAND</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255470</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
High-flying business ambitions will be catered for from Monday when a
new airline will encourage trade to and from Northern Ireland's second
city, as Alan Gulland reports
SCOTLAND's newest airline is about to bring Derry's businessmen in
from the cold.
From Monday, they will get their first ever daily air link --
specifically geared to meet the needs of the business traveller -- from
Londonderry to mainland UK.
The fledgling airline, Macair, will launch same-day return routes
between Ulster's second largest city and London Stanstead, Edinburgh,
and Birmingham.
It will come as a welcome boost to Northern Ireland's bid to put ''The
Troubles'' behind them and attract much needed new commercial and
industrial investment to the area -- and for Derry Airport which
recently underwent a #12m redevelopment.
Take-off day will also mean a dream come true for Edinburgh based
Macair's young pioneering managing director Captain John Maxton.
It was on a day trip to Derry three years ago that the 37-year-old
former Loganair pilot got the idea for his new airline.
Local businessmen told him of their frustration at having to drive up
to two-and-a-half hours to Belfast Airport to get the flights they
wanted to London and elsewhere in Britain.
''Launching my own airline was something I had often dreamed of.
''I was given a copy of a market research report which showed there
were some very compelling reasons why north-west Ireland should have
direct air links with England and Scotland.
''The more I thought of it , the more attractive it became. It rapidly
became clear that it was not just pie in the sky.
''I drew up a business plan which showed that it had a very good
chance of success.''
From then on it was all systems go. He approached a number of
investment sources -- including banks, travel agents, private investors
and Government funding agencies to raise the #500,000 capital required
for the first year's operations.
He has also put some of his own money into the business and airline
staff, who will total 26. They too are being invited to take a stake in
the enterprise.
''I am fully aware that others before me have tried setting up their
own airlines and have failed after only a short while.
''But they made the mistake of trying to take on the big boys and go
for a share of existing business.
''What makes us different and gives us the confidence that we will
succeed is that we are opening up new territory. We will not be
competing with anyone on the routes we have chosen. In fact we are being
actively encouraged to go for it.''
They are getting practical support from Air UK, who will carry out
Macair's passenger handling services at Edinburgh and Stanstead.
John said: ''They also want to use us as a feeder service for their
network of European routes.''
Initially, Macair are leasing two 18-seat Prestwick-built Jetstream 31
Aircraft for their routes, which will also include daily flights between
Donegal, Edinburgh, and Birmingham.
Over the past few weeks John has had the job of sifting through scores
of applications for the 12 pilot and seven stewardess jobs which are
being created.
''I have 12 years of flying experience but over the last 18 months or
so I have had to turn my hand to all sorts of administrative jobs,'' he
said.
''Although there will be a team of pilots, I have no intention of
being completely deskbound. I will continue flying -- probably up to two
days a week,'' added the father of three, who has an honours degree in
German and a post graduate diploma in European marketing.
But it won't be all business traffic for the new airline.
''We will also be doing charter work and we will be launching a
special service for golfers to give them a day out playing some of
north-west Ireland's top courses.''
The new air link is being welcomed by Derry's businessmen.
Michael Black, president of Derry Chamber of Commerce, said: ''We are
absolutely delighted that we are at long last getting direct links with
London, Edinburgh, and Birmingham. This has been the Chamber's top
priority for at least the last four years.
''I certainly hope it does well because it is a vital piece of
infrastructure in attracting inward investment to north-west Ireland.''
Derry Airport manager Shamus Devine added: ''The business community
here has been crying out for the direct services. At the moment business
people in this area have to rise at 4am to travel two hours to catch the
first services out of Belfast.
''The new services from Derry are a crucial building block in the
development of our local economy.They will not only benefit the business
community but will also encourage tourism.''
</TEXT>
