<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hidden cost of lameness</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JEANNE GAVIN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>22</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255471</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LAMENESS in the dairy herd may be costing many farmers much more than
they think, according to a leading vet.
By the time conditions such as foul foot or dermatitis were visible
the damage had been going on for anything up to six weeks Gloucester vet
Roger Blowey told a meeting of dairy farmers in Stonehaven yesterday.
The consequent effects on profitability should not be under-estimated.
''Around a quarter of cows in the national herd are treated annually
for lameness -- and independent investigation suggests that the cost per
case can be as high as #390 for a single ulcer,'' he said. ''The figure
is so high because of the influence of lameness on fertility.''
As well as economic loss, he added, there was a hassle factor of
treatment and the effect on cow welfare. More attention should be paid
to prevention.
Suggesting that a lot of lameness was associated with problems at
calving, Mr Blowey explained that vets knew from the days of horned
animals that calving was a stress on horn formation. The foot also gave
a historical picture but the effects were a bit harder to see.
''What we now suspect is that calving is a much more stressful
condition than we've hitherto given credit to,'' he said. ''As well as
that disruption we impose at the same time additional stresses on the
cow -- such as a sudden change in environment and diet. I believe we
tend to under-estimate these factors.''
Many causes of lameness were related to accumulation of fluid on the
udder and in feet, with heifers particularly at risk in a strange
environment which might mean them having to get used to the change from
the soft surface of grass to concrete cubicles. Common calving-time
diseases like mastitis also caused poor horn growth.
''At calving an animal spends longer standing up so she must have good
conditions in which to lie down in order to tempt her to do so,'' said
Mr Blowey.
He also urged farmers to take care when changing the feeding regime
and suggested that the use of high-quality precision chop silage --
which went through the cow very quickly -- was not ideal feed for dairy
cows. It was important to know what kind of silage was being fed -- some
could lead to acidosis, while more fibrous feed needed high
concentrates. Getting it wrong could ''blast the feet off dairy cows,''
he said.
The design of cublicles was also important. They had to be big enough
and comfortable enough for the animals to lie down and had to have
enough room for it to lunge forward when getting up or down.
''If we can make cows more comfortable and if we can make them lie
down at time of calving, then we will be going some way forward to
reducing the costs of some of the most common problems,'' he said.
Yesterday's meeting was organised by animal feed compounder BOCM
Pauls. It will hold a further meeting today for dairy farmers in the
Nairn area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Card work in spades</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LOUISE WELSH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255472</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LINZI GORMAN does not mince her words when asked why she and her
husband William have been so successful in business: ''Sheer, bloody
hard work . . . and you can quote me on that!''
The husband and wife team is the driving force behind one of
Scotland's fastest growing companies, Supercard Retail Ltd, a greetings
card and gifts store chain with outlets throughout Scotland -- from
Hawick to Dundee.
Supercard was formed in 1991 to be run in harness with their existing
card wholesale operation, Gorman Graphics, trading from premises at
Hillington Industrial Estate near Paisley.
The Gorman's story is impressive by any standards: from 1993 to
January 1995 the combined companies turnover increased by an incredible
385% to #2.1m and the number of employees rose from 7 to 106.
Linzi says franchising Supercard in July 1994 was an obvious
development and one which has proved extremely successful: ''At the
moment six of our stores are run by franchisees and this is an area we
are developing. I would estimate that by the end of 1996 we'll have
something like 30 Supercard stores on line throughout Scotland, of which
roughly half will be franchised.''
The greetings card industry is highly competitive with several
well-known chains competing for a share of the market. However the
Gormans believe Supercard is well placed to maintain its strong foothold
through a keen ability to evaluate customer buying trends.
''Willie's been in this business for nearly 16 years and I've been
working with him for 14 of them, so between us we have a nose for what
type of cards people want to buy,'' Linzi adds.
''Approximately 70% of all cards bought are purchased by women, so we
place huge importance in stocking our shops with the cards which will
appeal to female buyers. However, we are noticing that the teenage
market is increasing at a furious pace, with more and more youngsters
buying cards for a whole variety of occasions.''
The Gorman's entrepreneurial skills are well known within the
Renfrewshire Enterprise headquarters in Pailsey.
Chief Executive Tony Cassidy comments: ''The two companies developed
by Linzi and William Gorman have created jobs not only in Renfrewshire
but throughout Scotland as well. They recognise the importance of
employing a skilled workforce and have sought our support to help with a
number of business development and training programmes. We are proud of
the progress they have made in a relatively short space of time and wish
them continued success.''
The company have entered for Renfrewshire Enterprise's first Business
Awards scheme, entries for which have to be received by April 7.
As to the future -- Linzi Gorman answers in her usual down to earth
fashion: ''We plan to open more stores in every Scottish town that would
benefit from a Supercard . . . and more bloody hard work, no doubt.''
</TEXT>
