<DOCNO>GH950323-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Growing scourge of the office</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LINSAY HARROW</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979255473</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE traditional response to the sexual harassment issue is to
trivialise it, to see it as the province of a small number of over-sexed
middle-aged lechers who chase their young and pretty secretaries around
the office. In fact, sexual harassment is about power, not testosterone
and there is evidence that, in Scotland, there is a dramatic increase in
complaints and a growing recognition that sexual harassment is a
business issue which has to be addressed through better procedures and
training.
Research carried out by the Industrial Society in 1994 indicated that
50% of all working women in the UK had been sexually harassed at some
time in their careers. Perhaps more surprisingly, five per cent of cases
are brought by men. Closer to home, the Equal Opportunities Commission
in Scotland reported a 44% increase in sexual harassment cases in 1994
over the previous year. The commission believes that sexual harassment
may exist in every workplace and asserts that less than one per cent of
cases are based on false accusations.
Psychologist Dr Gillian Metze, who works with victims of sexual
harassment, observes that they become tense, anxious and frightened,
their self-confidence and self-esteem plummets and many experience
nightmares and a dramatic loss of interest in eating and socialising.
In common with much else in modern society, sexual harassment came to
the fore in the United States in the mid-Seventies, with a landmark case
in 1980 ruling that harassment on the grounds of sex was a violation of
the US anti-discrimination laws.
Scotland was the first country in Europe to implement sexual
discrimination legislation, with the 1985 case of Strathclyde v Porcelli
setting the standard -- sexual discrimination had not been a crime prior
to this case.
In 1993, the European Court of Human Rights ruled that the #11,000
ceiling imposed by British courts on awards in sexual harassment cases
was unlawful. The Law Society of England and Wales forecasts that
settlements of between #20,000 and #30,000 will be the norm, with some
lawyers expecting awards of #100,000 and more.
Clearly, the financial implications for a company accused of sexual
harassment are serious enough, but added to these are the effects such
cases have on morale, performance and staff turnover.
''We live in a society biased towards men,'' says Richard Thomson of
TW Associates, an organisation and management development consultancy
involved in this area, ''and many men are unaware that their language
and behaviour is contributing to a discriminatory environment. A sexual
discrimination policy in the staff handbook is not enough. Ingrained
attitudes need to be changed through active training and education. We
need to understand why there is a need to change, not rely on
legislation which sets out procedures and imposes penalties.''
</TEXT>
