<DOCNO>GH950323-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pair are cold comfort</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NIGEL DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255474</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE are just two Scots in the Great Britain world championship side
which will compete in Bratislava for the Pool B event from April 12 to
21.
Only six Scots made the top 50 for last week's training session at
Milton Keynes, with Fife Flyers' forward and captain Iain Robertson, a
former ''young player of the year,'' and his goalminder team-mate Ricky
Grubb having been given the nod.
And the lack of Scottish presence is worrying, particularly as four
British League teams are based north of the Border, Premier Division
Racers and Flyers, plus two Division 1 sides, promotion prospects,
Paisley Pirates, and relegated Dumfries Vikings.
Recently players from Scottish sides have featured prominently in the
national squad.
Meanwhile, this weekend's final series of regular games will decide
who plays who in the British championship play-offs, and the
promotion/relegation play-offs.
The British championship qualifying sections, featuring the top eight
sides in the Premier Division, are:
Group A -- Teams finishing first, third, sixth and eighth. Group B --
Teams finishing second, fourth, fifth, and seventh. The top two move to
the championship semi-final at Wembley on April 15.
The promotion/relegation play-offs, including the bottom four teams in
the Premier and the top four in Division 1, are:
Group A -- teams finishing ninth and twelfth in the Premier plus the
first and third in Division 1. Group B -- teams finishing tenth and
eleventh in the Premier against those finishing second and fourth in
Division 1.
The two group winners play Premier Division hockey next season.
</TEXT>
