<DOCNO>GH950323-000047</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000047</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Touch of Hastings magic rubs off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN LORIMER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<CORRECTION>ANIMATION FESTIVAL IS AT EAST KILBRIDE ARTS CENTRE, OLD COACH ROAD, (BOX OFFICE: 013552 61000) NOT THE            CIVIC CENTRE.</CORRECTION>
<RECORDNO>979255475</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT seems a just coincidence that in a season when Gavin Hastings has
achieved remarkable form in the Five Nations' Championship, his alma
mater, George Watson's College in Edinburgh, has enjoyed one of its most
successful seasons to finish alongside that other school of rugby
excellence, Merchiston Castle, in the top rankings.
Watson's success story is better measured in terms of the calandar
year rather than the school rugby season. In January 1994, Watson's
defeated Royal Grammar School, Newcastle, 7-3 to begin a sequence of
victories that was to continue until this year when they lost 19-18 to
local rivals Stewart's-Melville.
That added up to 27 victories that included wins over
Stewart's-Melville, by 18-14, and Eton College, 5-3, the latter
performance giving an indication of what was to follow later.
''That game gave us a guage of how things were going to turn out this
season,'' reflected Roy Mack, the head of physical education at
Watson's. Wins against Loretto, Fettes, and Glenalmond were followed by
a 17-7 victory over Edinburgh Academy but the big success this season
was the 27-22 defeat of Merchiston at Myreside watched by a crowd of
more than 1000.
Four days later, Watson's added Gordonstoun to their list and then
completed the year in fine style by defeating Heriot's 20-7. In the
twelve-month period, Watson's scored 1076 points while conceding just
172, figures which say a lot about the attacking ability of the side.
The first XV, of course, is the showcase for a school which turns out
24 teams every Saturday. A co-educational school, Watson's nevertheless
has 950 boys, all of whom are exposed to a balanced physical educational
curriculum consistent with current approaches. Rugby, in fact, is not
compulsory and, for the most part, is an after-school activity.
Mack heads a physical education department of 10 which includes Andrew
Ker, the former Kelso and Scotland stand-off, Ally Donaldson, the Currie
and Edinburgh player, Scottish Schools treasurer Ian Brown, and former
Trinity hooker Alan Bennett.
It also helps to have high-profile role models, the latest of whom are
Gavin and Scott Hastings. The brothers are two of the many Watson's
players who have represented Scottish Schools.
Their present-day successor is Danny Mallinson, who has played both at
full back and wing for Scottish Schools and could be the player to take
over from Gavin Hastings at Myreside when the Scotland captain decides
to retire.
And Mallinson could be destined to go all the way and win a full
Scotland cap.
After all, there is a well-trodden path to Murrayfield from George
Watson's College, a centre of excellence that should continue to
flourish as one of the top rugby schools in Scotland.
</TEXT>
