<HEADLINE>Toons of glory</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID GRANT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255476</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
What's up, doc? Animation festivals in East Kilbride and Stirling.
David Grant finds there is more to them than meets the eye
IT takes Quentin Tarantino a mere split second to splatter someone's
insides all over the big screen. So spare a thought for the poor
animator of old Wile E. Coyote, or Tom Cat, as they suffer through the
endless tiny movements before that anvil smashes heads.
Consider this: the traditional cartoon animation requires an artist
(or team of artists) to produce 24 drawings that create just a second of
screen action. When you know that director Tim Burton had to accumulate
108,000 tiny movements to assemble the mere 72 minutes of the
stop-motion horror extravaganza, The Nightmare Before Christmas, you
begin to appreciate the meticulous art of animation.
So children of all ages should greet two animation festivals
brightening up the screens in Scotland in the coming weeks.
The East Kilbride Animation Festival takes place in the town's Civic
Centre on Saturday, with five different types of animation -- cartoon,
live action with cell animation, models, computer-generated images and
collage.
Meanwhile, the twelfth annual Puppet and Animation Festival stretches
from Stirling to Lanark, with a myriad of events throughout the Easter
holiday period. Stirling's MacRobert Arts Centre has some impressive
screenings running from April 10 to 15.
The younger enthusiasts are well catered for at both festivals. At
East Kilbride, two workshops in animation will run. The first, for
younger children, will teach the basics of model-making and paper
cut-out techniques, and the work will be filmed to produce a
three-minute video.
The older children will be versed in the art of scratch-on-film
animation. Again, a three-minute 35mm film will be the product of the
workshop. Both will be viewed later in the day.
The finished articles from a series of school workshops will be seen
at the MacRobert, a prelude to a 70-minute overdose of Hollywood cartoon
tomfoolery on April 15.
East Kilbride is set to screen 32 international films (including
Nicole van Goethem's 1983 Oscar winner, Greek Tragedy), half of which
are Scottish premieres and three are 1995 Oscar nominees. The Civic
Centre wil also host a retrospective of Barry Purves' work.
In Stirling, too, there is something for every taste. After some
frantic fairytale reworkings, Tim ''Batman'' Burton's Nightmare is
coupled with his first animated work, Vincent.
The latest ultra-violent craze from Japan, Manga cartoons, is
represented by a sci-fi feature, The Wings of Honneamise.
The surreal and macabre wit of Jan Svankmajer and the Brother Quay --
devotees of Svankmajer's absurdist genre -- will appeal to older
aficionados of darker animation, but for many, the highlight of the
Stirling week will be an evening in the company of Aardman animation, in
the shape of the award-winning company's technical director, Glen Hall.
Wallace and Gromit fans will miss this helping of cracking toast at
their peril, as Hall follows screenings of The Wrong Trousers, A Grand
Day Out, and the plasticine-powered and socially-aware slice of Zoo TV,
Creature Comforts.
Finally, there's Tim Watts' and David Stoten's Oscar-nominated The Big
Story -- in which a cast of Kirk Douglases learn the truth of life in
the newspaper business. It's been showing with Pulp Fiction, but if you
haven't the stomach for Tarantino, you can see it at the end of Saturday
afternoon's programme in East Kilbride.
* Further information on the East Kilbride Animation Festival is
available from the Civic Centre, telephone 013552 71200, while details
of the Stirling-hosted Puppet and Animation Festival events are
available from the MacRobert Arts Centre on 01786 461081.
</TEXT>
