<DOCNO>GH950323-000049</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000049</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>McCuish blow for Oban</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH DAN MACLELLAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255477</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
OBAN Camanachd have been left counting the cost of last weekend's
Glenmorangie Camanachd Cup victory over Skye. Striker Dave McCuish has a
broken bone in a foot and will be sidelined for at least six weeks,
which means he will miss the Keyline MacAulay Cup final if Oban qualify
by beating Inveraray and a Camanachd Cup tie against Beauly.
Fort William, surprisingly easy winners against Kingussie last weekend
in the Keyline MacAulay Cup, face a similar set of travel arrangements
this Saturday as their Camanachd Cup tie against Inveraray has been
scheduled for Inveraray, Fort William, Taynuilt, or Spean Bridge as the
Camanachd Association battle to beat the fixtures pile-up which has
developed.
If Fort's match fails to make it at any of the venues, the match will
be switched anywhere, with Perth again a possibility, in a bid to get it
played. Extra time and penalties have been sanctioned for this replay
after the teams shared four goals on their last meeting.
In league terms, this Saturday could also be crucial with both
Kingussie and Oban Camanachd ready to take a major step toward clinching
their respective first division titles in the north and south.
Kingussie need three points from their two remaining matches and
should pick up two when they take on Beauly at home. Oban Camanachd, who
face Strachur, need six points from four matches.
</TEXT>
