<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>All to play for now in race for the checkered flag. Mansell could still be in the driving seat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY WALKER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255478</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
' There are no team orders at Williams so you can expect Damon Hill
and David Coulthard to be pushing each other '
By LEADING TV
COMMENTATOR
MURRAY WALKER
LET me start by saying that I believe that the coming season will be
the best for some time. I say that because so many things point to it
being a good year.
First, the conditions are right, the rule changes have ensured that
everybody has started with a clean sheet and a new car.
This was unavoidable because we now have new aero-dynamic regulations
and the engine capacity has dropped from 3.5 to 3 litres. With this
combination I can see a much closer championship.
We will still look to the ''big four,'' Williams, McLaren, Benetton,
and Ferrari, to provide the fireworks. However, I think by season's end
we could be talking in terms of the ''big five,'' because I think it's
graduation time for Jordan.
This is a team who achieved a coup in getting the Peugeot works deal
that McLaren had last year.
Eddie Jordan's team has been on the brink of stardom for some time, so
with Peugeot and drivers Eddie Irvine and Rubens Barrichello, Jordan are
an exciting prospect.
Looking elsewhere on the grid, I think we have to look for the French
team, Legier, to make a show. They were bought by Flavio Briatore, of
Benetton, last year and I expect there to have been some considerable
cross-fertilisation between the teams, the result of which should
provide Legier with a good car.
They will also have the Mugen engine and that means Honda, a company
used to winning. They have been at the top with Williams, Lotus, and
McLaren. So Legier is a team on the up.
You then have to consider Tyrell and Sauber, who have the highly
prized official works engine.
So they are the cars that should be making the headlines, but the most
important thing that is going to ensure a competitive championship is
that every one of the eight teams has two very closely matched drivers.
For example there are no team orders at Williams this season. So you
can expect Damon Hill and David Coulthard to be pushing each other.
Eight teams with drivers of this sort of combination will really turn
up the heat on the grid. With that in mind I would be very hard pushed
to say which team will do best this year.
Conventional wisdom says Williams, Benetton, and McLaren will be the
top teams and if you are a serious Formula One fan, you have to hope
Ferrari will do well.
The thing with them is that they could have a problem with their V12,
3 litre engine, the characteristics of which may not be perfect for the
new formula. I hope they can get it right because with Gerhard Berger
and Jean Alesi, you have two fantastic driving talents.
Alesi is in search of his first victory and so often it's the same
drivers who win the races. This year we could see some new faces holding
a grand prix trophy.
Martin Brundle for one. He is a fine British driver who's been around
a long time and deserves a win, Johnny Herbert could win this year
because he's in the Benetton team and it would be no surprise to see
David Coulthard notch his first championship win.
Scotland have produced outstanding drivers and David has the potential
to be a world champion. He has been impressive but we must not forget
that he has only driven in eight grands prix.
This fact alone should not let people get carried away and suggest he
might be world champion this year, especially bearing in mind the
calibre of opposition he faces this year.
I say that not in any way to put David down as a driver. I say it
because one of the things you need as a driver in F1 is experience, and
that is what David lacks.
He is a very level-headed, sensible, mature, and intelligent young man
and I'm sure if you asked him he would agree that he needs more races
under his belt.
Michael Schumacher won the world championship in only his third full
season. He is a phenomenal talent but everyone needs experience behind
them to be a challenger for the title, and Michael now is a veteran of
50-odd races.
Anybody could tip Schumacher to take the title again this year, but I
am not going to do it. I'm going to predict that Nigel Mansell will win
his second world championship this year.
I am overjoyed that Nigel is back in F1 and found a berth with
McLaren, although actually filling that berth seems to be a problem at
the moment. If the car overcomes its problems Nigel can certainly go all
the way.
He is as hungry as ever for success and really wants that second
championship. With his focus and determination, it would be folly for
the critics to write him off.
All in all this should be a great season for the fans and I can hardly
wait until March 26 when we get it under way on Sunday.
Murray Walker was talking to Jim Kelly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>First for Sri Lanka</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255479</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SRI Lanka yesterday clinched their first series victory abroad by
drawing the second and final Test against New Zealand in Dunedin.
The visiting side resumed in the morning on 210 for three, a lead of
136, but some ineffectual New Zealand bowling allowed them to reach 411
all out.
Bryan Young then faced just one ball before a successful appeal
against bad light ended play and completed Sri Lanka's triumph.
New Zealand skipper Ken Rutherford, whose side have lost five and
drawn two of the eight Tests they have played this season, now believes
his captaincy is in jeopardy. ''I imagine New Zealand cricket will be
thinking long and hard over who they want to see leading the side next
summer,'' he said.
Sri Lanka batsman Asanka Gurusinha resumed the day on 92 and went on
to make 127 -- his sixth Test century -- before lunch. Hashan
Tillekeratne recorded his second Test ton with 108.
Captain Arjuna Ranatunga said there was some thought to setting New
Zealand a target of 250 in 50 overs but an ankle injury to pace bowler
Pramodya Wickremasinghe forced a rethink.
Ranatunga was delighted. ''I have waited a long and hard 13 years for
this. I am very pleased that it has finally come about,'' he said. Man
of the match was all-rounder Chaminda Vaas, who took five wickets and
also made his maiden Test half-century in Sri Lanka's first innings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The other megaBugs industry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEITH BRUCE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255480</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The box office is not the only source of cartoon revenue. Keith Bruce
checks out the market in the art-form's collectables.
GARY Kogon practically boasts of the allergies which gave him the
nick-name of ''Sneezy'' as a child. There are two good reasons for this.
First, he's small and dapper and the parallel with one of Snow White's
little chums could have been much less kind. Secondly, it led directly
to the career that has made him a wealthy man.
In that cruel way adults have, the young Kogon was presented with
numerous gifts connected with his alter ego, so when he was taken to
Disneyland in the 1960s he invested his $1 pocket-money wisely in a
single celluloid frame of the dwarf from the original cartoon.
In a week when the Disney organisation has used a couple of elephants
to destroy pirate toys in India as a symbol of its litigous commercial
intent, it seems incredible that such a cherished item was simply dumped
in a souvenir bin little more than 25 years ago, but that was the way
things were.
It was not until 1984 that animation art was declared an indigenous
American art form (surely an arguable point), an honour only previously
accorded to jazz.
By then, the enterprising Kogon was well ahead of the game. He's moved
out of the restaurant business into collectable animation art, with a
couple of galleries in his home town of Boston.
The market had moved on some considerable distance by then with single
''cells'' from the 1940s fetching #16,000 at Christie's in London and a
1934 Disney cell from the cartoon, Orphans' Benefit, reaching a record
$454,000 in the US.
Predictably, the studios started to wise up to the value of their
assets but, strangely, Disney has still been slower to capitalise than
Warner Brothers, home of Bugs Bunny, Elmer Fudd, Sylvester, and the
God-like Chuck Jones, doyen of animators.
Kogon was head-hunted by Warners to direct its worldwide gallery
operations, which occupy a lucrative corner of its stores, including the
one in Glasgow's Buchanan Street.
Warners have moved $1 bargain-bins of discarded celluloid on to
another plane altogether with a range of collectable cartoon-derived
artefacts at prices for the dedicated.
Production cells range from #200 to more than #300, and the market has
been creatively expanded with the origination of limited edition cells
specially for collectors and runs of (similarly limited) commissioned
prints.
Surely, though, there are limitations on the archive Warners can
exploit. Bugs only made 170 six-minute cartoons, after all. That's a
mere 884,000 cells, or thereabouts.
Relax, Bunny-lovers, the Brothers have just signed the 82-year-old
Chuck Jones to a new 80-year contract and the new Roadrunner/Wile E.
Coyote opus, Chariots of Fur, is his first work in 30 years.
And he's training a new team in the techniques behind those Merrie
Melodies classics.
''Sneezy'' Kogon's personal collection now stands at some 110 pieces
-- some of them very valuable indeed -- and his job looks safe for some
time. Which understandably pleases the small man no end.
''As long as I can be a kid, I'm gonna be,'' he confesses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The flaky business of French baking</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JANET REID</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255481</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IMPORTING plane-loads of frozen croissant-shaped dough from France and
baking it in Scotland is certainly possible. But when you can buy
authentic French croissants, made to traditional French recipes and of
the finest quality flour, with no additives or preservatives, and which
are freshly baked every day in Springburn, it does seem a touch
unnecessary.
When you discover they are delivered, still warm, to delicatessens,
restaurants, cafes and hotels all over Glasgow, importing could be seen
as downright perverse. Especially when there are many who would claim
that these Springburn croissants, made by Patisserie Francoise, are the
best they've tasted outside France.
No need to search hard for the explanation for their delectable
excellence. Patisserie Francoise this year celebrates a quarter of a
century as a French bakery in Glasgow. And its roots go further back
still, to the twenties, when Tony Cocozza's grandfather first came to
Glasgow and built up three cafes which flourished until, like most of
Springburn, they were demolished in the sixties.
However, in the meantime, Cocozza's father, Adolfo, had married a
French girl, Francoise. She was a talented baker who had learned her
skills at her brother's baker's shop in Chalons-sur-Marne; and when she
came to Glasgow she became the very first baker of croissants here,
supplying them and brioches, patisserie, and gateaux to the three cafes.
As a result, by 1970, the bakery business had started to overtake the
cafes, and Francoise and Adolfo had established their Patisserie
Francoise in Springburn.
Now, 25 years later, it again supplies its own outlets as well -- the
Patisserie Francoise in Byres Road, which this year celebrates its tenth
birthday, and a licensed cafe in the Italian Centre, which opened three
years ago. And like its baguettes which gradually expand as they rise
and prove before baking, the business has grown so much that now not
only are there seven bakery employees but the entire Cocozza family of
four children also works for the firm.
This is a real family business in every sense of the word. Adolfo and
Francoise are still closely involved in the bakery, Adolfo turning his
hand to anything that needs doing, while Francoise makes all the special
gateaux, the wedding cakes, the crocodile cake ordered by Elton John
when he was once in Glasgow, and the special gateau baked in honour of
the Queen Mother when she opened the Royal Scottish Academy of Music and
Drama a few years ago.
Tony's three sisters are equally active in the company. Natalie is in
charge of the patisserie part of the bakery, helped by Linda; Yasmin
runs the two cafes, both of which have a loyal regular clientele as well
as plenty of passing trade -- in response to healthy customer demand the
Byres Road outlet doubled in size just before Chrismas.
And Tony himself has taken over the running of the whole business from
his parents. This means long 12-hour days which frequently start at 5am,
and in which he copes with almost anything and everything.
In what spare time he has, Tony is presently in the midsts of planning
the move from the current bakery premises to a larger site, nearby in
Springburn, where he plans a new purpose-built bakery which will give
still greater scope for the growth of the business.
There's no shortage of hard work but the satisfactions of creativity
as a baker and achievement as a businessman are more than compensation
-- indeed he relishes these as much as his customers relish those
delicious and perfectly baked croissants with their breakfast coffee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wester Ross yard may reopen for platforms</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANGUS MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255482</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SECOND company has been examining the Kishorn yard in Wester Ross,
with a view to taking advantage of renewed interest in concrete oil
platforms to exploit the oil fields west of Shetland and in the
Atlantic.
Last summer, Costain/Taylor Woodrow revealed that they are interested
in reopening the yard to build a concrete platform, and that they would
need a labour camp for 500 workers.
Now it is understood that representatives from John Laing Engineering
have also been to see the yard in the past few weeks.
They are believed to be examining the suitability of the Kishorn yard
for building a concrete tension leg production platform, in partnership
with another oil fabrication company, for the fields discovered west of
Shetland. BP are already known to be looking at several options,
including three concrete platform designs, for the second phase of its
Foinaven field development.
McDermott/Golar Nor and Brown and Root/Single Buoy Moorings are each
proposing a steel floating production storage and offloading vessel.
Three other consortiums are proposing a concrete semi-submersible, a
concrete tension leg platform, and a concrete monohull, respectively.
One of the consortiums involves McAlpine and Doris Engineering. Doris
Engineering were partners in Howard-Doris when the Kishorn yard was in
full operation in the seventies and eighties, but if they are
successful, they are more likely to use the yard at Ardyne Point, which
is owned by McAlpine.
Amerada Hess are also active in the area, in the Solan, Schiehallion,
Strathmore and Clair fields, and they are planning to drill at least a
dozen appraisal wells this year, one of which was reported to be ''dry''
earlier this week. It is likely that if the concrete options prove to be
cost-effective, this would be an attractive path for other companies to
follow. A spokesman for Amerada Hess said it was too early to say what
options they would choose, but that nothing is being ruled out at this
stage.
Costain/Taylor Woodrow, who are preparing to float out a concrete
gravity base structure from Hunterston in Ayshire next month, for BP's
Harding field in the central North Sea, are also interested in bidding
for work west of Shetland, and using the Kishorn yard for any contracts
they might win. But a spokesman would say this week only that as far as
the Kishorn yard is concerned, negotiations with the yard's landlords
are ongoing.
According to a spokesman for Doris Engineering, interest in concrete
platforms is increasing because the sea depths west of Shetland make
steel jackets, which would sit on the seabed, impractical. Concrete
platforms are more stable, and while the capital cost of building can be
high, easier maintenance means lower running costs.
They can also be designed to have inbuilt storage space for oil, which
can then be transferred to tankers for trans-shipment to shore
terminals. But this upsurge in activity will also have an impact on
Highland yards involved in steel fabrication, since orders for topside
facilities will also be placed. The industry, consequently, expects 1996
to be a busy year.
But even if the companies developing the west of Shetland fields
decide to go for the concrete options, the Kishorn yard faces stiff
competition, both in Norway and in the UK. Facilities at Hunterston,
Ardyne Point, and in England are also available, and the Highlands
Fabricators yard at Nigg is also presenting its dry dock as another
possible facility.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
