<DOCNO>GH950323-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chinese join the Hong Kong scrum</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN LORIMER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255484</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH University yesterday made rugby history by becoming the
first side to play against a team from mainland China in an
international tournament.
The Edinburgh students were taking part in a 10-a-side tournament in
Hong Kong in preparation for the Cathay Pacific/Hong Kong Bank
Invitation sevens this weekend.
Edinburgh, with centre Glen Howett in excellent form, had little
difficulty in defeating Beijing Agricultural University 24-0, their
tries coming from George McKinley (2) and Jamie Douglas (2), and two
conversions by Stuart Pearson.
In an earlier tie, the Edinburgh students opened strongly against Hong
Kong Dragons and won 24-0 through tries by Pearson (2), Craig Hunter and
John McKinley, two of the scores being converted by David Officer.
George McKinley added to his tally with a try in Edinburgh's third and
last game against the bizarrely named Funky Gibbons from Australia, who
scored a 12-5 win over the Scots. That result gave the Edinburgh
students second position in their pool and a place in today's
quarter-finals of the plate competition.
</TEXT>
