<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Credo of money</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255485</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GEORGE Hume's brilliant and devastating attack on the credo of money
and its sweeping consequences for the general wellbeing of society
should be a warning to all in power, and those who aspire to it (March
17).
But when the chips are really down at the national political beauty
contest in two years' time (or earlier), how many of the big players --
those with so much to lose -- will actually desert the Conservatives?
One thing seems certain. In the new millennium we can achieve that
ideal so eloquently proclaimed at Gettysburg in 1863, the faithful
enactment and delivery of which seem so far to have eluded us: '' . . .
government of the people, by the people''.
Thomas McIndoe,
41 Loch Laidon Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
