<HEADLINE>Hanging around for the plot</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM RUSSELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255487</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
William Russell reviews this week's crop of new film releases
THRILLS, spills and heart-stopping action are what you get in John
Badham's Drop Zone. What you don't get is a plot that makes sense, but
this is one of those films which began with the stunts and the plot got
tagged on to justify them later. The aim is to get the audience on the
edge of their seats as often as possible, and it does exactly that.
In a good thriller the hero is changed by the adventures he has
endured. Cary Grant in Hitchcock's North by North West, for instance,
starts off as a smooth, smug chap in control of events and ends up
hanging on for dear life from the stone faces on Mount Rushmore in a
somewhat dishevelled condition, very much out of control of events. He
has also fallen in love.
Here, Wesley Snipes, playing dense macho US Marshall, Pete Nessip,
ends up a little battered round the edges, but otherwise still the same
old macho thick Pete. He does not even get round to kissing the heroine,
Jessie Crossman (Yancey Butler), although he does give her a punch on
the jaw since he is a man's man and she is a man's woman. Jessie looks
pleased by the attention!
Pete and his brother Terry, also a US Marshall, are escorting a
computer genius from one jail to another on a commercial flight when it
is ambushed by terrorists led by Ty Moncrief (Gary Busey), who has
wall-to-wall teeth which he uses to bite off the computer expert's
little finger. In the ensuing melee a door is blasted open, and half the
passengers sucked out into space, including the terrorists, Terry, and
the computer man.
But it is all scam. The villains, expert sky-divers, have chosen this
method to spring the computer expert, because they intend to break into
the US Drug Enforcement Agency computer and sell the identities of all
the undercover agents to the drug cartels. The break-in is to be done
under cover of a Fourth of July mass parachute drop over Washington.
The violence is excessive -- a policeman has his throat cut on camera,
for instance -- though Busey's wallies, a miracle of modern dentistry,
keep distracting one's attention. But Badham and his stuntmen have
delivered the necessary thrills as they fly through the air with the
greatest of ease whether from 38,000ft or the top of a skyscraper.
Anybody who has not read the book, probably the majority of the
potential cinema audience, will hugely enjoy Gillian Armstrong's
gorgeously photographed, well-acted, politically-correct,
feminist-oriented version of Louisa May Alcott's Little Women. Those
familiar with Miss Alcott's work may have reservations, but Armstrong,
Australia's finest director, has at last achieved what has so far eluded
her -- a Hollywood box office hit.
The problem with this up-dating of the story for the 1990s is that the
picture it gives of the lives of young women in the 1860s becomes
falsified. Does it matter? If there are lessons to be learned by men and
women today from how society behaved in the past then one should see how
it behaved, not how we would like it to have behaved, which is what the
film provides.
It is not that Armstrong, best known for My Brilliant Career about a
young woman finding freedom through writing, or Robin Swicord, who wrote
the script, have done anything too awful to the story of the March girls
and their long suffering Marmee. But somewhere along the line what the
two novels, Little Women and Good Wives, on which the film is based,
have to say about women's lives at the time has vanished.
Ditching the Beth, the piano and old Mr Lawrence plotline for the
ineffectual revised version provided, seems perverse, and by stopping Jo
lamenting that she is not a boy -- something today's girl would never do
-- one takes away the dilemma any girl of spirit had to cope with then.
Society did not allow her to do things that a less talented boy would be
allowed to do as a matter of course.
The other alterations are of little moment. The details added from
what is known about the real life Alcotts -- Marmee (Susan Sarandon) is
a practitioner of homeopathic medicine, Jo (Winona Ryder) discusses
female suffrage when she goes to New York to work, and Professor Bhaer
becomes a transcendentalist -- being neither here nor there. The trouble
arises with the updating of Alcott's text.
In Little Women, Marmee tells her girls: -- ''I want my daughters to
be beautiful, accomplished, and good; to be admired, loved, and
respected; to have a happy youth, to be well and wisely married, and to
lead useful, pleasant lives with as little care and sorrow to try them
as God sees fit to send.
''To be loved and chosen by a good man is the best and sweetest thing
which can happen to a woman and I sincerely hope my girls may know this
beautiful experience.''
It contrasts starkly with the text for today Marmee actually delivers.
Sarandon is oddly ineffectual, but Ryder's Jo, although far too pretty,
and by no stretch of the imagination a tomboy, is the best thing she has
done. She conveys perfectly the frustrations endured by a girl of spirit
trapped by society's rules.
Expertly made and lovely to look at, it will warm the cockles of lots
of hearts even if Meg, Beth and Amy are no more than adequately cast,
and the men are a job-lot to say the least. Eric Stoltz's John Brooke is
the sort of sanctimonious creep sensible girls cross the street to
avoid, and Gabriel Byrne's Professor Bhaer is more a Glockamorra than
Mittel European heart-throb.
But for all its felicities, what we see is women's lives in the 1860s
as women of 1990 would like them to have been. The depiction of how it
was is what gives the novels their value and the film, by falsifying
things -- not for dramatic ends, but for feminist reasons -- does both
Alcott and the audience a disservice.
Another woman director -- they are not quite as thin on the ground as
all that -- Darnell Martin, makes an impressive debut with I Like it
Like That, a story about Puerto Ricans living in the South Bronx. A
chaotic affair bursting with energy and much Latin loving, as Lisette
(Lauren Velez) falls out with Chino (Jon Seda), the father of her child,
throws him out and sets about achieving her independence, it would have
benefitted from a little restraint. The top of the voice lifestyle
eventually becomes rather wearing, but the encounter between Lisette and
her new, sexually predatory boss (Griffin Dunne) is worth the price of
admission alone. No man should ever ask ''How was it for you?'' He may
get told. Rita Moreno sparkles as Chino's mother who thinks her son
could do better.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000060</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000060</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots plan an upset</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELSPETH BURNSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255488</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FIONA Campbell and Kirsty Hope, who will both compete for Scotland in
next month's Multi-Nations tournament at Edinburgh's Commonwealth Pool,
head Scotland's attempt to upset the English in this weekend's schools'
home internationals in Cork.
England have never been beaten in the annual event, but the Scots are
particularly strong at junior and intermediate level, with Bryan Morgan,
Karen-Marie Lewis, Fraser Bisley, and Lynn McLaren all having shown fine
form in recent weeks.
''Because of differences in the systems, the English pupils tend to
stay on for an extra year, so they always have an advantage at senior
level,'' said school's organiser Ken White.
The final qualifying round of the Speedo British Grand Prix also takes
place at Crystal Palace in London this weekend, but it has been almost
ignored by the Scottish swimmers.
Angela Pendrich, who returns today from the Scottish squad training
camp in Lanzarote, and Warrender's Richard Hope are competing along with
the Stirling University pair of Pauline McLean and Forbes Dunlop. The
Grand Prix Superfinal takes place in Cardiff in May, and is equally
likely to be short of Scottish interest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Putting a spanner in the works</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255489</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MURRAY Walker, ''The voice of motor sport,'' is, of course, a highly
respected sports commentator, but his tendency to make the odd cock-up
has helped to establish him as a legend in his own lifetime.
Once after a gruelling race he asked Nigel Mansell to show the viewers
a nasty bump the driver had sustained on his forehead. Mansell gingerly
lifted his cap off, whereupon Murray stabbed a finger straight on to the
bump, inquiring of a screaming Mansell that he had found the right spot.
Countless times Murray described the masterful display of driving on
offer only for the object of his comments to make a mistake and finish
upside down off the track.
Situations like this, Murray insists, best explain his reputation for
dropping clangers. ''So often it's not mistakes I have made but an
unhappy coincidence of my description of events turning disastrously
wrong almost instantaneously, but that's the beauty of live
television.''
Murray's voice is an impressionist's dream and his catalogue of
blunders have attracted much leg-pulling over the years. But it does not
bother him. He said: ''I have a sense of humour, so it's not a problem,
it shows I am only human and make mistakes like everybody else, it's
just that perhaps I make more than most.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Craig leads school to fourth triumph</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255490</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ST ALOYSIUS won the Bank of Scotland Schools Cup, beating Queen
Victoria School 44-10 with seven tries to one in the final yesterday at
Malleny Park, Currie.
It was the Glasgow schools fourth victory in eight successive finals,
but they owed much to captain and right wing, James Craig, son of
Celtic's 1967 Lisbon Lion, who ran in all three first-half tries as well
as kicking three conversions and a penalty goal for 24 points.
It was, too, one of St Aloysius' easiest final wins, though against
the wind in the first half they had to work hard to subdue the stuffy
Dunblane team. The difference was in Craig's scoring.
* SCOTLAND'S warm-up for the FIRA junior tournament next month
produced only one try last night at Murrayfield, but it was still a good
trial for the Bucharest challenge, according to the team's coach,
Alastair Christie.
The FIRA squad won 7-3 against a team drawn from those under-19 Scots
ineligible for the tournament.
Gregor Hayter scored the game's only try off a forward drive after 28
minutes. Graeme Hay converted. Four minutes later Michael Duncan had a
penalty goal for the opposition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>United bounce back and silence the Gunners</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255491</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MANCHESTER United trimmed Blackburn's lead at the top of the English
Premiership to three points after their 3-0 win against Arsenal at Old
Trafford last night.
Early goals from Mark Hughes and Lee Sharpe put United in command, and
Andrei Kanchelskis made sure of the points with a third after 80
minutes.
This success enabled United to bounce back to winning ways after
having been held by Spurs at home last week and then losing to Liverpool
at Anfield.
The result also tightens things up at the top again, but Blackburn
have the cushion of a game in hand.
Nottingham Forest boosted their hopes of qualifying for the UEFA Cup
with a 3-0 home win over Leeds. This success means that Forest now have
overhauled Liverpool, who fought out a 0-0 draw with Tottenham at White
Hart Lane.
Brian Roy, who struck twice, and Stan Collymore ended Leeds' run of
three successive victories, and the Forest defence can take credit for
keeping out Leeds, who had scored three goals in each of those last
three games.
Southampton completed a remarkable comeback after having trailed to a
goal in 17 minutes by Newcastle's Paul Kitson at the Dell.
Neil Heaney equalised four minutes from the end. Then new #1.2m
signing from Sheffield Wednesday, Gordon Watson, gave Saints the lead in
the last minute before Neil Shipperley made sure.
The win leaves Alan Ball's men in the bottom four, although they did
move above Crystal Palace. Kevin Gallen clinched victory for QPR in the
West London derby against Chelsea with a goal after 62 at Loftus Road.
In the FA Cup, Alan Smith's Crystal Palace booked their place in the
semi-final stage -- where they will face Manchester United -- with a 4-1
success at Wolverhampton.
At the top of Division 1, Bolton's 1-1 draw with Sheffield United at
Burnden Park did them more favours in the promotion race. They stay in
third position, but move to within a point of second-placed Tranmere and
two of leaders Middlesbrough, with a game in hand on both.
Nathan Blake gave Sheffield United the lead after 37 minutes, only for
Alan Stubbs to equalise five minutes later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>An early exit for Nicol</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELSPETH BURNSIDE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255492</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PETER Nicol and Senga Macfie completed a dismal day for Scottish
squash when they both made their exit in yesterday's first round of the
Leekes British Open at Cardiff.
For Scottish champion Nicol, the world No.5, a 15-14, 3-15, 17-15,
15-8 loss to French qualifier Julien Bonetat extended his disastrous
British Open record. Despite a meteoric rise through the rankings over
the past two years, he is still awaiting his first win in the top home
event.
In 1993, he failed to get past the qualifying rounds, while as a seed
last year he also went out to a qualifier. Even a return to the scene of
his most famous win -- against world champion Jansher Khan in the Welsh
Classic 13 months ago -- failed to end the jinx.
Macfie, the No.14 seed, looked set to make a remarkable recovery from
two games down to English qualifier, Donna Vardy, but she failed to
press home a 6-2 lead in the decider, and eventually lost 9-7, 10-8,
6-9, 0-9, 9-7.
Nicol attributed his defeat to a loss of confidence as the match
proceeded -- losing the third game from 6-0 ahead was particularly
destructive -- and there is little doubt that a recent bout of
tonsillitis has also taken its toll.
Ironically, Bonetat, the world No.27, paid tribute to the part played
by Nicol's coach, Neil Harvey. ''He has helped improve my fitness,''
said the 24 year-old.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bowled over in Ireland</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GORDON DUNWOODIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>26</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255493</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S women players almost certainly waved goodbye to their hopes
of a third win in the home international indoor championship in
Ballymoney, Northern Ireland, yesterday when they went down 132-99 to
England.
The Scots now must hope that Wales can beat England this morning and
they can then record a big win over the hosts to allow them to complete
the hat trick.
However, that is not a realistic hope with Wales struggling to beat
Ireland 117-102 yesterday.
Scotland started brightly against the English, and with five ends
completed they were 33-20 in front. However, England hit back to take a
57-48 lead at the halfway point, and they pulled away over the second
half for a convincing victory.
The main problem for the Scots came in the rink skipped by Roberta
Hutchison. The Falkirk player, who had been the highest scorer against
Wales, went down 36-10 and lost a maximum 8 on the eighteenth end
against Irene Molyneux.
Joyce Lindores, with world champion Jan Woodley winning her first
international cap as lead in place of Liz Kirkwood, lost 22-15 to Norma
Shaw, Frances Haxton went down 18-20 to Mary Price, and Anne Watson was
edged out 21-22 by Jayne Roylands.
Scotland's only win came from Jeanette Conran who beat Wendy Line
18-15, while Auchinleck's Nancy Davidson forced a 17-17 draw with Mavis
Steele.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A week of rising tempos</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MICHAEL TUMELTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255494</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT may not register on the Scottish festival seismograph, but in
several respects, the annual Glasgow Music Festival, which opens
tomorrow, is probably one of the biggest in the country.
The festival is funded 50% from sponsorship and the rest from fees and
admissions. It runs in the City Hall in Candleriggs and Renfield St
Stephen's Church Centre in Bath Street, and is a hectic, round-the-clock
affair.
Within eight days, the festival will feature almost 4000 performers,
ranging in age from six to 80. Audiences totalling over 6000 are
expected. And the entire venture is run on a budget of #12,000.
The Glasgow Music Festival -- now in its 83rd year -- offers, to the
man or woman in the street and the child in the classroom, the
opportunity to develop their performing skills.
The festival now offers more than 250 categories in music and speech.
New categories will allow performances from musicals and light opera,
while the range of piano solo events has been extended to include
ragtime and blues.
Speech categories, as usual, feature verse and public speaking, with,
this year, several new categories, including team debating, TV
newsreading (presented in association with BBC Television and judged by
newsreader Sally McNair) and drama monologues and duologues.
There is a competitive element, with trophies and prizes to be won.
However, festival chairman Robert MacDonald said: ''It's not the most
important part. We play down the competitive bit, though it does add
excitement.''
The results will be published in The Herald from Saturday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Integration of past and futures</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER SIMS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255495</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE ROYAL Bank of Scotland's corporate and institutional banking
division in the City of London has virtually completed its move into
shiny new offices located within the impressive late-nineteenth century
Prudential building off Holborn, now known as Waterhouse Square.
The move followed several years of strong growth in this divison. The
activities had been scattered among a number of locations in the City
and this was clearly becoming unacceptable.
''Customers should not expect to have to deal with people in several
different locations,'' observed Iain Robertson, a former head of the
Scottish Development Agency who has been managing director of the
division since 1992. He is now revelling in the new offices.
''I can now deal with issues with a quick walk round the office
whereas before it needed several separate phone calls.''
''We now have this tremendous capability of bringing teams together so
that when you get a particular proposal you can bring in a treasury
person, someone from structured finance, someone from the project
finance side, someone from the banking side, maybe someone from leasing.
So you can get the work done quickly.''
The main requirement for the new building was to obtain one of those
giant trading floors which are the feature of the City nowadays. This
floor is approximately 100 metres wide.
This requirement meant that there were few suitable buildings
available. The group's property people did look at Docklands, where a
financial area centred on Canary Wharf has been developed, but concluded
it was just too far from the City. Eventually the Prudential building
was chosen.
The site has been completely redeveloped while retaining the original,
elaborate facade -- which is a testament to Victorian bricklaying
skills.
The decision to take the 175,000 square foot site could not have been
better timed because the bank signed the lease just at the bottom of the
property bear market.
Royal Bank's property department worked with architects Thomas
Saunders Partnership to fit out the building. The costliest part of the
work was the #17m installation of the sophisticated electronics needed
to keep the trading screens winking. In all, some 650 miles of cabling
was laid. Previously the group had lagged a little in the technology
stakes but is now state of the art.
''We were lucky in a way because we did not invest perhaps as much as
we should have done in the 1980s,'' said Mr Robertson. ''But because of
the speed of technological change this has enabled us to leapfrog a
couple of generations. We have chosen products which are proven but at
the front end of the technology.''
Installed by a firm called Wall Street Systems, the network allows Mr
Robertson to see what positions the bank has outstanding at the press of
a button, a useful precaution these days. Not that the bank does much
proprietary trading, the great majority of business comes from
customers.
''One inevitably does it to a small extent,'' said Mr Robertson. ''But
the small amount of proprietary trading we do means any danger is
limited. We expect our books to be reconciled by the time the back
office goes home at night.
''But if you get what appears to be fraud, you don't want to say it
can never happen. However, given that we are customer driven, I feel it
is much less likely to happen to a bank like ourselves.''
The driving force behind the corporate and institutional division has
been to make better use of the customer base through offering more
services.
''Some 60% of income growth has come from encouraging existing
customers to use more services. The group is particularly strong in
certain niche areas like custody, security services and shipping and
increasingly in certain Treasury areas,'' added Mr Robertson
Customers have appreciated that the bank has stayed in the corporate
market despite making losses in the early 1990s. This has encouraged the
development of long-term relationships.
''This does not mean you get a better price but it does at least mean
that customers will give you first chance at a particular propositon.''
One area where the bank was behind was in treasury operations. Three
years ago its market share was perhaps half what it should have been
given its size in other activities. Now the division is two years into a
five-year plan to reach the market share it should have. Income from
this business has doubled, and could well double again as the customer
base has grown by a third.
The new premises have the capacity to handle this. Staff currently
number 800 and could go up to 1100 people. ''At that point we would
really have to move people into the corridors -- and don't believe I
wouldn't if we could get the business,'' quipped Mr Robertson.
Since 1991, the division's profits before provisions have risen by 59%
but its relative importance has not inceased because of growth elsewhere
in the group.
''As a percentage of the group total, our profits have actually fallen
but we shall continue to be a major contributor to the group as a
whole.''
</TEXT>
