<HEADLINE>Moore leads Fifers down victory path</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>29</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255496</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Hamilton Accies 1, Dunfermline 3
DUNFERMLINE deserved to take the three points on offer at Firhill last
night which pushes them into the pace-setting role in the first division
on goal difference.
Hamilton tried to block the Fifers' path to the top and avoid their
fifth defeat on the trot, but it was not to be. Defensively they were
suspect although Alan Ferguson made a number of good saves.
A bad mistake led to Allan Moore opening the scoring three minutes
before the break, and slack covering allowed Hamish French his late,
points-clinching double.
Dunfermline dominated the first half, putting Accies keeper Ferguson
under pressure without cashing in on their outfield advantage.
Mark McCulloch had a drive touched over, then Marc Millar repeated
that feat before Andy Tod's header brought a goal-line save from
Ferguson. Then, with three minutes remaining before the interval and
Hamilton, not having tested van der Kamp, conceded a crazy opener.
Paul Chalmers was weak with a headed back pass just outside the box,
and Moore pounced to drive the ball home, leaving Ferguson stranded and
frustrated on his line.
After the break French struck twice to to clinch the points for
Dunfermline. His first came in 83 minutes when he controlled a Derek
Fleming corner before driving the ball into the net. And he added his
second three minutes later from the edge of the box.
Peter Duffield netted a consolation goal for the home side with just
seconds remaining.
HAMILTON -- Ferguson, Renicks, McInulty, McEntegart, McKenzie,
Hillcoat, Clark, Tighe, Chalmers, Duffield, McCormick. Substitutes --
Baptie, Lorimer, Cormack.
DUNFERMLINE -- Van der Kamp, McNamara, Fleming, McCathie, Tod,
McCulloch, Den Bieman, Robertson, French, Millar, Moore. Substitutes --
Hawkins, Smart, Westwater.
Referee -- T McCurry (Queen's Park).
</TEXT>
