<HEADLINE>Widow and son killed in crofthouse blaze</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255497</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN 83-year-old widow and her son died when a blaze destroyed their
crofthouse near Grantown on Spey yesterday.
Firefighters discovered the bodies of Mrs Edith Ross, who had lived in
the cottage at Braes of Castle Grant for 60 years, and of her son,
Peter, 53.
The alarm had been raised at 4am by fencer, Mr David MacLeod, who
lives in a nearby caravan.
He said: ''I was wakened by the light from the flames. The whole
caravan was lit up. I ran round and the place was gone.
''The walls were falling in. There was nothing I could do.
''I phoned the fire brigade but there was nothing left when they got
here. Mrs Ross and Peter did not stand a chance in that fire.''
Deputy firemaster, Mr John Cheadle, said: ''It is a very rural
setting. The croft is in the middle of a field along a narrow track and
by the time we got there it was well alight.''
Mrs Ross, a widow for 20 years, and her son shared the corrugated-iron
roofed crofthouse which had no electricity.
Their meals were cooked over an open fire and water drawn from a well
50 yards away.
Mrs Ross's other son, Sandy, who lives nearby, said: ''We have been
trying for years to get her into a home but she was set in her ways.
''She loved that place. Nothing could persuade her to move.''
The cause of the blaze is under investigation.
* Another pensioner has died in a fire, in Chapelhill, Kirkcaldy.
A care assistant who called on 84-year-old Jane Purcell on Tuesday
night found her body in the smoke-filled living-room of the house where
she lived alone.
Firefighters discovered a small blaze had burned itself out.
Police said later that a post-mortem examination would be held.
</TEXT>
