<HEADLINE>Judging a nation</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255498</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE article by Iain Wilson regarding the homeless in the Anderston
Centre made grim reading (March 18). If, as someone has said, a nation
is judged by the way it cares for its most disadvantaged, perhaps we
need not look at intractable economic theory for our missing feel-good
factor.
With the money spent on the National Health Service (more than ever
before), can some small resource not be made available to ensure that
homeless men and women are not denied access to a doctor because they
have no fixed address?
Robert Brown,
23 Vancouver Road,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
