<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tenants claim they are being forced out. Buses tycoon under attack</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255499</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE millionaire owner of the Stagecoach bus company, Mrs Ann Gloag,
came under fire yesterday from small businesses.
Tenants of industrial units in Perth owned by Mrs Gloag claimed they
were being forced to move out.
Mrs Gloag, a former Businesswoman of the Year, has been a past sponsor
of Perthshire Enterprise Company, which helps small businesses in the
city. Yesterday, however, she was on the receiving end of criticism from
the people she has tried to help.
Mr George Moyes, 60, who has run his painting and decorating business
from one of the units for more than 15 years, complained that his lease
was not being renewed.
He said: ''She's a hard woman. I feel gutted about this. I've only got
five years left before I retire and we only built this office two years
ago.
''There was a fire in the adjoining building in January. But, even
before the fire, we were told the lease was not being renewed. We never
got a reason.
''We've paid our rent up until the end of May, so we'll be moving to
new premises before then. What can we do? We feel we have been forced
out. When you come up against these sort of people, there's little you
can do.''
The firm paid a total of #2700 a year to Mrs Gloag in rent and service
charges.
Mr Moyes's wife, Sheila, 56, who works in the business, said: ''We had
to think about nine people's work and had to get a new place to keep the
business going. This will cost us valuable money, which we can't
afford.''
Other small businesses at the site complained that they were facing
uncertainty about their leases.
The manager of a joiner's firm said: ''We don't know what is going on.
Despite our phone calls, they haven't told us what is happening.''
Last night, Mrs Gloag said she sympathised with the tenants, but
stressed that her main concern was safety considerations after the fire.
She said: ''It has been a difficult patch for the small businesses in
the units. There are a number of problems with the safety of the
building, which we are trying to sort out. We have been reasonable but
have had to be forceful with tenants who have been understandably
reluctant to move. But we have offered them premises elsewhere in
Perth.''
She added: ''It is a pity that all of the tenants have had to suffer
because of what I suspect was the carelessness of one tenant in the
first place who started the fire.''
</TEXT>
