<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000072</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000072</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Money managers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255500</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AT last we hear, in the letter from Paul Laverty (March 17), the note
of piercing alarm warranted by what is happening at lightning speed to
the world's economy, with its accompanying powerful threat to democracy.
Ralph Nader, in his book, The Case against ''Free Trade'': Gatt,
Nafta, and the Globalisation of Corporate Power, describes it as a
''race to the bottom'' led by the IMF, the World Bank, and above all by
GATT, NAFTA, and the new World Trade Organisation.
These bodies, he says, are leading the planet in exactly the wrong
direction. If you ''want a small-scale preview of the post-Gatt and
Nafta free-trade world'', check out what has happened to Mexico. Its
economy is now in the hands of the USA, the ''foreign tigers have
overwhelmed the Mexican pussycats'', as a Mexican businessman has said,
and the poorest of Mexico's poor, the Maya Indians of Chiapas, are
forced to take up arms in their misery.
The whole situation has been summed up by Herman E Daly, an economist
in the Environment Department of the World Bank, writing in a personal
capacity.
He says the Gatt agreements mean ''the destruction of local and
national communities in the service of a single cosmopolitan world of
footloose money managers who constitute, not a community, but merely an
interdependent, mutually vulnerable, unstable coalition of short-term
interests.''
Ralph Nader's book should be compulsory reading for all ''New''
Labour's leaders and MPs, indeed for all British Opposition politicians.
Andrew Lockhart Walker,
7 Lovers' Loan,
Dollar.
</TEXT>
