<HEADLINE>Meeting the Jung at heart</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255501</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
An off-the-couch joust with psychiatrists can be stressful, as Joe
Donnelly recalls
THEY were all there for the asking. In fact it was hard to decide
whether the trick cyclists were promoting depression or trying to cure
it -- at a recent afternoon gathering in the Moat House of the Royal
College of Psychiatrists.
Finding a collective noun merely added to the anxiety of attending
such a conference. A shrive of shrinks? A smirk? (They do when they
realise you're a lay-person with only practical and personal knowledge
of mental imbalance which, of course they have diagnosed at forty
paces.) A slip of Freudians?
Try to get them to speak in plain English and they look at you as if
you are mad. In their professional opinion, you probably are, though
they won't use two-syllable words in confirming their diagnosis and it's
a sure bet you need two Diazepam with every bill presented.
The wrong movie? I was in the Cuckoo's Nest suffering pre-frontal
assaults on all sides. There they were, handing out high-anxiety like
there was no tomorrow, and they'll claim tomorrow is merely a
present-induced abstract concept any old how.
Yet the psychiatrists, incomprehensible though they were, seemed
merely a front for the big issue. This was selling at its finest, at its
hardest. Even the brain-mashers would have recognised the techniques.
All the big suppliers were there, the world's dealers and pushers of
uppers and happiness capsules, of sunshine in a pill. They had stalls
and posters and free post-its and what-nots advertising this or that
cure for depression.
Every mental condition was catered for, to torment the easily led --
namely, me.
Kleptomania? There were samples for everything, except the tablets
(they assured me, though they may have lied). Yet many seemed reluctant
to be seen getting something for nothing, heisting the company gifts.
None the less, the free gifts disappeared like snow off a dyke.
Paranoia? The rep' from one pill-pusher was not having a happy day.
One had only to stand near her desk when she pounced. ''Didn't you get a
pen before now? Put that back. You've already had a leaflet. Who are you
looking at, eh?'' Scary stuff.
Lethargy? Two cups of the astringent coffee and I was bouncing along
like a pogo-person. At ceiling height. It was three hours before the
palpitations stopped.
Insomnia? Try reading Neuro Endocrine Challenges throughout the
Menstrual Cycle of Healthy Women. Then try to stay awake without the
coffee. Fail to understand it? See Paranoia again.
Hypochondria? See all of the above.
In fact, it's clear that simply to attend such a major league shrink
convention is symptomatic of the need for immediate specialist treatment
and all the happiness capsules the pill-mongers can churn out.
Yet the headshrinkers were a nice bunch of folk, even if they did
occasionally give one measuring looks that might have been assessing the
straight-jacket fit.
</TEXT>
