<HEADLINE>Scots not laughing after comedy of errors. Torrance, Gallacher crash out</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255502</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SAM Torrance and Bernard Gallacher, two experienced Ryder Cup players,
appeared to be cruising towards victory in their third-round match in
the Sunningdale Foursomes event yesterday.
The Scots were three up with as many to play when the wheels rather
came off their cart in devastating fashion against Richard Walker, the
23-year-old Wearside professional, and Robert Goldie, a 30-year-old car
upholsterer.
The English pair came back from the dead to win the match at the
nineteenth hole over the Sunningdale Old Course to provide the upset of
the tournament. Goldie could hardly believe that his side had won, even
though he was the star of the dramatic finish.
At the fifteenth, Goldie knocked in a four-foot putt to keep the match
alive. ''We were three down and we thought it was just a matter of time
before we lost,'' he said. ''I just knocked in the putt and we all
laughed about it.''
But then Goldie holed a No.7 iron from 165 yards for an eagle 2 at the
next hole and the two Scots three-putted the seventeenth, where
Gallacher missed from three feet. Now the Ryder Cup men were just one
up.
Worse was to follow for Torrance and Gallacher, for at the eighteenth
they took four shots to get down from 20 yards to lose the hole to a
bogey 5 and the match then went down the nineteenth.
Even then it looked as if the Scottish pair would win, for Walker cut
his second shot out to the right, and Gallacher was only just off the
green. But Goldie, who said later: ''It was the match of his life,''
played a superb chip to two feet, Torrance chipped four feet short, and
Gallacher missed the putt, while Walker sank his. Scottish scores:
SECOND ROUND
Old Course -- K Stables (Montrose) and A Webster (Edzell) (+2) beat A
Good and R Summerscales (Foxhills) (+2), 1 hole; D King and T Craik
(Frilford Heath) (2) beat J Collier and C Stewart (Walton Heath) (scr),
1 hole.
New Course -- S Little (Moor Park) and G Clark (Pinner Hill) (scr)
beat J Farmer (New, St Andrews) and D Scott (Letham Grange) (+2), 5 and
4; D Craik and L Jackson (Frilford Heath) (+1) beat L Donald
(Beaconsfield) and M O'Connor (Stoke Poges) (scr), at 21st; S Torrance
(Selsdon Park) and B Gallacher (Wentworth) (+2) beat C Panton-Lewis
(Scottish Life) and S Moon (Cross Rent A Tipper) (4), 6 and 5.
THIRD ROUND
Stables and Webster (+2) beat G Smith (Camberley Heath) and W Riley
(PGA European Tour) (+2), 3 and 2; King and Craik (2) beat T Morrison
and C Challen (Stoke Poges) (+1), 2 and 1; Little and Clark (scr) beat
Craik and Jackson (+1), 4 and 2; R Walker and R Goldie (Wearside) (+1)
beat Gallacher and Torrance (+2), at 19th.
* BARRY Lane is hoping that a change of clubs will bring a change of
luck as he defends the Turespana Balearic Open title in Majorca this
week.
He was told by Taylor-Made recently that they were not renewing his
contract and he has switched to playing Mizuno irons. ''It came as a
shock considering I was their highest-ranking player and had been with
them for five years,'' said Lane.
The 34-year-old, fourteenth in the Ryder Cup points table, went to
South Africa to try to rediscover his form, but had to fly straight home
again when his father died.
Lane won by two strokes last year, but that was at Son Vida and the
#250,000 event could not return there because of problems with the
greens. Instead, it is being played at Santa Ponsa II, a new course for
the European circuit which, according to Mark James, has ''some of the
smallest greens in the world.''
Already this season, five players have picked up their first pro
title, the latest being Glasgow's Adam Hunter at last week's Portuguese
Open. Hunter probably would have stayed at home celebrating but for the
fact that the Tour, having lost the Extremadura Open, takes a
fortnight's break after this week.
''I hardly slept on Sunday night,'' he said. ''Not because I was
partying, but because my mind was in a spin. It meant so much to me
after waiting 11 years.''
</TEXT>
