<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Faldo out to add a little history</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBINSON HOLLOWAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>28</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255503</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS week's Players' Championship may have fair claim to the greatest
field ever gathered for a golf tournament. Last year's Open was missing
the two top Americans, Fred Couples and Paul Azinger, while the US PGA
Championship, the next contender, had to pad out its field with 40 club
pros.
The Players' Championship is inching toward legitimising its claim to
be the fifth major by inviting the top 36 ranked golfers in the world,
46 of the top 50 in total are here, with the best player not present
being Sam Torrance.
Nick Faldo said yesterday: ''From a field sense, this tournament's got
everything. It's had quite a good run now, and it's getting a bit of
history behind it. The majors have so much history behind them. Another
90 years and they'll be there.''
With all of the talent gathered this week, there are still two names
which stand out -- Peter Jacobsen and Faldo. Jacobsen leads Faldo on the
US money list by more than $200,000, the bulk of his winnings coming
from his last five starts, in which he picked up two wins, a second and
a third. Faldo's record has been as impressive over just the last three
weeks, in which he has had a win at Doral, a runner-up finish the next
week at Honda, and a fifth place last week at Bay Hill.
After three straight weeks of grinding and contending, Faldo left Bay
Hill saying that was going to take the three practice days easy, perhaps
playing just nine holes on Tuesday and Wednesday. Faldo instead was
refreshed enough from just a one-day holiday on Monday to complete an
undiminished practice schedule over the next two days.
Aside from fatigue, Faldo left Bay Hill needing to tweak his driving.
He had been playing with persimmon for the past two weeks, but will go
back to a metal wood for this event.
Driving is going to be more important this week than in the past at
this course. This year the rough has been allowed to grow high,
narrowing the fairways by several yards and encircling the greens. This
change has been viewed by many players as a reaction to Greg Norman's
blitz of the course last year. Not only did Norman's winning score of 24
under par break Nick Price's record of 18 under, but so did Fuzzy
Zoeller's 20 under runner-up performance.
</TEXT>
