<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Union Parliament should be consigned to history.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WALTER REID</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>OPEN FORUM</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979255505</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ON March 25, 1707, the old Scottish Parliament met for the last time,
to be replaced, as was the old English Parliament, by a new Parliament,
a British Parliament. Now, 288 years later, there seems to be a growing
consensus -- reflected, for example, in two recent Saturday essays in
this newspaper -- that it is time for Scotland to resume responsibility
for her own legislation.
If we are to understand why such a change may be necessary, and, which
is more important, to ensure that a new Scottish Parliament is
constructed to meet a real need, we should look at the role that the
Union Parliament was meant to play. We may then recognise that the
desire for change is not a narrow, party political one, but flows from a
generative change in the institutions of the state, and we may
understand better what the nature of a Scottish Parliament should be.
The eighteenth-century view of government was very different from
ours. About a hundred years later, poets and thinkers began to reflect
that ''The best government is that which governs least''. They did so
because they looked back from the hectic pace of the nineteenth century
to a more placid age, when the different elements in the constitution
stood in elegant equipoise, and government had the limited role that
Johnson recognised when he said: ''How small of all that human hearts
endure/That part which laws or kings can cause or cure.''
So although there may have been some popular and sentimental regret
when the Scots Parliament voted itself out of existence, and Lord
Chancellor Seafield said: ''There's an end of an auld sang'', what was
happening was hardly cataclysmic. Much -- indeed most -- of everyday
life was unaffected by Parliament. The critical elements of Scotland's
real identity were regarded as her Church and her legal system, and the
Treaty of Union specifically guaranteed their independence.
Lawyers' law -- indeed the law that touched the ordinary man -- was
not the child of statute, but the creation of the institutional writers
and the Roman jurists, interpreted by the courts. There was no income
tax in the 18th century; what the Act of Union was really about was
duties. In return for a harmonisation of tariffs and duties, the English
allowed Scots merchants access to trade with the colonies. This limited
bargain worked well for both sides. Lowland Scotland and the new
merchant classes prospered, and there were few, other than a hard core
of unreformed Jacobites, who regretted the Union.
But things changed quite soon after the turn of the century that had
created the Union. In 1803, income tax was introduced, and the cost of
the war with the French was only one consequence of the French
Revolution. Fear of revolutinary ideas gripped Parliament and found its
expression in repressive legislation. For the first time, the existence
of the Westminster Parliament began to have an impact on the Scottish
people. And that impact became all the greater as legislation was
generated to address the problems posed by the new phenomenon of an
increasingly industrial society.
The fine legislative torpor of the eighteenth century gave way to a
purposeful stream of enactments which swept through every aspect of
Scottish life, changing her public and private law beyond recognition.
What is interesting is that almost as soon as the function of the Union
began to change, Scots started to feel that government from Westminster
was ill-adapted to meet their needs.
By the 1880s, Home Rule was being vigorously advocated. The Scottish
Office was established in 1885 and the Office of Secretry of State,
which had appeared and disappeared through the eighteenth century, was
permanently re-established. But the growth of nationalism was not
checked, and as the nineteenth century drew to a close, Home Rule Bills
for Scotland and Ireland were introduced annually.
So, for its first hundred years, the Union Parliament did what it was
meant to, which is to say, very little. In its second century, it had
much more effect on every-day life and, by the end of that century,
there was an increasing and significant feeling that the Union did not
truly reflect Scotland's needs. Only in the present century has Scottish
opinion been required to come to terms with a Parliament that is no
longer satisfactory because it is not doing the job that it was designed
for. It's important, then, that we recognise that change is needed, not
for doctrinaire reasons, but to accord with the changing nature of the
times.
But we would do best to work on the basis of evolution and organic
growth, retaining those aspects of the Union that we can. In a recent
Saturday essay, Gavin Stamp said he would prefer an ongoing relationship
with the rest of the United Kingdom. If this were achieved in a federal
context, such a move would be consistent with the principles of 1707;
Scots should have no great difficulty in contemplating federalism.
In 1707, both the Scots and English Parliaments came to an end, and
were replaced by the new British Parliament. England never remembers
this fact, but Scotland does. We know, as the English forget, that we
surrendered a measure of sovereignty for good, practical reasons, and so
we don't get into a lather about surrendering a degree of sovereignty to
Europe. Indeed, many might be happier to be an influential component of
a European Parliament than a minor partner in a London one. That would
be a situation that would have appealed to the pragmatic Scots of 1707.
</TEXT>
