<HEADLINE>Gastronomic jewel</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL MCLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255506</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KILLERMONT Polo Club, one of Scotland's most stylish Indian
restaurants set in landscaped grounds at 2002 Maryhill Road, close to
the Bearsden border, continues to enjoy well-deserved favour on the good
food front. A runaway award winner celebrating its second year in the
prestigious Good Food Guide, the city's not too far pavilion is fully
operational after minor refurbishment to the entrance hall. For
aficionados of the spicy specialities of the great sub-continent adapted
to contemporary taste all roads lead to this mid nineteenth-century
former manse with its Trophy, Club and Polo rooms open for business
seven days a week.
The Trophy Room, seating 20, is an intimate enclave ideal for small
receptions and private dinner parties, while the Polo Room, seating 50,
is the perfect spot for splashing out in the grand manner. The Club
Room, seating 30, epitomises the days of the Raj with its wood
panelling, period photographs and polo paraphenalia making it a popular
West End watering hole.
In a relatively short space of time brothers Cal and Pami Dhaliwal
have revolutionised the eating out scene in the West of Scotland and
beyond as far as Indian food is concerned. Great care is taken in the
preparation of all dishes and their presentation is an eye-catching
delight. From home-made chutneys to custom-grafted sweets there is
something for everyone on the well-balanced menu at moderate cost for an
establishment of Polo Club quality. Tamarind and carrot chutney is
becoming a favourite with regular customers and spiced duck with cabbage
and potatoes was a recent hit on the #9.95 Sunday to Tuesday Gourmet
Buffet carte.
Prawns in coconut milk and bananas in spiced yoghurt have featured on
buffet nights but tops with seafood fanciers are the mussels
Goanese-style on the a-la-carte and lunchtime menus. Lemon rice with
cashew nuts adds an exotic touch to main course munching and chicken
done in several different ways is always well requested. Indian lager
from the Laltoofan brewery makes a perfectaccompaniment.
A sense of occasion and value for money go hand in hand at the
Killermont Polo Club. Parking presents no problem but it is essential to
book at weekends. The restaurant must be unique -- it does have a polo
team attached!
</TEXT>
