<HEADLINE>Roger Sinha/Cas Public, Tramway, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MARY BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255507</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Dance
INTENSE, inventive, individual -- just three of the many celebratory
adjectives one could pin on the work shown by Canadian choreographers
Roger Sinha and Helene Blackburn.
Burning Skin, a solo made and performed by Sinha, is an astute brew of
images reflecting his own antecedents -- Armenian mother, Indian father
-- and the racist confrontations thus engendered. His text is taken from
Hanif Krueishi's Rainbow Sign but the dance and the brilliant
theatricality are very much his own.
He cleverly juxtaposes cogent symbols and dance styles from Eastern
and Western cultures. Garbed in flowing robes, he takes tea -- to the
elegant strains of the Blue Danube, synchronising his sipping as if at
some consular high tiffin. The next moment, he is whirling and kicking
in an intricate amalgam of contemporary movements and classical Indian
dance -- a kind of electro-Natyam, where traditional delicate hand
gestures are powered by a pounding modern beat and offset by
freewheeling contemporary footwork.
It's immediately exciting to watch, stumulating to reflect on
afterwards, because of the way Sinha evokes the blistering realities of
racial prejudice.
Helene Blackburn's company, Cas Public, showed two different pieces on
separate nights, one a work in progress. Both radiated a sense of
heightened ritual, a mantra-like use of reiterated motion leading to a
state of ecstatic entrancement that was both powerful and affecting.
On one level it's a meticulous pursuit of movement. Setting up a
phrase, like the on-the-edge rocking step in Bestaire, then letting it
gather unpredictable strengths through repetition, through being shared
by other dancers. But even as this technical exploration acquires its
own momentum, it's creating poetic images that are resonant with echoes
of spirituality, dedication, passion.
In Bestaire it's as if one was peeping into the life of some isolated,
closed religious sect. A group of people clustering together, supporting
one another through tiny shared gestures. These elements are being taken
further in Blackburn's current project, provisionally titled,
Kammermusik. It, too, is resplendent with taut energies, sharp
idiosyncratic steps, and above all a glorious sense of bodies being
speaking vessels for deep-felt beliefs.
No wonder New Moves Across Europe extended its remit across the
Atlantic: Canadian dance really leaves one speechless with admiration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
