<HEADLINE>Brindisi Quartet, Royal College of Physicians, Edinburgh</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CONRAD WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>REVIEW</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255508</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Music
WITH playing of this sort, and of the Vellinger Quartet's sort a week
ago, chamber music in Britain seems in better shape than is the country
as a whole.
In last night's programme of Beethoven, Schubert, and Frank Bridge,
promoted by the Young Musicians' Trust, nothing was shirked,
undervalued, or left to chance. Bridge's Three Idylls, far from seeming
to belong to some musical backwater of the early 1900s, brimmed with a
poetry which never became wishy-washy, and which showed exactly why the
young Benjamin Britten sought to be Bridge's pupil.
Lovingly articulated, the pieces sounded at times like Elgar with a
twist of something else, and proved that they no more deserved their
neglect than Beethoven's so-called Harp quartet deserved to lag behind
his others in general esteem.
But then -- though the performance did not suggest it -- it is a
treacherous work to play, though filled with rewards for those who can
generate the increasing momentum of the first movement and can cope with
the flurry of the scherzo.
The Brindisi Quartet did so yet held enough in reserve for Schubert's
great C major string quintet, in which they were joined by Charles
Tunnell as second cellist for a performance rich and robust in sonority
but with the plaintive sweetness the music also requires.
</TEXT>
