<HEADLINE>At last there's an end to the agony</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH WESTCOTT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255509</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The compelling healing potential of chiropractic has taken it out of
the realms of quackery and, as Elizabeth Westcott explains, there is now
no need to take back pain lying down
THIS year back pain will cost the nation more than #3000m in lost
production. Disability due to back pain has increased dramatically over
the past three decades, but the awareness of treatments available has
not. Legions of back pain sufferers will tread the dreary rituals of
visits to their general practitioner, prescriptions of painkillers,
anti-inflammatories, and the unavoidable bed rest, all in the belief
that there is no real cure for back pain.
What they don't realise is that chiropractic, the fastest growing
complementary medical therapy in the UK, could alleviate their symptoms
in the space of a few visits -- without drugs or surgery.
Chiropractors specialise in disorders of the spine, joints, and
muscles. Meaning literally ''done by hand'', chiropractors use
manipulations gently to unlock stiff joints. After one or a number of
treatments proper movement is restored. Chiropractic is generally found
to be a remarkably effective therapy, as one patient, James Smith, can
testify.
Smith was suffering from cervical spondylitis, a common condition
which gradually immobilised his neck over a period of two years. Unlike
many chronic pain sufferers he didn't ignore his problem; he sought help
from his GP and eventually from physiotherapists but nothing eased his
discomfort until he consulted a chiropractor.
''I was in extreme pain,'' he said. ''I couldn't move my neck at all,
it was just impossible. My doctor said there wasn't a cure for my neck.
I wanted to have an X-ray, but my doctor said there wasn't any point.
His exact words were: 'Your neck's knackered.'
''Then I went to see the physiotherapists and I was going for about
three months. They gave me some exercises to do but in the end they gave
me up as a bad job. They said there was nothing they could do for my
neck.''
Feeling desperate, Smith took a friend's advice and visited a
chiropractor.
''It wasn't until then that I found any relief at all. It took a while
-- I was seeing the chiropractor twice a week at first -- but after
about a month I could really feel the difference.''
The improvement in James Smith's case was striking. His ability to
rotate his neck increased from only 10 degrees on his first visit to 65
degrees and the pain disappeared. He wouldn't hesitate to recommend
chiropractic to anyone.
Another patient, Annie Coorey, found chiropractic could alleviate the
pain she was experiencing in her lower back after traditional medicine
failed.
''I had terrible backache while I was pregnant and after my daughter
was born,'' she said. ''Twelve weeks into my pregnancy I had to wear a
brace and after 22 weeks I left work. A friend told me about the
chiropractor so I came to see her, and within a month or so I had total
relief. It was really quite good by the time I got pregnant again. I'm
now pain-free most of the time, but I was really in agony before I came.
''I've recommended chiropractic to my postman, who gets terrible
backache from bending over all the time.''
Other back pain sufferers could experience similar relief if they
didn't adopt a ''wait and see'' approach, according to Glasgow
chiropractor Dr Ian Dingwall.
''Back pain hasn't changed but the disability due to back pain has,''
he said. ''It's very common to get patients who have had back pain for a
long time and have never had their backs examined. It's crazy -- it's
like treating toothache with painkillers for years and never having your
teeth assessed by a dentist.''
Painkillers may reduce pain in the short term but the underlying
problem will not magically vanish. If anything, it will probably worsen,
says Dr Dingwall.
''If a sportsperson with hamstring damage is given painkillers the
pain will go. But without proper rehabilitation once back on the track
there's going to be all sorts of problems.
''People with back pain say 'I'll learn to live with it' because they
don't realise they have any other option.''
* SCOTTISH back pain sufferers don't know what's good for them.
Chiropractic may be the third largest health care profession in the
world (after medicine and dentistry) but few people in Scotland are
aware of chiropractic therapy and what it can offer, according to Dr
Bradon Keil, spokesperson for the Scottish Chiropractic Association.
''Awareness of chiropractic here is very low,'' he said. ''We would be
lucky if one-tenth of those questioned even knew what it was. We've
still got people booking in for their feet to be done. The increasing
number of practitioners is improving matters but there still needs to be
a lot of PR work.''
When Dr Keil first arrived in Scotland four years ago there were only
16 chiropractors. Now there are over 30 and despite the lack of common
knowledge concerning chiropractic, news of their practices spread
swiftly, usually by word of mouth.
Dr Keil predicts a rapid chiropractic expansion in Scotland over the
next decade. ''Scotland has the same population as the state of Victoria
in Australia where they have 700 chiropractors. Another two or three
hundred here wouldn't go astray.
''People with back pain are suffering needlessly. The standard
recommendation is still bed rest, which has been shown to be
detrimental. After two or three days of bed rest there are no more
benefits, and more than that can actually increase the side effects of
back pain.''
Dr Keil referred to the Clinical Standards Advisory Report which
states that traditional medical treatment has failed to halt the
epidemic of back pain and may even have contributed to it.
''There is an epidemic of back pain in the Western world,'' he said.
Elsewhere in the Western world chiropractic is a commonplace therapy
and Britain is finally catching on. It has come a long way since the
sixties, when it was generally deemed to be an ''unscientific cult'' by
the medical establishment. Last year the Chiropractors' Act was passed,
ensuring that only those registered and qualified could use the title
''chiropractor''. This legitimisation is a landmark for the profession
and marks a new openness towards non-established therapies in the UK.
Chiropractic's compelling potential for healing has dragged it from
the realms of quackery and towards mainstream medicine. As it continues
to gain recognition, no doubt Scotland's thousands of back pain
sufferers will benefit from what is proving to be the most convincing
solution to back pain ever.
BACK FACTS
* Twelve million adults suffer from chronic (over three months) back
pain
* Sixteen million adults have recently suffered back pain
* Eighty per cent of people will at some point suffer from back pain
* Ten per cent of people have suffered back pain for more than 10
years
* Eighty per cent of sufferers believe it is something they have to
learn to live with
* Sixty million working days are lost each year through back pain
* Back pain is second only to bronchitis as a cause of lost working
days
* Two hundred and thirty thousand people are off work every day with
back pain
* Since 1971 there has been a 230% increase in days lost from work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
