<HEADLINE>Man sacked after West claims</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255510</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SOCIAL worker who offered to sell information about the children of
the alleged mass murderer, Mrs Rosemary West, was yesterday sacked from
his job.
Mr Errol Brown, 31, was dismissed by Gloucestershire County Council
after a disciplinary hearing in Gloucester.
He was suspended earlier this month after asking the Gloucester
Citizen for around #10,000, claiming he had information about the five
younger children of Mrs West, 41, and her late husband, Frederick, 53.
The newspaper had two meetings with Mr Brown, from the Forest of Dean,
before reporting him to the council.
Mr Brown later said his approach was a stunt for Comic Relief which
had gone wrong. He claimed he intended to give any money to charity.
Miss Anne Marshall, the council's press officer, said after the
hearing that Mr Brown had no knowledge of the children, had never met
them or worked with them, and did not have access to any confidential
records, which were strictly controlled.
She revealed that he had approached the newspaper offering, for the
price of a new car, to tell it where the West children were being looked
after.
Miss Marshall added: ''All those who have worked with this family have
strived to protect the children from publicity in order to help them
build new lives.
''Both the High Court and the Department of Health have complimented
the department on the efforts made to act in the best interests of the
childen and the care we have provided for them.
''Staff involved in this case are dedicated to the well-being of the
chldren.''
Mrs West, of 25 Cromwell Street, Gloucester, has been committed for
trial at Winchester Crown Court in the autumn.
She stands accused of 10 murders, including that of her stepdaughter
Charmaine, eight, and daughter Heather, 16.
Mrs West is also accused on four other charges alleging rape and
indecent assault. These were said to have been carried out jointly with
her husband, who was found hanged in his remand cell in Winsom Green
Prison, Birmingham, on January 1.
</TEXT>
