<HEADLINE>Hell mend the other woman scorned</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICOLA REEVES</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255513</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MARY ELLEN SYNON, the woman dubbed ''The Bonk of England'', has
seemingly got what she wanted, namely the resignation of Rupert
Pennant-Rea, deputy governor of the Bank of England. He will undoubtedly
be feeling very sorry for himself with no job and added strain in his
third marriage to Helen Jay, sister of Peter Jay the BBC's economic
editor.
One of my colleagues, who saw Pennant-Rea in the midst of the
negotiations to save Barings merchant bank, remarked on how tired he was
looking. We assumed this was because of his efforts to save a major City
institution, but perhaps now we know the real reason.
While Pennant-Rea comes out of this episode looking foolish and
irresponsible at best, it is the actions of Synon that I find
despicable. There is something rather cheap and nasty in her recent
conduct. Although she professes to love Pennant-Rea, there is something
premeditated and distasteful in keeping his love letters with their
date-marked envelopes and a photocopy of a cheque he sent her to cover a
flight to America.
The adage ''hell hath no fury'' seems more than appropriate given her
recent disclosures. These include a claim that when she had once
previously threatened to reveal publicly details of their affair, he had
attempted suicide and had climbed on to the railway line at Clapham
Junction in south-west London, before changing his mind.
One is left with a feeling that it serves her right. Much the same can
and has been said about Sandra Hughes, now wife of Robert Hughes who
also recently tendered his resignation, as junior Citizen's Charter
Minister, after admitting an extra-marital affair. At the time they met
and began their affair, Hughes, elected to the Greater London Council in
1980 as Tory member for Croydon Central, was a 28-year-old father,
married for the first time.
These women have been ''the other woman'' and now find the tables have
been turned on them. They are getting a taste of their own medicine,
and, perhaps not surprisingly, do not like it. I am not sure why Synon,
who presumably, given her journalistic career to date, sounds like an
intelligent woman, expected her relationship with Pennant-Rea to be any
different to his previous ones.
Although I do not know (or wish to) the circumstances surrounding the
breakdown of his previous marriages, at the age of 47 he is already on
his third wife. This to me does not signify a particularly committed
nature when it comes to his relationships with women. In any case, from
what I have heard so far of Synon, I would say that Pennant-Rea is well
rid of her.
Still, he can console himself with the fact that he is not alone in
his plight but joins an ever growing list of eminent men who have felt
it necessary to resign because of affairs. Most, but not all, have been
politicians. Two weeks ago Hughes resigned as Citizen's Charter
Minister. Before him, senior defence chief Sir Peter Harding had little
choice but to leave his job when his affair with the then Bienvenida
Sokolow formerly Lady Buck -- wife of Tory MP Sir Antony Buck -- was
revealed last March.
Lady Thatcher's successor as MP for Finchley, Hartley Booth, got no
further than the first rung of the ministerial ladder before he was
forced to resign last February as a junior aide after revelations of his
''innocent'' liaison with House of Commons secretary Emily Barr.
A MONTH earlier Tim Yeo, the Environment Minister, was pushed from
office after admitting fathering a child with Tory councillor Julia
Stent. Shipping Minister Lord Caithness also resigned in January 1994 in
the immediate aftermath of his wife's suicide. The elderly parents of
Lady Caithness later blamed the Earl's relationship with former royal
secretary Jan Fitzalan-Howard for their daughter's depression.
So far Steve Norris, Minister of Transport, has refused to stand down
despite revelations of not just one affair but five, with different
mistresses, in 1993. Some men in the middle years of their life feel the
need to prove their virility and desirability by taking a mistress often
young enough to be their daughter. One thinks of the memorable
''five-times a night'' Ralph Halpern, a former chief executive of the
Burton retail group.
However, in this case there was no such young bimbo. Given her
occupation as a journalist and her age of 44 years, one would have
expected American-born Synon to be a little less naive. What amazes me
is that so many people in supposedly demanding jobs in the public eye
find the time and energy for such potentially dangerous liaisons. What,
with this latest sexual scandal and the recent collapse of Barings
merchant bank, triggered by huge trading losses incurred by Nick Leeson,
who needs to go to the cinema, read Jilly Cooper or Jackie Collins
novels for entertainment when they can just open their newspaper.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>High standard set for living and leisure</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255514</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT might be a great place for business and communications, but
Motherwell District also claims to hold a few trump cards when it comes
to choosing a place to live.
The selection of quality housing, in both the public and private
sector, has never been better. Neither has the choice of leisure,
sporting, and entertainment activities.
This pocket of Scotland caters for everyone's taste, whether it is in
outdoor or indoor pursuits, or sitting back to see some of the biggest
names in arts, sports and entertainment. Swimming, rambling, canoeing,
skating, bowling, yachting, sub-aqua, and athletic activities are
available and the magnificent concert hall and theatre complex at the
Civic Centre regularly draws top stars from TV, theatre, and the music
scene.
One of Motherwell District's biggest assets is, of course, the Clyde
Valley: there are few areas more scenic when it comes to leisurely walks
or a country drive. The river also borders the magnificent Strathclyde
Country Park, flowing into its 200-acre artificial loch and providing an
ideal environment for a wide range of water-based activities.
The lake was the venue for the 1986 Commonwealth Games rowing events
and the park features a caravan and camping site, fun park, sandy
beaches, nature reserve, jogging tracks, and picnic and play areas.
As for sporting facilities, the Sir Matt Busby Sports Complex in
Belshill has a 25-metre pool, an outdoor synthetic sports pitch, and a
health suite. A sports hall is also being constructed at the complex.
A new pool being built as an extension to Wishaw Sports Centre, which
was opened in 1982 and is the district's major sporting complex, will
also be 25 metres long. The eight-lane all-weather athletics track there
has been used regularly by international athletes such as Tom McKean and
Yvonne Murray, and the latter continues to use the facility regularly as
an active member of the Motherwell Lucozade Athletics Club.
An outdoor all-weather tennis-court complex is also being built at the
centre.
The council opened a state-of-the-art leisure complex at Shotts in
1990, having introduced the jewel in its crown, the Aquatec, in
Motherwell only a year earlier. This water and ice-based complex
continues to draw visitors from near and far, with the longest
wild-water channel in Scotland, water cannons, a flume, waterfall and
outdoor hot spring among the attractions of its leisure pool.
The other half of the building is given over to a free-form ice rink
complete with laser lights, Alpine trails, and ice cavern. A hi-tech
conditioning gym has also recently been opened.
Chief Executive John Bonomy considers that a district which has a bird
sanctuary only half a mile from its civic centre -- Barons Haugh Nature
Reserve, owned by the RSPB and adjoining Dalzell Country Park -- has to
be something special. ''You don't normally have such wildlife riches so
close to an urban environment,'' he says.
In all there are 3000 acres of parks in Motherwell District and five
golf courses cater for those with a purpose in their walk. Cultural
attractions are frequent at the concert hall and theatre, which houses
art exhibitions as well as performance art, and a purpose-built cultural
centre at Bellshill has facilities for plays, musicals, dance and a
multi-purpose room suitable for exhibitions, seminars and workshops.
An award-winning Arts Service offers a wide range of participative
arts and cultural activities.
The district is also building a #3.7m Heritage Centre in Motherwell
which will feature many innovative displays and exhibitions recording
the area's history from earliest times to the robust days of the iron,
steel and coal industries, and on to modern times. A smaller centre is
also based in Shotts.
Motherwell Football Club offers Premier League action. And all the
leisure, sporting and cultural attractions of Glasgow and Edinburgh are
a short distance away.
It's a central location. That is a large part of its attraction.
</TEXT>
