<HEADLINE>Thinking again on Pacific Quay</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255515</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PERHAPS I am not alone amongst your readership who skips lightly
through Scotland's Business but the headline above Stewart McIntosh's
article may well be prophetic: Oceans rise up against each other to turn
tide of tenants (March 16).
Even those with the shortest memories among potential developers,
builders, insurers, and tenants viewing the Pacific Quay project in
Glasgow might think again.
The Atlantic Ocean, and the Rivers Clyde and Kelvin, have already
spoiled the equanimity of the infilled dock area on the north bank, and
they may well wonder what will safeguard their properties in the old
southern docks.
The apparently solid blocks of river wharfage have stood for over 100
years but the flimsy Bell's Bridge appears to have revealed that the
waters have continued to erode the hard core behind.
The silt continues to accumulate and elevate the flood tide of sea and
spate of rivers, so what price the computer ''super highways'' of the
future to those edifices on Atlantic Quay?
Whatever the best laid plans of Glasgow's ''movers and shakers'', they
would do well to acknowledge that the land, the rivers, and the oceans
have but one Maker. Man may well make modifications but if these are not
maintained into the future they will soon revert to nature.
You published a letter from Geoffrey Jarvis, subscribed by many
concerned and authoritative persons in our community, advocating a
careful examination of the whole aspect of Glasgow's river frontage. It
is surprising how many assets are already there which could, with viable
and economic adaption, be rescued from dereliction.
Whatever form that authority might take, I would suggest the priority
is to get the river right; and then take a walk around the Govan
Heritage Trail with the excellent guidebook in hand so that late
twentieth-century persons might get the proper perspective of the making
of Glasgow.
Ian H. Grant,
1 Hillend Road,
Burnside,
Rutherglen.
</TEXT>
