<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Guinea-pigs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255516</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is a dreadful indication of the degree to which we have become
habituated to cynicism, duplicity, and dishonesty in public life that
when Scotland's leading national newspaper publishes a report detailing
a previous Government's complicity in deliberately causing physical harm
to 22,000 British Servicemen used as human guinea-pigs in experiments
with H-bombs this is relegated to page three (March 20).
This horrendous crime is not even noted on TV or radio, there is no
public outcry, and we all continue to entrust our fate to the
powers-that-be.
Are we expected to believe that those who live by the nuclear gospel
have somehow mended their ways and would never dream of committing such
an atrocity again.?
Or is it the case that we should simply accept the logical fact that
those who support the mass slaughter of innocent civilians as a
permitted means to their desired end cannot be expected to have any
qualms about the lesser crimes of killing soldiers, devastating the
environment, lying to the public, deceiving Parliament, and threatening
the lives of all of us?
Brian Quail,
Joint Secretary,
Scottish Campaign for
Nuclear Disarmament,
15 Barrland Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
