<DOCNO>GH950323-000089</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000089</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Funding levels in education</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255517</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BARCLAY McBain's report, Dismay as funding levels confirm education
fears (March 17), makes very depressing reading. The fact that the
majority of academic institutions in Scotland will have substantially
less resources than last year but will have to cope with additional
students underlines the Government's parsimonious attitude towards
education.
The present policy will ensure that students, with ever-increasing
levels of debt, can expect to receive from the academic institutions
even less in terms of teaching and other resources than they did this
year.
The Government's doctrine of cost-effective education is based on the
flawed philosophy that the less each student receives in terms of
resources the more cost-effective the education system is judged to be.
Is this what parents want for their children or what our young people
are entitled to expect from the Scottish education system?
Thomas L Inglis,
7 Menzies Avenue,
Fintry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000090</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000090</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wait for Paradise</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255518</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I read Mr Penney's letter with great sadness (March 18). I can excuse
his ignorance of journalistic procedures (I did not choose the headline
for my original letter) but I have to struggle a bit to be gracious in
the face of his hubristic description of me as a poisoner; that seems to
go beyond the bounds of an honest difference of opinion.
Such a pity, too, that his student days were a hard slog; mine were a
joyful confirmation of vocation, but then I was preparing for
ordination, not for a career in the ''business'', whatever he might be
trying to convey by the usage.
Since all we seem to have in common is weariness with each other
(although I am willing to be weary with a brother in Christ), perhaps
this correspondence should end now.
Let's leave things where they are for now and agree to discuss them in
Paradise. Unless God, having consulted Mr Penney, as it appears He
surely will, takes his advice and doesn't let me in!
Rev John Young,
51 Cromarty Road,
Airdrie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>High Dunoon for the magnificent seven</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM SHIELDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>TOM SHIELDS DIARY</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255519</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WE hear of a sudden outbreak of the democratic process in Dunoon where
one of the seats is being contested by no fewer than seven candidates in
the elections for the new shadow-of-their-former-selves councils. By
contrast another Cowal seat for the Argyll and Bute Council is
unopposed.
The SNP has opened the war of the hustings by issuing a ''public
warning'' leaflet about the ''Tory menace'' of voting for candidates who
stand under the label Independent but are actually Conservatives.
This will no doubt be firmly denied by Councillor Scott McClure who is
standing as an Independent despite being on the Tory short-leet of six
last time round for the Argyll and Bute parliamentary seat.
Mr McClure is a publican in Dunoon and given that Raith Rovers have
been elevated almost to cult status in his bar since the Coca-Cola Cup
final it appears that he is not canvassing any Tim vote that may exist
in his ward.
Two Cowal publicans are standing for election this time around, giving
some weight to the opinion held locally that being an elected member is
no hindrance when it comes to licensing matters.
Even better, in Campbeltown we have a candidate standing against the
leader of the council on a platform of ''Legalise cannabis and bring
back hanging''. Great to see that a return to one-tier local government
has maintained the tradition of multi-tiered local politics.
The Name Game
EDINBURGH Healthcare NHS Trust's ''Vasectomy Secretary'' is one Joan
Dix. The Green Party candidate in the election for the Battlefield ward
of the Glasgow City Council is a Brian Chislett, who is a joiner to
trade.
Siberian insult
WE hear from another Diary foreign correspondent, Howard Tindall. The
last time we heard from Howard, a former economist with the Bank of
Scotland, was when he was in Ulan Bator complaining about the food at a
Burns Supper. (If you must have the full details, get a back number of
The Herald for March 31 last year.)
Howard is now working in a bank in Kazakhstan, assisting the former
Soviet colony in its transition to a free-market economy. To help him
achieve this, he has been issued with one of these personal hand-held
computer notebooks.
He was drafting a letter home when the spellcheck queried his
reference to Glasgow. It suggested ''Gulag'' as an alternative.
Concerned that his PC was suggesting that there was a touch of the Ivan
Denisovich about Glasgow's post-war housing schemes, he looked up
Edinburgh. And drew a blank, not even an insult.
If the cap fits
THE Labour Party is on tour with an event called the Rambling Rose
Roadshow. As part of the hype and glitz, representatives of the People's
Party will be wearing baseball caps (made in the People's Republic of
China) adorned with roses. The baseball cap is an article of clothing
which must have fond memories for those of a Labour persuasion: notable
previous wearers include Robert Maxwell and Arthur Scargill.
Cruise control
A CONFERENCE on ''Issues and Crisis Management'' in London next month
will be addressed by a chap from Cunard Line, the people who had a bit
of a problem recently with their boat, the QE2.
The talk is entitled ''If you're the Queen and your slip shows, you've
had it!'' We are sure it will be a paradigmatic exposition on crisis
management. Even if the man delivering it, Cunard's PR supremo, rejoices
in the unconvincing name of Eric Flounders.
Well-travelled
A NICE bit of non-synchronous film and commentary from the BBC news
during HRH's visit to South Africa. We see the royal yacht Britannia
steaming into harbour. The reporter is observing what a fine old ship
she is. Unfortunately by the time we get to the words: ''Over one
million miles on the clock and still in service'' the cameras were
giving us a close-up of the Queen Herself.
By the left
A Diary correspondent, recently returned from France, tells us that
Jil, the French underwear company, has just launched the first-ever
range of left-handed Y-fronts. ''Forget scissors, potato-peelers and the
like,'' enthused one reviewer, ''these have to be the greatest boon to
the male southpaw yet.''
We admit to being confused, and somewhat alarmed, by the stuff about
scissors and potato-peelers but were pleased to be told it was nothing
to do with any handling of the contents of the Y-fronts. Merely a
reference to other artefacts which have been redesigned to help the
corrie-fisted.
Faller at first fence
DEPT of Appropriate Venues: Glasgow Hillhead SNP Association is
holding a race night at the Multicultural Centre on Rose Street.
Timely reminders of knowing not the hoor
EXAMPLES continue to surface of colourful demotic language on the
theme of passage of time. Bill Maclaughlan of Kilburnie remembers his
granny saying: ''Eight o'clock and no' a heid looked or a po' timmed.''
''Look at ma hair -- it's like a hoor's handbag,'' was another of her
favourites.
George MacDougall of Sandyhills recalls: ''Eight o'clock and no' a
dish washed or a heid looked.'' A chap of Leith descent heard at his
granny's knee: ''Eleven o'clock, not a piss-pot emptied, not a hoor
dressed, and the French fleet in port.''
Rhona J Young of Old Kilpatrick contributes a farming version from
Stirlingshire where the men would be greeted of a Monday morning with:
''Hash on, boys. The day's but a blink and the rain's at Buchlyvie. The
day after the morn's Wednesday and no' a stroke o' work done yet.''
Jean Taylor of Brookfield, Johnstone brings the hale thing up to date
with: ''It's 9.30am and not a fax received or a call on my mobile
phone.''
</TEXT>
