<DOCNO>GH950323-000092</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000092</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Land-value taxation</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255520</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SIR Hector Monro asserted in the Commons that it is not the ownership
of land that matters but how it is managed (March 16).
While it is entirely predictable that he should try to defend the
privileges of the landed minority, this is still an enigmatic statement
from a Minister whose Government has publicly renounced responsibility
for land management through its espousal of the ''voluntary principle'',
despite severe condemnation of upland land-use practices in recent
publications by its own agency, Scottish Natural Heritage.
By contrast, what clear vision was shown at the same debate by Calum
MacDonald in his call for a tax on land values. In capturing the full
annual economic rent for the Exchequer this would indeed destroy the
speculative value of land by cancelling out the financial advantage of
mere ownership.
The landowner, as distinct from the land-user, is a purely negative
element of the economic equation as he provides nothing, yet demands
payment for the use of what is already there. His status as such
deserves no protection.
How appropriate that the demand for land value taxation should come
from the MP for the Western Isles where, far removed from Westminster,
communities have retained an awareness of their relationship with the
land and the way this has been distorted by the system of landlordism
imposed on them from outside.
Although last week's debate was about the future of wild land, it is
to be hoped that Calum MacDonald's parliamentary colleagues will
recognise the significance of land value taxation applied universally to
all land and the admirable way it would fit into the ideology of the
new-look Labour Party.
With assessment based on annual market rental values excluding
buildings and other improvements, and taking into account planning and
environmental restrictions on development, it would automatically
penalise the owners of idle or under-used land and so stimulate optimum
permitted land-use, rural or urban.
Crucially, as an alternative rather than additional source of revenue
to the Exchequer, land value taxation would provide the Government with
the means to free the economy from the stifling effect of penal taxation
on production and consumption.
Unpopular and counter-productive taxes such as income tax and VAT
could be slashed to a degree undreamed of by politicans blinkered by
conventional economic dogma.
While Sir Hector Monro may not choose to admit that the issue of
land-use is inseparable from that of landownership, the ignominious end
to the Government he represents is surely now in sight.
Tomorrow's politicians must acknowledge that land monopoly is at the
root of social injustice and economic security, and must be prepared to
tackle the issue head on.
John Digney,
Creagmhor Lodge,
Lochard Road,
Aberfoyle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bank gets rid of 1750 in bad day for job losses</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CAMERON SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255521</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MORE than 2000 workers yesterday experienced the real meaning of the
dearth of the economic feelgood factor identified by Chancellor Kenneth
Clarke when they were told they were to lose their jobs.
Midland Bank announced that 1745 jobs would go as part of a shake-up
aimed at focusing on ''communuity banking''; 320 pie-factory jobs are to
go in Stoke-on-Trent; Dalepak Foods is axing 75 jobs at its Hull
factory; and 50 textile jobs are to be lost in Dundee.
The jobs haemorrhage was compounded last night when one of Britain's
richest families -- the Vesteys -- saw Dewhurst, their main UK food
trading company, fall into administrative receivership, putting
thousands of jobs at risk. To complete the economic gloom, the
Government is planning to privatise engineering work at its GCHQ
communications centre, threatening 400 jobs.
The Midland Bank, part of the huge HSBC group, said most of its
regional business banking centres were to be integrated into branches.
It would be moving a number of senior managers with increased
authority into its branch network.
''These changes will result in the loss of 1745 jobs across the
country. However, where possible, the job losses will be achieved
through natural staff turnover, early retirement, redeployment, and
voluntnary redundancy.''
The bank has a small presence in Scotland, with offices in Glasgow,
Edinburgh, and Aberdeen. A spokesman said the number of job losses there
would be ''small if any''.
The Banking, Insurance, and Finance union claimed there would be more
than 2000 job losses as part of two separate job shedding programmes.
The union, which fears there will be a number of compulsory
redundancies, attacked the Midland for the scale of the cutback so soon
after the bank made profits of #905m.
Bifu said the number of jobs lost or at immediate risk in the finance
industry over the past five years had risen to 150,000. A total of
115,000 jobs have been axed and a further 35,000 are at risk this year,
according to a union analysis.
The number of jobs lost in banking fell from 17,500 in 1993 to 14,000
last year. However, a further 10,000 banking jobs have been targeted
this year and workers at building societies are threatened with
redundancy because of mergers.
''There is no feelgood factor in finance in spite of bumper profits,''
said Bifu's deputy general secretary, Mr Ed Sweeney.
In Dundee, two factories manufacturing man-made fibres have been the
subject of a management buy-out. The 50 redundancies are being made as
part of a restructuring plan by the new owners.
The factories, previously owned by the Sidlaw Group plc, will now
operate as New South Mills Ltd. About 270 workers were employed at the
two face-yarn operations, which produced man-made fibres mainly used for
carpets.
Mr Graham Scott, managing director of New South Mills Ltd, said: ''The
market has been very low for the past year. This is restructuring the
operation to what the market forces are now.''
Mr Colin Coupar, district secretary of the Transport and General
Workers' union, said: ''I will be negotiating the options and I think we
will be able to reduce the numbers involved.''
Trentham Bakeries, in Stoke-on-Trent, will close at the end of August.
The company, owned by the Northern Foods group, blamed the decision on a
shortage of demand for its pies.
The jobs going at Dalepak Foods in Hull are due to the transfer of
production of Ross meat products to its plant at Northallerton, North
Yorkshire.
At GCHQ, a spokesman said it was impossible to say how many
engineering jobs would be lost under the privatisation exercise. The
centre blamed falling workload for the decision but the Government has
been keen to cut back its Civil Service budget.
Dewhurst details in Scotland's Business
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Glass blowing operation to close</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RON MACKENNA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255522</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CAITHNESS Glass is to end manufacturing in Oban after 25 years.
Four jobs will be lost when the company, which produces paperweights
and other glass products, closes its glass-blowing operations at the end
of September.
Mr David Maxwell, the firm's manufacturing director, said Caithness
Glass would retain its retail shop in Oban's waterfront development.
''We have got to become more efficient and we will be consolidating
all our production in Wick and Perth.''
Mr Maxwell said only two employees would lose their jobs. ''The two
glass makers have been offered positions in Wick or Perth.''
Mr David Webster, president of Oban Chamber of Commerce, said
manufacturing had been stopped because it was no longer necessary to
pull in tourists.
''When the company were at Lochavuillin Industrial Estate, they needed
manufacturing to get people to visit the shop.
''They have recently moved to the waterfront development and don't
need glass making to attract people, so they are just ditching it.''
Mr Webster said the firm's decision also would hit the viability of
the recently-opened waterfront development.
''The exhibition centre has been closed down and the restaurant. All
that will be left when the glassworks close is a wool shop and a glass
shop.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000095</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000095</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Strategic sites</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255523</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOU have to have the right sites to attract industry these days, and
only five minutes away from the Eurocentral development is another major
success story in the Strathclyde Business Park. Extending to 155 acres,
this is a prestigious and strategic location for companies of all sizes,
from start-up to multinationals.
The park has already attracted big names such as the Mercury
Communications' Scottish headquarters, William Grant Distillers, and the
LDA which has its headquarters there.
The total investment in development has already exceeded #110m and
part of its success story is the 26 advance factory units in the
integrated Birchwood Courtyards, a high-specification two-phase
industrial environment which meant a #4.4m investment for Motherwell
District Council.
These units offer between 2000 and 5000 sq ft and their success -- all
the units are now fully let -- means a third phase of the project is to
start soon.
The business park has already attracted more than 700 jobs and is a
joint development among the LDA, Morrison Developments Ltd, and H F
Developments Ltd.
LDA Chief Executive Archie Bethel describes it as, ''an excellent
example of private and public sector working together to achieve further
economic regeneration in Lanarkshire.''
And Motherwell District contains about 322 acres of prime development
land which enjoy Enterprise Zone status. That, of course, means a rates
holiday which extends to February 2003, tax incentives designed to
reduce development costs, and simplified planning procedures.
Motherwell has four such sites, all easily adapted for any type of
commercial and industrial development. They are at Newhouse West (owned
by Scottish Enterprise/Rail Link Scotland Ltd), Tannochside (owned by
Scottish Enterprise/ Motherwell District Council), Excelsior Park (owned
by the council) and Airbles Road, Motherwell (owned by Lanarkshire
Development Agency).
Newhouse West extends to 195 acres at Mossend and enjoys close
proximity to the M8 and the Eurocentral development. It is seen as ideal
for distribution and manufacturing companies. Tannochside is
particularly suited to distribution operations and has already met with
significant success, and Airbles Road is scheduled for quality office
and business units.
Excelsior Park at Wishaw has already got off to a good start with
three companies in the process of moving into its first phase, a
self-contained section on its eastern corner called East Yett. Then
there came news in the middle of this month that a second development
had been approved and was going to be carried out by Micklegate Special
Projects of Leeds, covering 3.3 acres and consisting of nine units.
In all, there is a potential in these four Enterprise Zone sites for
about 8000 new jobs and the Industrial Development and Estates
Department of Motherwell District Council is in the middle of a
concerted campaign to make the most of the opportunities they offer.
Says Councillor Harry McGuigan, chairman of the Economic Development
Committee: ''Security for the future is fundamental if our communities
are to be caring and productive. The District Council is committed to
retaining existing jobs within the district and to construct a new
economic base. The Enterprise Zone developments are part of that
effort.''
</TEXT>
