<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000096</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000096</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sometimes, suckers, the favourites fall</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRIAN MEEK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>19</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255524</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TRAMP, tramp, tramp, the boys are marching . . .
It is hard enough fighting elections on my own behalf but with the lad
Michael also standing for a seat in the new unitary authorities,
kick-off April 6, my old plates of meat are taking a hammering. On
Tuesday night we were bowling along pretty well, had resisted two offers
of tea and one of something stronger -- by his casting vote -- when we
reached a large house in leafy Marchmont.
I rang the doorbell, noting the two cars in the ample driveway, and an
overweight, middle-aged man appeared. Before either of us could say
''vote for us, guv'', he went into orbit.
''You're selling something,'' he roared. My son shook his head. ''A
political party -- even worse,'' shouted the oaf and slammed the door in
our faces.
Michael, who is a gentler soul than I am, dissuaded me from stamping
out through his flower beds or indeed re-ringing the bell to tell this
creature what I thought of him. For there is absolutely no excuse for
rudeness of that sort and particularly towards those who, unlike the
majority of the electorate, actually take part in the local democratic
exercise.
In the next couple of weeks you may receive a call from a candidate.
From whatever party they come, they deserve civility. Without them, how
would councils operate? Fortunately such boorish behaviour is extremely
rare. If I had accepted all the soft drinks I have been offered my
bladder would have packed up by now; if all the hard drinks had gone
down so would my liver. Most people are charming and hospitable.
I have not managed, so far this time, to intrude accidentally on a
house lingerie party. ''Oh, yes, do come in, I think the ladies will be
thrilled to see a man.'' Michael lives in hope.
Nor have I had one of the more confusing interludes. At a General
Election I was canvassing for Malcolm Rifkind and told an elderly lady
that the Minister was counting on her support. She showed me into a
sitting room full of pensioners, all taking tea.
''We are very fortunate today,'' announced the host, ''to have with us
the Rev Rifkind who is to give us a report.''
On my own patch this time, I am accompanied as ever by the Old Doc,
agent extraordinaire, his arthritic knees giving constant cause for
complaint. ''I hope you have a wheelchair in that car boot,'' he
growled.
''No,'' I replied, ''there's a set of castors being delivered on
Thursday and I will have you roped behind me.'' Wouldn't be nearly as
much fun without him.
Actually I do enjoy myself at elections, whatever the political
climate. In Edinburgh, all the pundits tell us it is a one-horse race.
According to them, and the comrades themselves, the Labour Party is
going to skite home.
In a kind of mini-Sheffield rally, an early Ally McLeod sort of
celebration, the socialists have not only declared themselves the
winners, they have even chosen the people who will fill the main jobs in
the new authority. Eric will be LP, Keith will be leader, David will be
transportation boss, the list is quite long.
What is clear is that, should this scenario come to pass, the current
Labour members on Edinburgh District Council will be fried and filleted
by their counterparts on Lothian region. So long, suckers.
Makes you wonder why we are having an election at all. Still, as the
last big contest showed us, sometimes the favourites fall.
Of one thing I am certain, the Labour Party will win nothing on
grounds of policy; for in many fields it has none.
I bechanced to hear the shadow education secretary, David Blunkett, on
Radio 4 on Wednesday morning. He was asked, extremely politely, this is
not a member of the Government we are interviewing, to say whether
Labour would force schools which have opted out to return to local
authority control.
''That policy will be ready in the summer,'' he declared. There are
local elections in Scotland in April and in England and Wales in May yet
a major policy plank in education will be ready in the summer? Ask again
then.
Surely we can assume, however, said the man with the mike, that Labour
intends to spend more on education? ''Money will be spent in a wiser
fashion.'' Is that a ''yes'' or a ''no''? I have a question myself,
which has a direct bearing on events in Edinburgh, which I should like
to pose to Shadow Secretary of State Mr George Robertson. No, it is not
the one the Nats asked you, George.
Could you possibly inform the thousands of Edinburgh parents who have
children in non-state schools what is to happen to these establishments
should Labour win a General Election?
Specifically may they know (1) whether the assisted places scheme will
be scrapped and (2) whether there will be any change in the schools'
charitable status? I will pursue the postman until the reply arrives.
By the way, I had a most enjoyable afternoon talking at and with the
400 good souls who turned up for the Conversation Pieces series at
Glasgow Royal Concert Hall on Tuesday. ''It's a great pleasure for me to
be here in Glasgow, or, as the Chancellor of the Exchequer might put it,
Aberdeen,'' I told them, and we had a grand crack.
A lady stood up at the end and suggested I should be the candidate for
Sir Nicky's old seat. Madam, I may appear not too bright but . . .
Back to the hustings.
''Open that box.
''Put in the mail.
''Another two weeks, and we win or fail!''
Tramp, tramp, tramp.
</TEXT>
