<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Quality of life</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255526</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I HAVE watched with considerable interest the machinations of the
various environmental groups who are protesting about the M77 and its
impact on the environment. What has been forgotten is that due to the
lack of the M77 the level of traffic pouring through Cardonald and
Penilee is totally outrageous and seriously impinging on the
environmental quality of life of the people of Cardonald and adjacent
areas.
It is all very well for environmentalists to hammer steel nails into
trees and protest about this, that, and the other when it is affecting
the environment at one end of the area. What has been forgotten, and I
speak for the people of Cardonald, is that people on the through-road
from Crookston Road to Sandwood Road have suffered for years as a result
of the massive traffic input flowing through the area.
Similar problems exist at Berryknowes Road where people use the tunnel
to reach the motorway as there is no alternative such as the M77.
I would ask for a balanced view to be taken of the construction of the
motorway and for critics not to be bogged down on the issue of what the
impact will be on certain areas.
As the situation stands just now areas like Shawlands, Cardonald,
Crookston, Hillington, and Penilee are affected and those who care for
the environment should recognise that it is essential that we get
traffic out of residental areas and on to the motorways to improve the
quality of life of those who live immediately adjacent to roads such as
Crookston Road and Berryknowes Road.
I assure those environmentalists who say they care that there are
thousands of people living now in a situation where heavy traffic is
impinging greatly on their quality of life.
Councillor J McCarron,
Glasgow City Council,
City Chambers,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
