<DOCNO>GH950323-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Truth v rules</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>CORRESPONDENCE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255527</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRUCE McKain's article, Judge challenged over admissibility (March
17), once again highlights the grey area of seeking truth and justice
versus rules and regulations.
It assumes a trial is always conducted to perfection with no margin
for error. It does not allow for incompetence, malpractice, or
complacency.
It should be basic -- if evidence is produced, whether it was
available or not at a trial, that throws new light on a conviction why
on earth should it not be heard?
It must be dreadful for an innocent person knowing there is evidence
that could clear him but is considered inadmissible because of wording.
Parliament surely never legislated to allow this to happen.
Robert Kennedy,
27 Border Way,
Kirkintilloch.
</TEXT>
