<HEADLINE>Angela found out the hard way</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANN SHAW</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255528</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PEANUTS are taboo for 10-year-old Angela Rennie from Dumfries. She is
allergic to them, and both her parents and school keep a supply of
adrenaline injections handy in case she should accidentally eat some.
A year ago, her parents, Josephine and Bill Rennie, thought they were
the only family in Scotland to have a child suffering from peanut
allergy.
Today, they realise they are one of at least 100, possibly more, in
Scotland.
As Co-ordinator of the Anaphylaxis Campaign for Scotland (South),
Josephine says the aims of the campaign include better recognition of
the condition, better labelling of all foods, educating the public about
life-threatening food allergies and giving comfort and support to other
parents.
She still recalls vividly the occasion seven years ago when Angela
nearly died from an allergic reaction to peanuts:
''We were at a local social function and there was a buffet. Suddenly,
our eldest daughter, Clare, came rushing up, shouting: 'Come quickly,
Angela is choking!' We couldn't see anything in her mouth, yet she was
getting worse.
''We grabbed her, jumped into a car and rushed to our local casualty
department. The doctor said we were just in time. She almost died. They
kept her in for a few days and discovered she's allergic to peanuts.
''At first I thought: 'Oh, that's alright. It's only peanuts. We can
easily avoid them.' I was afraid it might have been something serious,
like cystic fibrosis. Little did I know then how potentially lethal the
condition could be.''
For further information on the Anaphylaxis Campaign, contact
Co-ordinators Josephine Rennie on 0387 262437 (Scotland South and
Central), or Barbara Neely on 01343 548595 (Scotland North).
The Anaphylaxis Campaign HQ can be contacted on 01252 318723.
</TEXT>
