<DOCNO>GH950323-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>When peanuts can kill</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANN SHAW</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255529</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
It surprises most of us to learn that the humble peanut can be
dangerous. Yet, as ANN SHAW reports, there are thousands of people to
whom avoiding it is a matter of life or death
THE sudden death of 20-year-old Jennifer Mott, after eating a
strawberry gateau decorated with nuts, has led her mother, Anne Mott, to
join one of Britain's youngest charities, the year-old Anaphylaxis
Campaign to highlight the dangers in peanuts. She was among 120 parents
who gathered in Stirling last Sunday for the launch of the Scottish
branch of the campaign. Such is the interest that people had travelled
from as far away as Elgin and the Borders.
Anne recalls the death of her daughter, who worked with Grampian
Police: ''It happened at work. Shortly after eating the gateau, she
complained about her lips feeling itchy, and she went outside for some
fresh air. Within an hour and a quarter she was dead. She was taken to
hospital but it was too late.''
Jennifer suffered from asthma, and, as a child, she once had an
allergic reaction after eating peanuts. Anne has since learned that some
bakers, to cut costs, put flaky peanuts instead of almonds on their
commercial cakes. ''Maybe this is what happened. I've no way of finding
out.''
So far, there are more than 100 members of the Scottish campaign and a
further 1800 in England, where the campaign was launched a year ago by
David Reading, of Hampshire, whose daughter Sarah died after eating a
crushed peanut.
So how common is this allergy? ''That's the problem. We don't know,''
says Dr Evelyn Kirkwood, an allergy specialist at the Western General,
Glasgow, who gave the keynote lecture for the launch last Sunday.
''My advice to parents is to take peanut allergy very seriously. It is
potentially lethal. If you think your child is in the least bit
allergic, go to your GP.''
Once diagnosed, either through skin or blood tests, the condition can
be controlled by total avoidance of peanuts. If a child should
accidentally eat peanuts, the treatment is an immediate injection of
adrenalin.
If the child is old enough, often he or she will be trained, like
diabetic children, to self-administer injections. The usual practice is
for parents and schools to keep a supply of adrenalin injections.
It's not known how many people have died as a result of eating
peanuts, though anecdotal evidence in the media suggests that it may not
be as rare as had been supposed.
Because of the paucity of medical data, there is very little in the
way of statistical evidence. The International Classification of
Diseases has no code for food anaphylaxis -- sudden death through food
allergies.
It is suspected that such deaths may be recorded inappropriately as a
heart attack, asthma attack, or even sudden infant death syndrome. As
one doctor explained: ''If a person is brought into casualty department
and promptly dies, it may be put down to cardiac arrest. Until now
nobody thought to ask whether he or she might have been allergic to
peanuts.''
Is there not a risk that, with all the media attention on peanuts,
parents may panic? ''No,'' says Dr Kirkwood. ''This is a rare but
potentially dangerous condition. Until we know more about it, parents
have every right to be concerned.'' What is known is that children whose
immune deficiency system is impaired are more likely to suffer from
asthma, hay fever, and eczema and in turn are more likely to be at risk
of peanut allergy. Unlike other allergies, children do not grow out of a
peanut allergy.
Nobody knows why the number of people suffering from asthma and other
related conditions has increased substantially during the past 20-30
years. The finger has been pointed at several culprits, ranging from
environmental pollution, to central heating, dust mite, and food
additives, but without conclusive proof.
Dr Charles McSharry, an immunologist at the Western General Hospital,
Glasgow, suspects that the real cause may be something that has not yet
been identified. ''It's not outdoor pollution. The air is cleaner today
than it was a 100 years ago. Yet asthma is on the increase in the
Highlands, even on the Isle of Skye.''
One of the concerns of parents at Sunday's launch meeting is that the
condition is not as rare as doctors claim. Anne Brown, a nurse from
Stonehaven, has a seven-year-old son who is a sufferer. There are three
other children in his primary school who are also allergic to peanuts,
and the teachers keep a supply of adrenalin injections for emergencies.
An allergic reaction can occur within minutes of taking peanuts or up
to two hours later. The faster the reaction, the more potentially
dangerous the situation. The signs include swelling, itching of lips,
nausea, pain, tingling, overwhelming sense of fear, swollen throat,
fainting, and stomach pains. The worst thing you can do if you feel an
attack coming on is to go to the toilet. You could die alone before
anybody recognises the situation.
So who is at risk? Those who are already known to suffer from asthma
attacks, eczema, hay fever, or those with a family history of allergy.
It affects mostly children, though some adults suffer, too.
Dr Kirkwood advises: ''Listen to your body and do what it tells you.
If certain foods trigger an attack then avoid them in future. Carry
appropriate medication.''
The real danger is in the hidden peanuts in processed foods, something
that is high on the campaign agenda. Often these foods contain extracts
of peanuts or peanut oil. One of the aims of the campaign is to get all
food manufacturers to list in detail what their foods contain.
Even a Yorkie chocolate bar may contain traces of nut.
Chocolate-coated raisins may have been produced by machinery that
earlier was used to coat peanuts and there may be sufficient residue
left to trigger an attack.
Unlike hay fever, or some other allergic reactions, the danger with
peanut allergy is the speed of the reaction and its potential to kill.
This was certainly news to Sharon McIllwraith, from Dumbarton, who
attended Sunday's meeting. She's glad she did. Her daughter, Corinna,
suffered an allergic reaction when she was three years old, after eating
a peanut-butter sandwich.
''Her whole body was covered in a rash and she had a high temperature.
I dealt with it myself but next time I went to the doctor I mentioned it
to him. All he said was: 'Don't let her eat peanuts.' I had no idea
until today how potentially lethal the situation can be. I'm going back
to him to get her tested so that I can have proper medication. I'm
extremely glad I came to this meeting. It's been very useful.''
Meanwhile, there are two allergy clinics in Scotland, one in Edinburgh
and the other in Glasgow, and research is going on at Southampton
University. In May, all GPs' surgeries will be circulated with a leaflet
informing them about the potential dangers of peanut allergies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tips on peanut allergy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANN SHAW</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255530</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
* Avoid all contact with peanuts, peanut oil, peanut products, ground
nuts, monkey nuts.
* Read labels carefully and check contents of food if eating out.
* Treat as ''suspect'' any foods containing vegetable or hydrogenated
vegetable oil.
* Avoid all nuts.
* Some foods known to contain peanuts: cakes, biscuits, ice creams,
frozen desserts, Indian and Oriental dishes, vegetarian dishes, salads.
* Peanut allergy reactions are likely to be more severe. Children will
not ''grow out of it'', as may occur with some other foods.
* Wear a Medi-Alert identify disc, or make certain people are aware of
the allergy.
* Be sure schools are informed of the potential seriousness of
reactions.
* Signs of severe reaction: rapid pulse, difficulty breathing,
sweating and collapse.
* If in doubt, call 999 for an ambulance and be sure to say:
'Anaphylaxis'.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cheesemaker pleads for justice</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255531</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CHEESEMAKER claimed yesterday he was denied natural justice when a
decision was taken to condemn batches of his gourmet product, which is
reputed to be enjoyed by the Queen.
Mr Humphrey Errington has asked a judge at the Court of Session in
Edinburgh to overturn the decision condemning 44 batches of his cheese
which a Justice of the Peace ruled was potentially hazardous to public
health and unfit for human consumption.
Mr Errington produces a blue-veined, semi-hard sheep's cheese, Lanark
Blue, made from unpasteurised milk. It has been at the forefront of
re-establishing traditional cheesemaking in Scotland. However,
Clydesdale District Council and the JP decided the 44 batches, worth
about #27,000, should be condemned as it failed to comply with food
safety requirements.
Mr Errington, of Walston Braehead, Ogscastle, by Carnwarth,
Lanarkshire, fears the decision could jeopardise his business, which
employs seven people. Other independent cheesemakers have expressed
concern about the effect the case could have on their industry.
Samples of Lanark Blue were discovered to contain listeria bacteria,
some strains of which can cause the illness listeriosis: Mr Errington
said 63,000 portions of Lanark Blue have been sold without one case of
listeriosis being reported.
The council took the issue before JP Elizabeth Wilson, who decided on
March 3 that 44 batches failed to comply with food safety requirements
and ordered its destruction.
Mr Errington then won an interim interdict at the Court of Session
preventing the destruction of the cheese pending a hearing of his
judicial review of the justice's decision.
His counsel, Mr Michael Jones QC, told the court yesterday that Mrs
Wilson refused to allow cross-examination of witnesses called before her
and had given no reasons for her decision.
He argued that the JP had reached her decision without regard to the
principles of natural justice and it should be set aside.
Mr Colin Sutherland, QC, for the local authority, said the relevant
food safety legislation had been enacted following a series of food
scares. It was envisaged the hearing before a JP or a sheriff would not
involve lengthy inquiry or cross-examination, he argued.
The hearing continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000104</DOCNO>
