<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Partnerships take the lead in regeneration process</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ERIC KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255532</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BREATHING new life into Motherwell District is a story of partnership,
and it is a tale which seems to enter a new chapter every other month.
The most obvious example is the Motherwell Partnership itself, which
brings together organisations such as the District Council, the LDA,
Scottish Homes, Strathclyde Regional Council, British Steel (Industry)
Ltd, and the Motherwell Enterprise Development Company (Medco).
This body makes a real contribution to the regeneration process
through its organised efforts to make the best collective use of
financial resources and professional expertise.
''People often talk about partnership between the public and private
sectors and among authorities and the various agencies when the reality
is that some of the partners are still pulling against each other,''
says Jim Hope, executive director of Medco.
''In this district, the partners really do work hand in hand. I have
seen some remarkable achievements here.''
At the Strathclyde Business Park Scottish headquarters of British
Steel (Industry), regional director John Fairlie has a similar story.
''In years to come, people will come here to make case studies of
partnership in action,'' he says.
It seems fitting that BS(I) should play a significant part in helping
an area so badly hit by the disappearance of the steel industry. The
initiative was set up in 1975, offering managed workspace and financial
help to small and medium-sized businesses.
It specialises in making loans, share capital, or a combination of
both available to companies which have the normal difficulties in
raising finance particularly what tends to be seen as risk capital from
the usual sources.
John Fairlie moved his headquarters team in 1994 to BS(I)'s new
Grovewood Business Centre at the Strathclyde Business Park in Bellshill.
The #3.5m centre is a high-quality complex of 34 industrial units and
a central office block offering 16 units suitable for anything from
start-up companies to reasonably-sized business concerns.
All the offices are fully let and occupants have access to fax, colour
photocopying facilities, and other communal features -- all welcome
features for small concerns.
The industrial units in the surrounding ''courtyard'' are causing some
interest and already nine of them are let despite having been opened
only in September of last year. John Fairlie is certain that all 34 will
be let within 12 months.
When fully occupied Grovewood will have generated about 400 jobs.
Already 19 companies are there, 99 jobs have been created, and there are
instances of companies being attracted there as opposed to other sites
outside the district.
John Fairlie also places importance on the Youth Enterprise Centre
based in the old Dalzell High School annexe in Motherwell. Here BS(I)
combined with the District Council, Strathclyde Regional Council, and
the Lanarkshire Development Agency to effect a #2m refurbishment, helped
by European Regional Development Funding.
The centre is now about to open its doors to young people wishing to
''have a go'' at start-ups. It occupies about a third of the refurbished
building -- the rest is to be let to other concerns by Strathclyde
Region -- and young entrepreneurs will be offered up to two years of
highly discounted rent, along with professional support in the areas of
training, computers, and advice.
BS(I) has funded it for three years and it is being run by Motherwell
Youth Enterprise Centre Ltd, with its own board of directors and
charitable status.
BS(I) is involved in a variety of other joint initiatives with the
LDA, Motherwell District Council, Strathclyde Regional Council, and
Medco.
Over at Medco's Brandon Street headquarters executive director Jim
Hope has a clear concept of its role in economic development.
Its slogan, For Business And The Community, survives from its origins
as Motherwell Enterprise Trust and continues to reflect a wide-ranging
programme of activities and schemes designed to help companies establish
and consolidate in the district.
This is done through grants, loans, business start-up advice, and a
variety of schemes designed to smooth the path in the way of computer
training, graduate placement, information technology programmes, and
grants for training and employment.
Jim Hope's set-up runs the Prince's Scottish Youth Business Trust for
the whole of Lanarkshire, and the New Business Start-up Programme for
the LDA under which about 80 companies receive grant aid each year.
It also offers workspace and use of a computer to start-ups qualifying
for priority assistance, and runs the Scottish Co-operative Development
Scheme and the Livewire Award Scheme, all designed to help companies
develop.
Medco's 22-strong team paid more than 1600 visits to Motherwell
companies last year, 750 of them in connection with business
development. Most of the other visits were in connection with grant
schemes for start-ups, and these efforts alone found jobs for 340
unemployed.
The last word on the pulling-together theme goes to Councillor Harry
McGuigan, chairman of the Motherwell Partnership, who sees the body as
''crucial'' to progress in the district.
''The Partnership share a vision for Motherwell District for the new
millennium.''
Bright
future ahead: Jim Hope of Medco
