<HEADLINE>A link to Europe</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ERIC KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255534</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONE of the biggest boosts to Motherwell District recently has been the
Eurocentral freight terminal, now in operation at Mossend with five
trains already leaving daily for various points in Europe.
It is Scotland's passport to 320 million consumers on the Continent.
The terminal was built at a cost of #8.6m by the Lanarkshire
Development Agency, which handed it over to Railfreight Distribution to
run, then embarked on three other imaginative schemes to help the area
draw maximum benefit.
About #27.4m has been spent, or is committed, to acquire, prepare and
service land at Eurocentral. The first project is the Eurocentral
Industrial and Distribution Park, a 100-acre site being developed
through a joint venture between the LDA and Amec Developments. It lies
within the Lanarkshire Enterprise Zone and the first 45 acres are now
available.
A #7m contract is under way to provide the necessary infrastructure
and there are three units currently under offer, involving a total of
450,000 sq ft of distribution space. These developments alone could mean
550 jobs.
The second project, already in existence, is the 95-acre Strategic
Investment Site which recently came within a whisker of attracting the
Japanese electronics giant Samsung to Motherwell District.
Mercedes Benz was also interested and the LDA is confident that a big
name will move in.
The third project is the Rail Freight Village alongside the
Euroterminal and consisting of a 100-acre site expected to provide
1,000,000 sq ft of modern industrial and distribution facilities.
About 1000 jobs are projected to be created over the next 10 years and
planning consent has already been granted to a #2.4m car terminal within
the village.
The LDA reckons the entire Eurocentral development will ultimately
cover nearly 800 acres, with the potential to create more than 4300 new
jobs.
</TEXT>
