<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000107</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000107</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Motherwell sets its sights on industrial growth</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ERIC KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255535</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
In April next year Motherwell District Council will become part of
North Lanarkshire Council. In this three-page feature, Eric Kennedy
reports on the changes that have taken place within the district and
what is being done towards smooth reform
IT has been a truism over the past decade or so that the people of
Motherwell District are facing a time of change. What else is new? They
have come through a period not merely of change but of wholesale
readjustment to a radically altered industrial scene.
The change this time will be the absorption of the district council
into the North Lanarkshire Council. That comes in April of next year but
the preparations are naturally already in hand. The upheaval promises,
to be much less traumatic than at the time of the collapse of the old
industries: a groundwork has been laid to facilitate a prosperous
future.
The dust and dirt of the steelmaking, engineering and mining
activities have gone but with them the jobs. Motherwell District might
now have a cleaner and more pleasant environment but it is making every
effort to improve things on the employment front as well.
It is appropriate that some of the efforts of Motherwell District
Council and its partners in regeneration have been centred on the
establishment of bright new industrial estates and business parks on the
very sites once occupied by the old industries. Rehabilitation,
landscaping, modernisation have been the order of the day.
Allied to this has been a concerted effort to draw new companies to
the district, aided by incentives, help with planning procedures,
assistance in training, and the provision of state-of-the-art units.
Many of these are situated within the Lanarkshire Enterprise Zone,
which helps more than a little.
John Bonomy, Chief Executive of Motherwell District Council, feels the
area has a great deal going for it, in fact he is tempted to say that if
this part of Scotland can't make a go of things, which one can? ''We are
ideally situated as a centre for communications and distribution,'' he
says. ''The M8, M73 and M74 are only minutes away.
''The district is more or less equidistant from the two main cities of
Scotland, with their international airports within easy reach. Even
Prestwick is not that far away. And the establishment of the Eurofreight
Terminal at Mossend means fast access to Europe's growing markets. That
is our direct Channel Tunnel link.''
He worries about the hard-core long-term unemployed, especially among
men, and remembers the days of wholesale employment at the steel mills.
The future, he considers, has to lie with rather smaller concerns,
plenty of them, and with the potential for growth.
It is in attracting such companies, including start-ups, that the
council's efforts have been concentrated, although there are very large
sites with development potential situated near the motorway network
should a multinational concern wish to move in.
The council's Industrial Development and Estates Department provides
all possible help to companies, finding the right site and right
financial package.
Flexibility of leases, help with training, and fast planning
procedures also help.
But Bonomy feels Motherwell District has another asset, in its people.
A flexible and committed workforce is there, and it has already shown
its versatility in adapting to new industrial scenarios.
A variety of training initiatives, often supported by financial
assistance, as well as vocational training at local colleges, help keep
the workforce in touch with the changing requirements of the modern
employer.
This is one of the reasons why the Motherwell Food Park, which brings
more than 40 food companies and suppliers together in what was Britain's
first park of its kind, has been a success. The quality food products
emerging from there include anything from traditional Scottish fare to
exotic Japanese dishes.
Another innovation has been the Euromed Business Park, offering a
unique environment created to meet the legislative, quality and other
demands of marketing medical and healthcare products within the European
Union. It contains Scotland's first commercial sterilisation facility
and this and other initiatives mean Motherwell can claim to lead the way
in medicines, biotechnology, electronics, food and engineering.
John Bonomy says his council has much of which to be proud in its
regeneration efforts. ''Almost from day one of the council, it set aside
an element of its finance to provide industrial units, or be involved in
providing the infrastructure for sites for industry,'' he says.
He is also proud of the council's housing record and points to the
fact that the council inherited 40,000 council houses when it was formed
20 years ago. Today there are only 30,000, and all of those built
between the wars have been extensively modernised and upgraded.
Meanwhile owner-occupation has risen, reaching 23.81% in 1987, 31.72% in
1990, and a projected 39.44% for 1995.
''There is still much to be done,'' says Bonomy. ''But we are handing
over to North Lanarkshire a significantly improved housing stock.
''The council has also made significant progress in the provision of
leisure and sporting amenities to suit modern-day needs.
''Life can be good in Motherwell District if the proper efforts are
made in regenerating its economy through industrial growth. That has to
be an ongoing task, before and after 1996.''
</TEXT>
