<HEADLINE>Inquiry told of body find by climber</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255536</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE mother of avalanche victim Dr Katharine Herd wept yesterday as a
climber told how he had found the 28-year-old woman's body buried in the
snow.
Mr Kevin Fear, 33, an outdoor instructor from Llangollen, told a fatal
accident inquiry at Dingwall how his own party had been on the same
mountain, 3458ft Liathach in Torridon, on the same day in January last
year.
His party had come off the mountain. Minutes after returning to their
vehicles, they were flagged down by Mr Marcus Cross, 18, of Aberdeen,
one of the avalanche survivors.
Mr Fear and three others headed back up the mountain and found Dr
Robin Dawson, of Dumfries, lying badly injured.
Mr Fear said: ''At first, we didn't spot Kathy. She was under the snow
and we dug her out. She was unconscious but still breathing.''
A helicopter airlifted the injured pair to hospital on Skye. Dr Herd
died next morning in a Glasgow hospital to which she had been
transferred.
Mr Terry Doe, 48, then leader of Torridon Mountain Rescue team, said
that, for the first time in his experience, there had been a
communications breakdown.
Mr Tom Forrest, 48, also a member of the rescue team, said he would
not have taken people into the gully in such conditions. The inquiry
continues.
</TEXT>
