<HEADLINE>Englishman converts to SNP on the road to Brussels. I believe Scottish interests in Europe can never be pursued through London.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID MCCARTHY,ROBBIE DINWOODIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>PROFILE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255537</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
On the surface, David McCarthy is scarcely someone you would expect to
have much sympathy for Scottish nationalism. Born 57 years ago in Kent,
he was educated at Winchester and studied modern history at Magdalen
College, Oxford, before joining Unilever.
A high-flying career saw him travel the world with his wife and three
children. He headed the multi-national's operations in Malaysia and
Chile, before he was posted to Scotland in 1988 as chairman and managing
director of their salmon-farming subsidiary, Marine Harvest.
He retired in December, two months after the company was bought by
Booker plc and merged with its main rival in the sector to become Marine
Harvest McConnell.
From his home in Kinross, this former ''soft'' Labour voter looked
back on his eight years of dealing with civil servants and Ministers at
the Scottish Office and bureaucrats in Brussels. It was an experience
which made him realise where his political allegiance now lies. Today he
will join the SNP. Here, he explains why.
Robbie Dinwoodie
ALARGE and growing number of people in Scotland believe that the time
has come for independence. I am now one of them. Scotland cannot be
governed indefinitely by the Tories. Their support in Scotland has been
abysmally low in the past two General Elections, in both of which they
were successful in England. No doubt this trend will be confirmed by a
further Tory disaster in the forthcoming Scottish local elections and
the loss of the Perth and Kinross by-election, whenever it is held.
The continuing governance of this country by a party now regularly
humiliated by the Scottish electorate offends democratic principles. It
has turned the Scottish Office into a quasi-colonial administration.
The Tories no longer even seem to expect to recover in Scotland and
their language and treatment of Scots has become offensive.
Ian Lang illustrated the point perfectly when he recently referred to
Scotland as a ''burden'' on the Tories.
Take as an example of Tory indifference their attitude to an industry
that I know well -- salmon farming. That industry is worth #200m a year
to the Scottish economy, with 55% going for export.
Six years of dealing with the Scottish Office led me to the
inescapable conclusion that the Tory Government just couldn't be
bothered with us.
Why? Because there aren't any Tory seats anywhere near a salmon farm,
nor are there likely to be. And, of course, there aren't any Tory seats
near Rosyth, Ravenscraig and several other examples of Tory disinterest
in Scotland. The only thing that the Tories are bothered about is
Scotland's oil. That is why the Union is so important to them.
Of course, some people say that this doesn't matter. There is a big
change coming in Scotland, for at last Labour have an electable leader.
The pendulum, so the story goes, is swinging Labour's way and provided
they can keep quiet about policy and avoid the crass errors of the 1992
election campaign, we will soon have a Labour government. That
government will then introduce devolution.
Scotland is keen on constitutional change and, Labour argues,
devolution will mean that we can run our own affairs. But the key
question is: ''How much power will be transferred?'' And if the answer
is ''not very much'' then what is the point of devolution?
For me the two key tests which determine where real power will lie
relate to the control of the Exchequer and relations with Europe. In
both these areas Labour's devolution proposals show Westminster
remaining in virtually full control.
Labour's timid proposal to allow its assembly to raise or lower income
tax by 3p has already apparently frightened the Labour leadership in
London into believing that they may be exposing the flank to the Tories
on which they lost the last election. The Tories have seized upon this,
with Ian Lang having already converted 3p to 19p by way of a typically
wild press release.
But there can be no real transfer of power if the Treasury in London
remains as dominant as now. I have lost count of the times over the past
six years I heard Scottish Office Ministers say that they would dearly
like to help the salmon-farming industry, ''but the problem is the
Treasury, you see!''
Relations with Europe are equally critical. It is essential to any
real transfer of power to Scotland that we be able to deal directly and
authoritatively with Europe.
Nothing, but nothing, has handicapped Scottish salmon farming more, in
their repeated efforts to engage Brussels in action to bring some
stability to the European industry, than total lack of support from the
Scottish Office.
Scottish Ministers say they would like to help but the trouble is that
even Scottish Ministers can't lift a finger in Brussels without
permission from London. The Scottish Office makes no secret of this --
they have told it to us many times.
Under devolution, Labour proposes some vague kind of direct contact
between an assembly in Edinburgh and the Commission in Brussels. That
won't work. We have had a little office over there before. It achieved
precisely nothing.
Officials of the European Union only start to listen when they know
they are speaking with people who represent, or are being fully
supported by, sovereign governments. I know, because I have been told
so, across the table in Brussels.
From my own observations of the European Union, I have no doubt that
Scottish interests in Europe can never be pursued through London in the
way that they could be out of Scotland.
I have observed, too, how effective the Irish are in Europe, because
their Government and industry have their act together. Even the
Norwegians, from outside the Community, get a better deal than we do.
Thus, if devolution ever comes to pass it will quickly become obvious
that without control of the Exchequer and without a real voice in Europe
any Labour assembly can only be a talking shop. Devolution will then be
seen as a messy and unnecessary halfway house.
And the SNP? What do they offer? To this observer, a great deal.
First of all, the return of democracy to Scotland would avoid the
indignity of being thrown bones by a Labour government just trying to
keep us happy, with the obvious objective of keeping the parliamentary
seats in Scotland and the power at Westminster.
Secondly, Scotland would be a full member of the European Union. The
benefits of membership for any small state are very great.
The EU is constructed to benefit small nations; they have equality of
representation in the Commission and the Council of Ministers and they
take their turn at the presidency. They can also use a veto.
Scotland will get even greater benefits because today Scotland ranks
only as part of a nation that is, in my observation of Brussels, the
least liked, the least enthusiastic and much the least competent member
of the EU -- and that incompetence includes the pursuit of its own
interests.
Thirdly, I believe that with independence Scotland would be a magnet
for inward investment. One of the attractions of a small country for the
investor (and I have experience of Singapore, Malaysia and Chile) is the
ease with which they can speak to top government Ministers and
officials. They like that.
For the foreign investor we could open a ''one-stop shop'' like they
have in Singapore.
Another attraction to the inward investor is the quality of the
Scottish workforce. It is a fact that education in Scotland remains
among the best in Europe.
Some Tories, and even some Labour politicians, argue that independence
would lead to an exodus from Scotland of businesses, banks and other
financial institutions -- a very curious view.
In six years of running quite a large Scottish company I certainly met
businessmen who were opponents of change, but I never met one -- not one
-- who said they would ''flit'' if independence came to pass.
The Tories keep saying that there is a transfer of resources from
England to Scotland -- a subsidy from London to keep us going.
This is an assertion unsupported by the facts. Most probably, when all
''unidentified'' (that is, conveniently excluded) expenditure is taken
into account the highest subsidies go to the South-east of England.
Scotland is rich enough and talented enough to make a pretty good job
of running its own affairs and looking after its own people.
We must decide things for ourselves, and I am glad that more and more
people seem willing to make that choice, including growing numbers
within the business community.
The twenty-first wealthiest nation in the world has nothing to fear
from going it alone. It's high time we did so.
</TEXT>
