<HEADLINE>TUC agrees to set target for minimum wage</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS, INDUSTRIAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255539</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TARGET figure for a national minimum wage will be set by the TUC --
even though Labour leader Tony Blair has made it clear he does not want
a specific sum agreed before the next General Election.
Yesterday's meeting of the TUC executive also agreed that unions
should be involved with a Labour Government and employers on the
''setting and uprating'' of the wage, possibly through new tripartite
machinery.
Although no target is expected until after the September congress, TUC
general secretary John Monks said he fully expected it to be in place in
time for the election.
The move, seen as a bid to placate several larger affiliates including
Unison and the Transport and General Workers Union and so head off any
rebellion at congress, will not please the Labour leadership.
Although commited to the introduction of a statutory minimum wage,
Labour wants to assess what the nation can afford once the party is in
power.
Mr Monks denied the TUC decision was in ''defiance'' of Mr Blair's
wishes, adding: ''We are just doing our job as we see fit. The Labour
Party will do its job as it sees fit -- that is perfectly legitimate.
''We are just making it clear that we will come up with a target
figure. It is not anti-Labour. We are just making our position as clear
as possible.''
Many unions have urged Labour to back a minimum wage of half median
male earnings -- a formula worth #4.15 per hour. Current TUC policy is
for a minimum wage at half male earnings to be uprated to two-thirds,
but it has never before set a precise figure.
</TEXT>
