<HEADLINE>Loch Lomond sale finalised for #2.6m</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALF YOUNG, ECONOMICS EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255540</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE deal for Dunbartonshire Enterprise to buy the Drumkinnon Bay site
on Loch Lomond from its private developer owners, first revealed in The
Herald on March 8, has been completed.
The price being paid to the previous joint owners, Cala Homes and
Dixons Commercial Properties, for the 77 acres is #2.6m.
''We paid not a penny more than we had to for this site and we intend
to get every penny back,'' said DE's chief executive, Mr Donald
MacInnes.
Mr Michael Kelly, chairman of the sellers, the Drumkinnon Development
Company, welcomed ''the solution that local people wanted''.
The local Labour MP, Mr John McFall, will also welcome the move, but
is still concerned about the price paid to bring the land back into
public ownership. He is concerned that Drumkinnon Development has
profited from planning permission granted by Scottish Secretary Ian Lang
in December.
He said there was now ''a scandalous situation'' whereby
Dunbartonshire Enterprise ''provided #2.6m from the public purse to buy
land from developers who have failed to see the grandiose plans they put
to Ian Lang materialise''.
He said the price must have reflected the enhanced value after the
Secretary of State granted planning permission, and he is to ask him how
much was paid for this land over and above the price paid initially by
the developers.
The land will be linked by footbridge to Balloch Country Park to
create what DE describes as an opportunity to make Loch Lomond a ''must
see'' tourist destination.
The development could include a visitor attraction on a Loch Lomond
theme, a shop window for Scottish crafts, a hotel, a children's play
area, and a wet weather centre.
The main development phase, costing up to #80m and creating a
projected 400 direct jobs, will be funded entirely by the private
sector, if DE has its way. If any further public funding is needed,
according to Mr MacInnes, it will be restricted to #10m over a period of
five or six years.
</TEXT>
