<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Poor students turning to drugs to cope</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LYNNE ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255541</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STUDENTS are turning to drugs to cope with the triple demands of
poverty, work, and study.
Strathclyde University NUS vice-president (welfare) Michelle Sherlock
yesterday said hard-pressed students were taking amphetamines to cope
with the stress of their lives.
''We do have a stimulant problem at Strathclyde, with students abusing
amphetamines as they juggle their workload and jobs to survive,'' she
said.
She claimed grants cutbacks had led to greater student debt and led
many to seek work to make ends meet, leaving them with less time for
study and forcing them to turn to drugs to stay awake to work into the
night to meet the demands of their courses.
''The thing that angers me is that if this was happening in big
business, it would not be allowed to happen. We have legislation to
protect employees, so why are we allowing this to carry on with
students,'' said Ms Sherlock.
The NUS aims to help by distributing leaflets raising awareness of
common stress symptoms and offering a sympathetic ear through
counsellors. The NUS said the case of a 20-year-old Edinburgh University
student who died after he was thought to have tried to control his sleep
patterns with chloroform earlier this month was an example of the
pressure students faced.
''Inevitably, students are going to slip through the net. We can't
make it any easier in terms of finance but we can listen and advise,''
said Ms Sherlock.
Strathclyde University's welfare officer had seen more than 6000
people in 1994 -- with an increasing number suffering from
poverty-related stress.
The NUS in Scotland claims a rapidly-increasing number of students now
have to work to survive because of grants cutbacks.
More than 200 staged a demonstration in Edinburgh yesterday,
protesting at a ''triple whammy'' of cuts in the Scottish Office
education budget.
The students say their grants have been cut back to just #1975 a year,
with further reductions expected over the next two years.
The NUS claims the mature students' allowance and benefits for
part-time students are also set to be axed by the Government.
Scottish NUS president Douglas Trainer said: ''Student poverty has
reached shocking levels and evidence is growing of the disturbing
effects on study performance and health. This triple whammy of cuts can
only make things worse.''
Mr Trainer said the problem was particularly acute in Scotland because
of the four-year degree programme.
The NUS in Scotland says student grants have fallen by almost half in
real terms since 1979. It estimates an average of 43% of students across
Scotland are combining employment and study in an effort to beat the
poverty trap.
</TEXT>
