<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>UK's oldest twins celebrate with older sister</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255542</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S oldest twins are planning their 98th birthday party -- and
the guest of honour will be their 100-year-old sister.
Annie and Fay Sutherland accord their longevity to hard work and the
fact that elder sister, Rita, has always been around to look after them.
The twins, daughters of a Victorian sea captain, managed bakers' shops
in Edinburgh until the 1950s, when they moved with Rita to Crieff to
manage a hotel.
The three sisters now live at Moyness Nursing Home in Broughty Ferry,
Dundee, where a party is planned for May 16. Staff will dress in
Victorian costumes.
Rita said: ''This is very exciting. I'm very proud of them. I still
look after them. I see Annie and Fay as my little sisters.''
None of the sisters married but Rita said: ''We all had plenty of
chances.''
She said: ''We've lived well and looked after ourselves.''
Mrs Sheilagh Andrew, matron at the home, said: ''It's been a big
surprise to find this out. To have a 100-year-old in the home is special
but having Britain's oldest twins as well is something else.''
However, Annie and Fay will not feature in the next edition of the
Guinness Book of Records. A spokesman explained: ''They won't be in the
book because we just list the oldest twins ever.''
That honour falls to twins born in Surrey in 1888. They reached 102.
</TEXT>
