<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chastened Tapie tells court: 'I'm finished'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255553</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Valenciennes, Wednesday
MAVERICK former Marseille football club boss and MP Bernard Tapie told
a French court he was ''finished'' as his trial on charges of
match-rigging and interfering with witnesses ended today.
After a dramatic eight-day hearing, a chastened Tapie, facing a
possible prison term, pleaded for clemency.
''This affair has finished me, ruined me, left me in a financial and
professional situation that is called oblivion,'' he said.
Presiding judge Bernard Langlade said the court would issue its
verdict on May 15, eight days after France's presidential election.
The public prosecutor has demanded a six-month prison term, with
another 12 months suspended, against the former left-wing Cabinet
Minister, who admitted to lying in court.
''I have already been heavily punished and I did not expect to be even
more so,'' Tapie said.
Prosecutor Eric de Montgolfier's request at the trial in the northern
mining town of Valenciennes was the first formal call for Tapie, who
faces a string of legal actions over his collapsed business empire, to
be sent to prison.
A self-made millionaire, Tapie was declared personally bankrupt and
ineligible to hold public office for five years in December. He has
appealed against that ruling.
The court today heard defence pleas on behalf of Tapie and five others
accused of rigging a 1993 league game between Marseille and Valenciennes
six days before his club won the European Cup against AC Milan.
Marseille won the match 1-0.
Tapie, accused by former right-hand man Jean-Pierre Bernes of
instigating the scam, denied to the end any involvement in the bribery
of Valenciennes players to throw the game.
However his alibi on the charge of tampering with witnesses collapsed
when a former Cabinet colleague, Jacques Mellick, admitted he had lied
in court and had not been in Tapie's office on June 17, 1993.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Belgian scandal claims deputy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE, EUROPEAN EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255554</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Brussels
A FESTERING political scandal in Belgium yesterday ensnared yet
another prominent public figure when Foreign Minister and deputy premier
Frank Vandenbroucke resigned after admitting ordering the burning of
cash.
Mr Vandenbroucke summoned journalists to tell them that in 1991, he
had issued an instruction for the incineration of money discovered in
secret safety boxes in a Brussels bank. The money, meant for the
Socialist Party, is suspected of being linked to illegal kick-backs
allegedly paid to senior Belgians by the Italian helicopter firm,
Agusta.
The scandal has so far led to the resignations of three ministers and
the murder in a Mafia-style attack of a prominent MP in Liege. Two weeks
ago the former head of the Belgian air force committed suicide in a
Brussels hotel room after being linked with the scandal.
It also threatens the future of Mr Willy Claes, former Foreign
Minister and recently-appointed the secretary general of Nato. He was
Finance Minister when the bribes were offered but claims he is innocent.
Mr Vandenbroucke said he had ordered the destruction of the money --
about #120,000 -- to comply with laws on financing political parties.
However party officials ignored his order, although he did not know that
at the time.
A statement from King Albert, who accepted his resignation, said Mr
Vandenbroucke would be succeeded as Foreign Minister by Development
Secretary Eric Derycke and by Interior Minister Johan Vande as deputy
premier.
Mr Vandenbroucke, 38, became Foreign Minister last year after Mr Claes
moved to Nato. Both men are members of the Flemish Socialist Party.
The scandal centres on bribes paid through a Swiss bank to senior
politicians by Agusta in return for the Belgian Government ordering 46
attack helicopters.
A Liege magistrate, Mrs Veronique Ancia, has become a national folk
heroine as she investigates the affair, which has also threatened the
position of Mr Karl van Miert, Belgium's respected member of the
European Commission.
On May 21 Belgians will vote in a General Election in which the
socialists, who rule in coalition with Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene's
Christian Democrats, are expected to pay a heavy price for the bribery
scandals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mandela raid ruled illegal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255555</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Johannesburg, Wednesday
PRESIDENT Nelson Mandela's estranged wife Winnie said after winning a
court battle to have a police search of her mansion and offices declared
illegal that her critics were ''hunting with the devil''.
Her remarks came after a judge ruled that police search warrants were
invalid and that documents seized in the raids should be handed back.
''The issuing magistrate did not appreciate that he needed reasonable
grounds to issue a warrant . . . The magistrate should not have issued a
warrant and it should be set aside,'' Judge Piet Streicher told the Rand
Supreme Court.
Police are investigating allegations of fraud and corruption against
Mrs Mandela, the deputy Minister of Arts, Culture, Science, and
Technology, over the awarding of building contracts to a firm in which
she had financial interests.
Officers raided her Soweto mansion and offices on March 1, when she
was away on an unauthorised visit to West Africa.
Mrs Mandela said in a statement: ''What this case has made clear is
that those who allow themselves to be used by certain sinister elements
both inside and outside the African National Congress, will in the end
find themselves hunting with the devil.
''They should therefore not be surprised when the masses call their
bluff.''
The ANC, in which Mrs Mandela heads the powerful women's league,
welcomed the ruling, describing the searches as ''melodramatic,
heavy-handed, and reminiscent of the past''.
''We hope the police will take note of the fact that South Africa is
no longer a police state where basic democratic rights of citizens could
be trampled upon without recourse to justice,'' an ANC statement said.
Police Commissioner George Fivaz said he was studying the decision and
Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi said there was no
suggestion in the judge's ruling of any wrongdoing by the police.
Mufamadi added that the criminal case against Mrs Mandela would
proceed.
Mrs Mandela, who was in West Africa when the raids took place, accuses
police of carrying out a witch-hunt against her and said she was not
guilty of any crime.
However she still has to face the music over her defiance of her
estranged husband's orders not to make the trip to West Africa.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000128</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000128</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dealer cleared in hijacking</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255556</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MADRID: Arms dealer Monzar Al Kassar was yesterday cleared of
supplying the arms to the Palestinian terrorists who hijacked the
Italian cruise liner Achille Lauro 10 years ago. The 49-year-old Costa
del Sol playboy, known as the Prince of Marbella, had been charged with
piracy. The liner's 600 passengers were held hostage in the hijacking
and an elderly wheelchair-bound American was shot dead and thrown
overboard.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000129</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000129</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Saddam's son 'recovers from coup attempt'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255557</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Amman, Wednesday
THERE were conflicting reports from Jordan today about the eldest son
of Iraqi dictator Saddam Hussein having hospital treatment in the
Jordanian capital Amman.
One source claimed he was being treated for gunshot wounds he
reportedly suffered in an assassination attempt in Baghdad last week,
but a senior Jordanian official dismissed the reports.
Odai Hussein, 31, underwent surgery on Monday shortly after he was
admitted to the King Hussein Medical Centre in Jordan.
Iraqi officials were tight-lipped, apparently seeking to avoid linking
his hospital treatment with reports of the assassination bid.
A Jordanian source said Odai was in the hospital's intensive care
unit. Two Iraqis, well informed on Saddam's family, said Odai had been
shot in the neck and the abdomen.
However hospital officials declined to confirm whether Odai was being
treated and Adel Ibrahim, spokesman for the Iraqi Embassy, flatly denied
the report.
Last Thursday Kurdish rebels claimed that Odai was wounded in a
Baghdad shooting amid widening reports of unrest and military moves
across Iraq.
The Patriotic Union of Kurdistan has been clashing with Saddam's
forces in northern Iraq for three weeks.
Opposition sources reported a coup attempt in Baghdad earlier this
month.
* Turkish troops have detained villagers suspected of being Kurdish
guerrillas in a huge operation against rebels in northern Iraq.
On the third day of a mission involving 35,000 soldiers, Turkish
troops searched houses in Derkar township, north-east of the border town
of Zakho, and detained some residents.
An Iraqi opposition group said hundreds of villagers were involved.
Amid growing international concern, US Defence Secretary William Perry
urged Ankara not to harm civilians and to complete the action as soon as
possible.
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel and French Foreign Minister Alain
Juppe voiced concern and questioned the legality of the operation.
The Foreign Office said: ''We are watching the situation closely and
with concern.''--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000130</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000130</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Danger signals point to Gulf</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255558</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Washington, Wednesday
THE diplomatic spotlight has suddenly swung to the Persian Gulf. Iran
has deployed 6000 troops, equipped with chemical weapons, on the Straits
of Hormuz and a new crisis with Iraq is brewing.
The United States remains determined to keep UN sanctions enforced
against Iraq, but has now to face the possibility that Iraq will
retaliate by breaking off its co-operation with UN control commissions.
The Americans argue that Saddam Hussein has not fully complied with
the UN resolutions that ended the 1991 war. He has not completely
destroyed all his chemical, nuclear, and biological weapons facilities
and has not satisfied Kuwait on its missing citizens and stolen
property, still less pay reparations.
President George Bush and his successor, President Clinton, hoped that
sanctions would force Saddam from office. He is still in power and
despite repeated rumours of coups, appears as strong as ever.
Now sanctions are up for renewal in May, and the Iraqis say that if
they are not lifted, or if no timetable for lifting them is offered,
then it will no longer consider itself bound by the UN resolutions. Its
position is supported by France and Russia.
It could expel the UN commissions, and might even revive its claims on
Kuwait. That might enable the United States to keep sanctions in force
indefinitely, but the purpose of the exercise is to bring Iraq to
civilised behaviour, not to ensure its permanent enmity.
As for Iran, the US secretary of defence, William Perry, is touring
the Gulf and announced today that Iran has moved substantial numbers of
troops to the Straits.
Their purpose in unknown, but they could, in theory, close the Gulf to
sea traffic and instantly cause chaos in world oil supplies.
Mr Perry confirmed that Iran had also deployed chemical weapons.
''We really do not know why Iran would choose to deploy chemical
weapons there but we consider it a very negative factor,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000131</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000131</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Worker charged in post robbery</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255559</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MONTCLAIR: Christopher Green, a 29-year-old former postal worker
intent on stealing enough to pay his back rent, was last night charged
with killing four men in a post office robbery in the quiet New York
suburb of Montclair. The town was in mourning yesterday after two post
office clerks, both known to the accused from when he worked there, and
two customers were shot dead. A lone survivor, computer expert David
Grossman, 44, was critically wounded in hospital but was able to tell
police about the killings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000132</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000132</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cousin incriminates accused in killing of Briton</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255560</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Gainesville, Wednesday
MURDER accused John ''Billy Joe'' Crumitie told of shooting into the
car at a Florida rest stop where British tourist Gary Colley was slain
and his girlfriend wounded, his cousin testified.
''He said he shot the bitch and Aundra (Akins) shot the man,'' said
Thaddeus Crumitie.
Akins, 16, who prosecutors say fired the shot that killed Gary Colley,
has pleaded guilty to second-degree murder. He has agreed to testify
against Crumitie.
John Crumitie is on trial for the second time in the murder of Mr
Colley and the wounding of Margaret Jagger at a rest stop near
Monticello in September 1993. His first trial ended in a mistrial when
the jury was unable to reach a verdict.
Thaddeus Crumitie also testified he wore a ''bug'' supplied by police
trying to capture his cousin on tape making the admission, but tape
quality was poor. He also said he wore a wire to record statements from
some of the other young men originally charged in the case.
Earlier Ms Jagger, who has sat in the courtroom since testifying
yesterday, began to cry when medical examiner Dr Thomas Wood began to
describe Mr Colley's wounds.
He said one was caused by a .38-calibre bullet. Crumitie is accused of
firing a .22-calibre pistol into the air, while Atkins fired the
larger-calibre pistol.
Dr Wood's testimony followed that of a firearms expert who said the
bullet found in Mr Colley's chest was fired by the same gun used in a
motel robbery the day before the murder.
It also matched a bullet dug out of the couple's rented car.
There is no physical evidence linking Crumitie to the crime scene and
Ms Jagger could not pick him out of a police lin-eup. Crumitie testified
at his first trial that he was home sleeping when the attack occurred.
His new trial was moved south from Monticello, where the attack and
first trial occurred, because of concern about publicity. The attack on
the couple was the last of several on foreigners two years ago that
tarnished Florida's reputation as a tourist destination.--AP/Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000133</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000133</DOCID>
