<RECORDNO>979255571</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE first Scottish Canals Week is launched on Saturday. The activities
are organised as part of British Waterways' Millennium Link proposals
for the re-opening of canals between Bowling, Grangemouth, Glasgow, and
Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000143</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000143</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Little hope held out for sleeper campaign</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGREGOR, PARLIAMENTARY CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255572</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Office Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton made clear last
night that the sleeper service to Fort William is unlikely to be saved.
The Government still is fighting a rearguard action, but at Scottish
Questions the best that could be done was to put a gloss on the
situation.
Lord James said that the new Euro-sleeper service between Glasgow and
Paris, to be introduced next year, could be timetabled to connect with
daytime services to Fort William.
The Minister said: ''The franchising director has undertaken to look
at timetabling flexibility in daytime connections and that will be
important for day services to Fort William. These services will tie up
with other services, including the new sleeper service between Glasgow
and Paris to be introduced next year.''
The Minister came under pressure from Labour's Brian Wilson to
subsidise the threatened services, while a proper consultation process
took place. The services should not be ''condemned without trial,'' he
said.
However, Lord James told him: ''I cannot agree to divert funds from
education, health and social work for the purposes you have mentioned.''
Earlier, SNP leader Alex Salmond raised concerns over the future of
sleeper and Motorail services to Scotland.
He said the Government had compared the subsidy for these services
with the subsidy for passengers in the South-east of England, and
implied this was unfair.
He demanded: ''What hope is there for the consultation exercise when
the rolling stock is going to be stuck up a siding, when the Transport
Secretary already has made up his mind, and when the Scottish Office
team is in a state of total paralysis, unable to defend the Scottish
interest?''
Scottish Secretary Ian Lang responded that cash invested in rail
infrastructure south of the Border did benefit Scotland. He said: ''The
#300m upgrading of the East Coast main line benfited Scotland, the #600m
investment plan for the West Coast main line will benefit Scotland.
''It is a measure of the short-sightedness and narrow-mindedness of
the SNP that they cannot understand the benefits to Scotland which
accrue from services like the Channel Tunnel.''
* The Liberal Democrats yesterday issued a questionnaire to all
Conservative candidates in the forthcoming local elections asking for
their views on railway privatisation, Motorail and the Fort William
sleeper.
</TEXT>
