<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000144</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000144</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Government pledge averts defeat on immigration controls. Europe sceptics angry as Howard wins vote.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENEDICT BROGAN, POLITICAL REPORTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255573</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government avoided an embarrassing defeat in a Commons committee
yesterday by promising to put before Parliament any changes in Britain's
immigration laws resulting from the implementation of European
legislation.
Home Secretary Michael Howard's pledge to consult MPs won over Tory
Euro-sceptic Bernard Jenkin, who had threatened to support a Labour
amendment that would have forced a debate on the floor of the Commons on
European proposals for loosening visa requirements.
The Government's victory left Euro-sceptic Tory MPs complaining of a
lack of democracy.
After the vote whipless rebel Sir Teddy Taylor kicked the partition
separating MPs from the public as he left. ''They might as well close
this place down,'' he said.
The debate also was attended by former Chancellor Norman Lamont, not a
member of the committee.
He said he believed the matter should be discussed on the floor of the
House, adding: ''It's potentially an explosive issue.''
The two-and-half hour debate in the normally quiet Standing Committee
B on European legislation was heavily attended by MPs from the
Euro-sceptic wing of the Tory Party. The rules of the committee allow
non-members to speak, but not vote.
Those who did speak, including several of the nine MPs who have had
the whip withdrawn, said the Government was allowing the EU to undermine
British immigration controls without consulting Parliament.
Sir Teddy told the Home Secretary: ''Unless we get it written into
European law, the EC will step by step sweep away every part of our
immigration controls.''
Mr Howard said the External Frontier Convention would in no way affect
Britain's right to control immigration. Just because a non-EU national
was granted a visa by Portugal did not mean Britain would have to grant
that person entry.
However, another whipless rebel, Mr Tony Marlow, pressed Mr Howard to
explain what the Government would do if its interpretation was
over-ruled by the European Court. ''Are we going to break the law?'' he
said.
Mr Howard said any change would require the unanimous approval of EU
members. ''We would not give our approval to any directive or regulation
that had the effect of dismantling our frontier controls,'' he said.
The Tory benches were packed with MPs from the anti-EU wing of the
party, including , Tayside North MP Bill Walker, the former Imigration
Minister Charles Wardle, and Euro-sceptics Bill Cash and Nicholas
Budgen.
They pressed Mr Howard to explain how far the Government was prepared
to go to defend British immigration laws against tampering by Brussels
or the European Court of Justice.
Mr Howard repeated the Prime Minister's promise that the Government
would take any steps necessary to preserve Britain's external frontiers.
''It is very important that we retain our existing frontier controls,''
he said.
''We do not see it as a step towards the abolition of internal
frontiers. We have no intention of dismantling our frontiers and we will
take whatever steps are necessary to ensure that they are not removed.''
Draft of the convention on controls at external and internal frontiers
are under discussion in Brussels. They include a proposed ''mutual
recognition of visas'' regime whereby someone granted a visa by another
EU state could then enter the UK without a separate UK visa.
EU members are also negotiating a ''common visa list'' of non-EU
countries whose nationals would be required to have a visa to enter any
EU country. Labour claims it would hit people from at least 28
Commonwealth countries.
Shadow Home Secretary Jack Straw said a convention that would threaten
civil liberties and compromise Britain's policy of controlling
immigration should be debnated and voted on by all MPs on the floor of
the House.
The commitee voted on party lines by seven to six against Labour's
amendment. Afterwards Mr Jenkin, MP for Colchester North, said the
''very warm assurances'' he had received from Mr Howard persuaded him
not to rebel.
''I was always going to support the Government if I got sufficient
undertakings that the Commons and Parliament would have ample
opportunity to debate the effects of the External Frontiers Convention
before ratification,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000145</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000145</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Premier makes the latest gaffe</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255574</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The Prime Minister yesterday was accused of the latest Government
gaffe -- only 24 hours after setting up a team described as the
''committee for banana skins''.
Just six days after a verbal clanger by Chancellor Kenneth Clarke over
Consett in Durham, the text of a letter was released suggesting the
Prime Minister does not know his trade union history.
The letter, carrying Mr Major's signature, refers to the late former
seamen's leader Jim Slater as the ex-president and general secretary of
the National Union of Mineworkers.
It was sent to Shadow Defence Secretary David Clark, MP for South
Shields, Tyne and Wear, where Mr Slater lived.
Dr Clark said he was ''flabbergasted'' at the mistake.
A Downing Street spokeswoman said: ''It's an unfortunate clerical
error.''
The letter was written following a newspaper article last month
containing claims that the KGB considered former Labour leader Michael
Foot and others, including Mr Slater, to be agents of influence.
Dr Clark was outraged by the allegations about Mr Slater.He wrote to
Mr Major to complain about the article -- but the reply, dated March 16
and signed John M, upset him further.
It reads:''Thank you for your letter of 22 February about the
allegations in the Sunday Times about the late Jim Slater, the former
president and general secretary of the National Union of Mineworkers.
''I have considerable sympathy with some of your concerns about the
Sunday Times's story. But this is not a matter for the Government.
''As you know, Michael Foot has decided to take action against the
Sunday Times in respect of the allegations against him.''
Dr Clark said he was ''very annoyed'' about Mr Major's mistake over
''one of the best-known and campaigning leaders in the history of the
trade union movement''.
He added: ''It is outrageous that someone with access to the best
advisers in the world could make such an elementary mistake. This
blunder just compounds the damage.''
Mr Slater's brother, Walter, who used to be NUM lodge secretary at the
former Westoe Colliery, South Shields, said: ''This is a bloody
disgrace.
''All these people are nuggets -- they can't get anything right. If it
wasn't so serious, it would be laughable. It is beyond comprehension.''
</TEXT>
