<DOCNO>GH950323-000146</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000146</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cult raid uncovers starving faithful and gas stockpile</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>EUGENE MOOSA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255575</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Tokyo, Thursday
JAPANESE police raided a large complex of the Aum Shinri Kyo sect in
the village of Kamiku-Isshiki, west of Tokyo, for the second successive
day.
Yesterday about 2500 officers, backed by a chemical warfare unit,
raided 25 buildings belonging to the sect across the nation, inluding
Tokyo and in the village 63 miles west of the capital.
Officers, backed by a chemical warfare unit and caged canaries to
sniff gas, found stockpiles of a toxic chemical linked to the Tokyo
subway nerve gas attacks and rescued victims who said they had been held
against their will.
Yesterday's raid, the largest since a 1972 operation against the Japan
Red Army, officially stemmed from an abduction charge.
Officials have not publicly linked the sect to Monday's rush-hour
attacks on five subway trains, which killed 10 people and left nearly
5500 ill. Seventy remain in a critical condition.
Police sources said they were certainly investigating the sect over
the case, but gave no details.
Police said the swoop yielded 34 big containers of acetonitrile, a
toxic chemical found in the subway after the attacks, along with
residues of the nerve gas sarin.
As police moved in, sect followers screamed in protest. About 50
followers were taken to hospital in a comatose state suffering from
starvation.
Police said they had rescued six people who had apparently been held
against their will. One 23-year-old Yokohama woman told police she had
been forcibly detained.
Police said they had arrested five sect officials, three of them
doctors, on illegal confinement charges.
In a chilling message echoing the end of other doomsday cults, the
elusive head of the Aum Shinri Kyo was reported to have told followers
this week: ''It's time to carry out the salvation plan and to greet
death without regrets.''
Cult members based in Russia denied that other followers had carried
out the Japanese attack, and in fact claimed cult members had been
gassed in Tokyo and Moscow.
The Japanese director of the sect's Moscow branch, identifying himself
only as Juyu, told a news conference, ''They say in Japan that Aum
Shinri Kyo has spread poison gas, but that's far from being true.''
In fact, he added, ''in Japan we have suffered gas attacks''. He did
not elaborate.
Prime Minister Tomiichi Murayama, vowing to take all necessary
measures to avert a repeat of Monday's ''hideous crime'', said he would
seek a blanket ban on sarin and other such lethal gases.
Media suspicion fell on the sect because of an incident last July near
its Kamiku-Ishhiki complex when the national police forensic team
detected sarin in the ground nearby.
Search warrants for today's raids were issued in connection with the
abduction last month of 69-year-old Kiyoshi Kariya, last seen being
pushed into a van by four men on a street near his home in central
Tokyo.
Kariya's younger sister had been trying to break with the sect after
pledging family assets as a donation.
Police did not find Kariya, and neither did they find guru Shoko
Asahara who founded the group in 1987. He claims he can levitate himself
and teaches that the world will end in 1997.
It emerged today that at least one Briton is known to have been drawn
into the Aum Shinri Kyo cult, and that worried families have contacted
watchdogs such as the Cult Information Centre seeking help about
relatives.--Reuter/AP.
</TEXT>
