<DOCID>GH950323-000150</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Islands ferry crews to take strike ballot</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255579</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FERRY crews in Orkney are to be balloted on possible strike action, it
was announced yesterday.
The islands' council-owned ferry company said the men had been offered
a generous pay deal and that a strike would have a devastating effect on
remote communities.
However, Steve Todd, Scottish shipping organiser for the RMT union,
said crews wanted more time ashore rather than extra money.
He said the 29 men serving on the three ferries serving the outer
North Isles presently work three weeks on, two weeks off.
For three years, they had been seeking an even-time arrangement of two
weeks on, two weeks off, or one week on, one week off.
This had been rejected when he held talks with directors of Orkney
Islands Shipping Company, said Mr Todd.
He said a ballot on industrial action would be held next month.
Councillor Stephen Hagan, the shipping company chairman, said crews
had been offered a backdated rise of 1.5% plus #100 from April last year
with another increase of 1.4% plus #100 from next month.
</TEXT>
