<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000151</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000151</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Seatbelt plea over pupils</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255580</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A BILL to make seatbelts mandatory on school buses was introduced
yesterday by Clydesdale MP Jimmy Hood in memory of two young
constituents.
The Bill would make seat-belts compulsory in all buses and coaches
carrying children; outlaw overcrowding on seats; and require supervision
of children by someone other than the driver.
He dedicated the Bill to the memory of Tony Cousins, 13, and Francis
Scorgie, 15, pupils at Biggar High School, who died after a bus accident
on February 17 last year.
The 10-minute rule Bill will not have Government support, but draft
regulations published this week will require seatbelts for children. Mr
Hood said the measures were ''too little too late''.
</TEXT>
