<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000152</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000152</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A few MPs get on with the real work of the House</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>COMMONS SKETCH</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979255581</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE exciting part of the day -- Scottish Questions -- was over. Labour
had said the Scottish economy was in trouble; Mr Ian Lang had said it
was wonderful. Mr George Robertson had promised devolution yet again; Mr
Ian Lang had said it was a terrible idea; Labour attacked on the water,
health and railway fronts; Mr Lang and his tiny army fought them at the
barricades.
Still, fun can't go on for ever. To work. As about 600 MPs busied
themselves outside the Chamber, 17 or occasionally 16 remained to deal
with the remaining stages of the Jobseeker's Bill.
The Sketch expected a bigger turnout in the Press Gallery than
actually occurred because the short title of the Bill describing its
main aims includes ''the assistance of persons without a settled way of
life,'' which would seem to cover journalists quite exactly.
But no, the Chamber was plunged into that dead atmosphere which
denotes that boring though necessary things are being done. Feeling that
even a Sketch should have its educative moments, the Sketch tried to
take it in.
This was not easy as Mr Keith Bradley (Manchester Withington) was
moving a Labour new clause in a speech written in impenetrable prose and
delivered in a monotone which had the odd effect of making one feel one
was hearing a blur. Mr Bradley looks born to be a middle-ranking
Minister who does most of the work of a department while flashier
colleagues have all the fun.
The Sketch worked out he was on the side of the angels, a conclusion
ratified when, first, the stunning Liberal Democrat Miss Liz Lynne
(Rochdale) and then the stunning wet Tory Mr Alan Howarth
(Stratford-upon-Avon) gave it their support.
Miss Lynne, a strapping, dark haired lady, normally clad in
eye-catching and becoming primary colours, unfairly adds to all that a
throaty voice which must have tempted many a Minister to abandon his
briefing notes and accept all her amendments
We will have to wait and see, though perhaps not for so long, what
effect Mr Howarth will have on female Labour Ministers. He has the looks
of one whom American political parties hope will be available to run for
President and, or perhaps one should say but, appears a very decent sort
of guy.
He was worried that some disabled people will find under the new
system that they will qualify neither for an incapacity allowance,
through not being disabled enough for the rules, nor for the Jobseeker's
Allowance, which is to replace unemployment benefit, through not being
fit enough to meet the rules governing that.
The exchanges illustrated an important parliamentary truth -- the most
boring debates are often the most important. There were no fireworks but
some MPs were trying to ensure that a group with enough problems already
would be fairly treated.
Dr Norman Godman (Greenock and Port Glasgow -- Lab.) joined in on
behalf of thousands of women between 60 and 65 whose benefit has been
suspended while a European Court of Justice judgment on their
entitlement is awaited. Such debates can bring home better than grander
setpieces that what Parliament does touches virtually every citizen's
life.
Miss Anne Widdecombe, the combative but able junior Social Security
Minister, argued that disabled jobseekers will be able to qualify the
number of hours, etc, they are able to work and still be eligible for
benefit. She then saw off and onslaught on behalf of those studying
while unemployed by Mr Ian McCartney, using a barrage of recycled
cliches.
This was ''knee jerk opposition'' said Miss Widdecombe. There were no
cuts in part-time study. The Opposition should withdraw and they ''might
even like to apologise''. Mr McCartney was too incensed at this
impudence to more than splutter -- briefly, for his colleagues were
hanging around waiting to vote and then be off, perhaps to an early high
tea.
Some 531 MPs of whom 17 had heard the debate trooped into the
lobbies. The Government won 277 to 254 and Labour returned to the charge
with a thinly disguised bid to introduce a statutory minimum wage. The
Sketch decided that it would be too painful to watch Miss Widdecombe
knock spots off that and left.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000153</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000153</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Six life terms for train gunman</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255582</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
New York, Wednesday
RAILROAD gunman Colin Ferguson, who killed six people and wounded 19
others aboard a Long Island commuter train, was sentenced to life in
prison today, with families of his victims applauding the punishment.
''I have never presided over a trial with such a selfish and
self-centred defendant as you,'' said Nassau County Court Judge Donald
Belfi, calling Ferguson a coward and sentencing him to ''the functional
equivalent of life without parole''.
''What is even more remarkable is your total lack of remorse,'' he
added.
The judge gave Ferguson the maximum sentence under the law -- life
sentences for each of his six second-degree murder convictions and up to
25 years for each of his 19 attempted murder convictions. The sentences
are to be served consecutively.
''You will never, never return to society,'' the judge told him. ''You
will spend the rest of your natural life in prison.''
Belfi remarked that Ferguson ''unfortunately'' was not subject to the
death penalty, newly signed into state law.
Jamaican-born Ferguson stood impassively, although his face twitched
several times. He was found guilty of opening fire on the Long Island
Rail Road train on December 7, 1993.
Before he was sentenced, Ferguson made a rebuttal statement to victims
who had appeared in court yesterday to describe how they had suffered at
his hands. But as he began, the victims rose and walked out. Most
returned when the judge began to speak, and broke into applause when it
was over. Many then voiced their relief.
''A lot of the anger is gone,'' said Robert Guigliano, who had shouted
at Ferguson yesterday: ''Five minutes -- that's all I need with you.''
''I didn't get the five minutes, but that's all right,'' said
Guigliano, who was shot in the chest but survived.
Ferguson, after being found mentally competent, acted as his own
attorney in the bizarre trial. His courtroom performance was
characterised by frequent nonsensical ramblings as he confronted his
victims on the witness stand.
He said a white man had taken his gun and did the shooting, and that
he was framed because he is black.--Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000154</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sentence on mother is upheld by judges</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE MCKAIN, LAW CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255583</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THREE appeal court judges yesterday backed Kilmarnock Sheriff David
Smith over his decision to impose a 60-day sentence on a young mother of
two.
The sheriff imposed the 60-day sentence on Victoria Leiper, 19, on
January 10 this year after she admitted attempting to defeat the ends of
justice.
She admitted falsely telling police that her husband had threatened
her with a real gun when she knew the gun was a toy.
Her husband was kept in custody for almost a month and was finally
admonished by Sheriff Smith.
Yesterday, at the Justiciary Appeal Court, Mr Alan Muir, counsel for
Leiper, who has two children aged 10 months and 22 months, argued that
because of his client's personal circumstances the custodial sentence
was excessive and inappropriate.
He explained that she had been only 18 at the time of the offence and
was a first offender.
According to background reports, she had committed the offence out of
fear, firstly of her husband, and secondly of the court.
She was now divorced and if she had to serve the sentence her two
children would have to be looked after by her mother who would have to
give up her job.
She would normally serve half of her sentence and had already spent a
week in custody, leaving 23 days to go.
Mr Muir accepted the offence was a serious one but asked the court to
defer sentence to give Leiper the chance to demonstrate that she could
keep out of trouble and to assess her suitability for community service.
Lord Allanbridge, who heard the appeal with Lords Mayfield and Morton,
said the seriousness of the offence was that Leiper had given false
information to the police which she did not withdraw until the day of
her husband's trial.
The judge said it was an anxious case because it involved a young
first offender.
In his report to the appeal court, the sheriff had explained that
because of Leiper's false statement her husband had been charged with a
crime for which he could have been jailed for many months.
On the morning of the trial, Leiper had admitted that she had known
the gun was a toy but that, maliciously for vindictive reasons, she had
led police to believe the firearm was real.
The sheriff took the view that the false accusation of a crime was in
itself a grave crime, rendering the victim liable to unjustified
incarceration and causing unnecessary work and inconvenience to police
and members of the public.
As far as he was concerned, the gravity of the offence far outweighed
the personal circumstances of the accused.
Lord Allanbridge said the appeal court also considered that this was a
very serious charge.
He added: ''In all the circumstances, we cannot say that the sheriff
was not entitled to impose a custodial sentence.
He made the sentence a short one, and it will remain a short one, but
it must remain because it was an appropriate disposal.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000155</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000155</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Progress on seafront plan</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255584</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PLANS are finally under way to develop Oban's waterfront, with the
official planning application now lodged.
Argyll and Bute District Council and developer Iain Wotherspoon have
been in a ''stalemate'' for months over the prime site.
The council has pressed for an ice rink as part of the development
project while Mr Wotherspoon has held to plans for a bowling rink.
However, following recent talks with councillors, Mr Wotherspoon, of
Lismore Developments Ltd, is hopeful that he will be given the go-ahead.
Councillor Campbell Cameron said: ''The talks went very well. It was a
very positive meeting.''
Mr Wotherspoon hopes his plans will be passed at the May planning
meeting and added: ''There is no reason why we couldn't start the work
straight after that.
''It is now a #4.5m project. Costs have been going up all the time, so
we would have to carry it out on a phased basis.
''I would try to start with the visitors' centre and the 24 flats in
the first phase of work.''
The application is for a leisure centre and parking, incorporating a
cafe, office, visitors' centre, library, and exhibition area, to include
a retail sales area and bowling rinks.
Mr Wotherspoon said: ''There is one principal issue which is still
outstanding.'' He would not comment further but it is understood the
matter concerns the financing of the new library.
A further meeting will be held with councillors on March 29 and he was
hopeful he would get council support for his project then.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000156</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000156</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mixed response to health complaints move</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MACDERMID, MEDICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255585</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROPOSALS for a new system to deal with complaints about the National
Health Service got a mixed reception yesterday from doctors' and
patients' representatives.
The plans, announced by Scottish Secretary Ian Lang in response to a
report on existing procedures, Being Heard, will leave a three-tier
system for dealing with patients' complaints about service from
hospitals or GPs.
Stage one will be a response from the provider of the service, with
the aim of dealing with the complaint on the spot through rapid informal
responses and, possibly, conciliation.
Stage two will be the opportunity of a review of the complaint by a
panel with an independent lay chairman, a non-executive member of the
NHS trust and a non-executive member of the health board concerned.
Independent clinical assessors will provide professional advice in the
case of complaints involving clinical judgement.
Stage three will be recourse to the Health Service Commissioner
(Ombudsman) whose jurisdiction will be widened so that he can cover all
complaints including clinical complaints and complaints against GPs and
other primary care practitioners.
The Scottish Consumer Council and the Association of Local Health
Councils both welcomed the proposals, but the association's director
Patricia Dawson said: ''We will be interested to see more detail about
how the independent chairmen of the stage two procedures are appointed.
However we welcome the emphasis on reconciliation and speedy resolution.
That is what people want.''
The British Medical Association regretted that the Government appeared
to be moving away from the present informal procedure for hospitals,
towards a more legalistic process.
Mr James Johnson, chairman of the BMA consultants' committee, said:
''Giving NHS trusts the responsibility for organising complaints
procedure is yet further evidence of the gradual break-up of a National
Health Service.
''Complainants are unlikely to be convinced that trusts will be
impartial when investigating complaints about themselves. We regard the
need for independent medical assessors as paramount.''
* In the Commons, Mr John McAllion, for the Opposition, asked how the
Government could justify the introduction of local pay bargaining
''which means that nurses and midwives in one part of Scotland will be
paid less than nurses and midwives in another part.'' He demanded the
abolition of pay bargaining and urged the Government to ''instruct the
management in every NHS trust in Scotland to pay the full 3% to all
nurses and midwives, with no strings attached?''
Scottish Health Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton said: ''Those at
the sharp end of the health service should be paid the rate for the
job.''
</TEXT>
