<DOCNO>GH950323-000157</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000157</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Protest over 'cost-cutting' justice measures</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DUNCAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255586</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government yesterday was accused of increasing the risk of
miscarriages of justice in Scottish courts in its determination to cut
costs.
The attack was made by Mr Paul Langan, president of the Glasgow Bar
Association, whose members are concerned by a ''considerable number'' of
the clauses in the Criminal Justice (Scotland) Bill.
Mr Langan will visit the Commons today to lobby MPs as the Bill
reaches its committee stage. He will be joined by representatives of the
Law Society of Scotland.
The Glasgow association has criticised the Government for not having a
Royal Commission prior to presenting the Bill before Parliament, and
claims the consultation periods on various papers relating to the
reforms were too short
It is especially worried about clauses relating to juries, judicial
examination, and an accused person's right to silence.
Mr Langan said yesterday: ''This Bill is a series of cost-cutting
measures by the Government and there is a danger that the whole
combination will result in an increase in justice miscarrying.''
The reforms which worry the association include the removal of
occupations from lists of potential jurors, and the abolition of the
right to object to potential jurors.
Mr Langan said: ''We should recognise that knowledge about jurors,
their occupations, and the right of challenge are vital safeguards to
prevent unfairness to the accused and the possibility of justice
miscarrying.''
The abolition of the right to challenge potential jurors had
significant Treasury implications, he said. ''If this clause becomes
law, there will be substantial savings to the public purse in the number
of potential jurors that require to be cited at a sitting. I think such
Treasury implications run through this Bill.''
The association also is concerned by the proposed strengthening of the
judicial examination, a procedure gone through when an accused is
brought to court on a serious charge. It says the changes would amount
to inviting accused persons to admit crimes at an early stage in
proceedings when they would have little information about the evidence
against them.
Mr Langan said the most unpopular reform was the ''attack'' on the
accused's right of silence, the proposal to allow the prosecution to
comment in court on an accused person choosing not to give evidence.
''The clause, in our view, simply erodes a cardinal principle of our
system, that the burden of proof in a criminal trial rests with the
Crown. It is an attempt to introduce an alien concept to our system.''
</TEXT>
