<DOCNO>GH950323-000160</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000160</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH, LOCAL GOVERNMENT CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255589</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
* Scottish Liberal Democrats were trying to spoil the SNP launch in
Perth yesterday, focusing their attention on the forthcoming
Parliamentary by-election, writes Local Government Correspondent Frances
Horsburgh.
Opening the party's election headquarters, president Robert Maclennan
said voters had the choice of choosing a party which aimed to break up
Britain, or choose the Liberal Democrats who had a clear message for the
constutuency.
Meanwhile, at a press conference in Edinburgh, SNP leaders yesterday
claimed that where they were in power they had already put into practice
the ''Fresh Start'' principles on which their local elections campaign
was based.
The party's vice convener for publicity John Swinney said the SNP had
developed eight principles covering water, local services, open local
government, fuel poverty, concessionery travel, housing, nursery
education and economic development.
For example, he said, SNP councillors in Highland and elsewhere had
been active in seeking to set up shadow water authorities which would
monitor the three new quangos the Government was setting up to run the
services.
</TEXT>
