<DOCNO>GH950323-000161</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000161</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bitter clash on Scots economy and devolution</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN MCGREGOR, PARLIAMENTARY CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255590</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANGRY exchanges over the Scottish economy and Labour's plans for
devolution dominated Scottish Question Time in the Commons yesterday.
At one stage, Speaker Betty Boothroyd had to call for order as Labour
MP George Galloway (Glasgow Hillhead) tried to shout down Scottish
Office Minister George Kynoch.
Mr Galloway followed Dr John Reid (Motherwell North -- Lab.) in
attacking the Government over the disappearance of manufacturing jobs in
Scotland, particularly at Rolls-Royce.
He argued that the Government was presiding over an economy in which
people had low-paid, short-term jobs, compared with what they used to
have, and he demanded to know when the Government would ''clear out and
give the Scottish economy a chance?''
Mr Kynoch told him there was no point in harking back to the past when
what was required was forward thinking. ''Business in Scotland has to
adapt to what the market requires,'' he said. ''Scottish business is
looking up, members opposite are looking downwards and backwards''
The angry atmosphere was reflected in the exchanges on devolution.
Lady Olga Maitland (Sutton and Cheam -- Con.) said businesses were
threatening to ''pack up and leave Scotland, taking jobs and investment
with them.''
She said the assembly would have tax-raising powers which would cost
taxpayers 3p in the pound, affecting every family in Scotland.
Mr Lang replied that the tax-raising powers which, he claimed, would
cost the average family more than #6 a week, was ''only the beginning of
what Labour would seek to achieve with tax-raising powers in a Scottish
Parliament.''
As the argument raged, the Tories raised Labour leader Tony Blair's
weekend ''gaffe'' in which he said that all Scottish Bills now go
through a Scottish Grand Committee.
Mr Lang said that if the Leader of the Opposition did not know how the
House handled Scottish legislation, how on earth was he in a position to
say how a Scottish Parliament would.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson said one of the roles for a
Scottish Parliament, which he pledged Labour would deliver, would be to
take Scotland's water back into full democratic control.
He challenged Mr Lang: ''Today, on the anniversary of the 97% bloody
nose the people in the Strathclyde referendum gave you, will you now
recognise that Scotland's water, which is among the safest and cheapest
and cleanest in the world, is going to be transformed by your
quangoisation into the most expensive in Europe?
''Why on earth do you not recognise the folly of your arrogant refusal
to listen to the people of Scotland and abandon this plan now?
Mr Lang retorted: ''You are lamentably ignorant of the facts of this
matter.'' The creation of the new water authorities would ''lead to the
more efficient delivery of water and sewerage systems at the least extra
cost to the people of Scotland.''
</TEXT>
