<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Storm of protest in the wake of Pintail</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ELIZABETH BUIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255592</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Elizabeth Buie charts the troubled voyage of the Pacific Pintail --
the ship the world does not want to know because of the radioactive
cargo it as transporting from France to Japan
ABRITISH ship loaded with 14 tons of high-level nuclear waste, en
route from France to Japan, is now sailing into the staunchly
anti-nuclear South Pacific.
The British-flagged ship, the Pacific Pintail, which is being shadowed
by the Greenpeace ship NV Solo as it travels half-way across the world,
has already encountered political condemnation from Caribbean and South
American states and taken part in a dramatic confrontation with the
Chilean Navy.
The environmental campaigners Greenpeace have raised the spectre that
an accident involving the ship could be of similar dimensions to the
Chernobyl explosion.
The Pintail, operated by Pacific Nuclear Transport Ltd (PNTL), a
subsidiary of British Nuclear Fuels, is carrying radioactive waste from
the nuclear reprocessing plant run by France's state-owned Cogema group
to Japan. Cogema's customers include some of Japan's main electricity
utilities who use its facilities to reprocess spent nuclear fuel rods
and plutonium.
Cogema, like BNFL (whose Thorp reprocessing facility is only now
coming on stream) is committed to sending back all the waste to its
customer.
Thus, as long as Cogema has reprocessing contracts with Japan, and
BNFL is poised to accept them, the Pintail's shipment is likely to be
the first of many regular shipments of waste.
The waste is the 3% residue left after uranium fuel rods, originally
brought to the European countries for reprocessing from the Japanese
utilities, have been stripped of re-usable material. Usable, unburnt
uranium comprising 96% of the imported spent fuel rods is recycled by
BNFL and the French company Cogema into new fuel rods for power
generation, while the small amount of waste is dealt with in a
relatively new process of vitrification. This process involves mixing
the waste with molten glass and pouring it into 1.3m high stainless
steel containers. As the molten material cools, the waste becomes locked
into the solid glass.
The vitrified waste is carried in specially designed flasks; massive
steel structures which weigh more than 100 tonnes each. The flasks are
subjected to rigorous tests laid down by the International Atomic Energy
Agency, including two ''drop'' tests -- one on to a solid unyielding
surface and the other on to a steel spike.
The ships used for carrying nuclear material -- in 20 years PNTL have
transported nuclear material more than three million miles by sea
without an incident resulting in the release of radioactivity -- are
covered by regulations laid down by the International Maritime
Organisation.
Regulators regard these ships as among the safest afloat, and few
would deny that oil tankers and even ships carrying chemical waste have
a much worse record. Nevertheless, the potential damage of a nuclear
accident is enough to cause the kind of political protest that the
passage of the Pintail has created.
However, Dr Edwin Lyman, an American research associate with the
Center for Energy and Environmental Studies at Princeton University, has
produced a report for Greenpeace claiming that the nuclear industry is
sacrificing safety to cut costs.
Certain of his criticisms based on the kind of seals used on waste
caskets and the temperature of waste transported have been described as
''inaccurate'' by BNFL.
Meanwhile, as the Pintail battles through 30-ft waves and 70mph winds,
rounding Cape Horn, the debate over whether nuclear waste should be
transported by sea -- or even transported at all -- is raging unabated.
First to protest were the Caribbean Community leaders, who appealed to
the governments of Britain, France and Japan to avoid their coastlines,
''now and in the future''.
Then, representatives in Washington of the US possessions of Puerto
Rico, the US Virgin Islands, American Samoa, and Guam, and of the US
State of Hawaii, asked President Clinton to demand that the British,
French, and Japanese government postpone the shipment of nuclear waste
until concerns over safety had been resolved.
South African politicians expressed their disquiet that the Pintail
might go round the Cape of Good Hope, and asked the relevant governments
to ''dispel our doubts by removing the secrecy shrouded around this
shipment''.
Protests have also been delivered by the Micronesian state of
Kiribati, one of the smallest nations in the South Pacific with a
population of 78,000, Fiji, the Federated States of Micronesia, and the
Republic of Nauru.
The most decisive action, however, came from the Chilean Government in
Santiago which attempted to ban the Pintail from its 200-mile exclusive
economic zone. The Chilean patrol vessel Macalvi approached the Pintail
shortly after she entered the Chilean EEZ, but the Pintail's captain
refused to change course. The Chilean navy later reported that the
Pintail had changed course, but not, apparently, until the Chilean
captain threatened to use force.
According to Greenpeace the Chilean navy ship warned that the Pintail
could be ''exposed to the use of weapons against you from navy vessels
or airplanes of the Chilean navy.''
Greenpeace claimed the Pintail's response was: ''I hear your message
and with the nature of our cargo I would not think that is a very
sensible thing to do, to use arms.''
The Chileans also, claimed Greenpeace, threatened to interfere with
the British ship's navigation and to throw ropes into the water to stop
it.
But as Chile's navy chief said the ship had taken ''the worst route
possible'' and environmentalists claimed that international protest had
succeeded in driving the Pintail away from what would have been its
shortest route through the Panama Canal, the supremacy of international
law was being called into question.
Few would argue that political clout, rather than observance of
international agreement, has won the day on this occasion.
Alan Boyle, professor of public international law at Edinburgh
University, said that Section 19 of the UN Convention on the Law of the
Sea III (Unclos), makes clear the principle that foreign merchant ships
conducting peaceful, lawful trade have the right of free or ''innocent''
passage through a state's territorial waters, so long as the ship's
actvities are not prejudicial to the peace or good order of the coastal
state.
The Pintail, therefore, has every right to be in a state's territorial
waters, even under the 1989 Basle Convention on the Control of
Transboundary Movements of Hazardous Waste. On signing that agreement,
the UK Government declared that '' . . . the provisions of the
convention do not affect in any way the exercise of navigational rights
and freedoms as provided for in international law.
''The ship, therefore, has every right to be there. It may pose a risk
to the coastal state, but then lots of ships do. Oil or chemical tankers
are much more obviously a risk. International law can regulate, but not
prohibit passage,'' said Professor Boyle.
The Chilean Government could doubtless be taken to the International
Court of Justice for its actions against the Pintail -- but at present,
that would serve little purpose.
Greenpeace can protest as much as it wants that the Pintail will
probably be passing through the nuclear-free zone of Antarctica in the
next few days. But as long as it does not release radioactive material
in that area, no international sanctions can be applied. The battle of
the environmental campaigners and the politicians versus the
industrialists of the world's nuclear power has a long way to go yet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
