<HEADLINE>Cunningham looks for a local victory</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN HUNTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255593</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
VOTERS in Perthshire and Kinross have an ideal chance to drive a nail
in the coffin of the Tories at the April 6 elections for the new unitary
councils, according to prospective SNP Parliamentary candidate Ms
Roseanna Cunningham.
She was speaking in Perth yesterday at a launch of the party's local
government manifesto.
Along with other SNP speakers, Ms Cunningham claimed that their party
-- which is contesting every seat in the area -- was the only one
capable of taking control away from the Tories.
SNP Group leader, Councillor Bruce Crawford said that since 1992, the
area had slipped back as a result of Tory indifference, and in order to
take advantage of the opportunities available under the new single-tier
authorities, a fresh start had to be ensured.
Ms Cunningham, who will be fighting to wrest the Tory-held seat from
the Tories in a by-election caused by the death of Sir Nicholas
Fairbairn, said that she would be fully supporting local candidates.
Ms Cunningham said: ''People have the chance to get shot of the Tories
at the elections, which will put another nail in their coffin.''
</TEXT>
