<DOCNO>GH950323-000166</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000166</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A dam hard life on the hydro-electric</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LORN MACINTYRE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>979255595</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Building Scotland's hydro schemes was a memorable feat for the
thousands of Gaelic-speakers involved, as Lorn Macintyre reports
BELOW the dam at Kinlochleven -- nearly half-a-mile long and holding
back 24 million gallons of water -- is a small cemetery, the graves of
navvies killed in the construction and who died in bogs crossing the
moor to Kingshouse in search of drink. But where is the resting place of
the Irish gambler allegedly murdered at the Loch Awe scheme 30 years ago
for being too lucky?
The Kinlochleven cemetery and the riddle of the gambler are two of the
compelling stories in a programme on BBC2 tonight at 7pm, the first in a
series called Obair Latha (A Day's Work) in which Gaelic speakers relate
their work experiences.
Early this century British Aluminium built a power station at
Kinlochleven, with water for it harnessed nearly five miles away in the
mountains in a dam that took 2000 navvies four years to build, by pick,
shovel and crowbar. Patrick MacGill recorded the squalid conditions in
his classic Children of the Dead End.
''The room, 40ft square and 10 foot high, contained 50 bed-places,
which rose one over the other in three tiers . . . A spring oozed
through the earthen floor.''
The strong, light metal, excellent for armaments, rescued British
Aluminium's fortunes in the First World War. To meet post-war demand the
company built another factory, on a site near Fort William, taking their
water supply for power from Loch Treig by 15 miles of tunnel through the
mountains.
John MacDonald, whose father had worked on the Kinlochleven scheme,
went to work at Lochaber in 1928 in the tunnel at #1 a shift, big money
at that time.
MacDonald recalls: ''I was on the concrete mixer all the time. The
tunnel is 15ft high and 15 broad in the shape of a horse-shoe. It was
lit on both sides as far as you could see like a Glasgow street.''
The hydro-electric schemes offered work to thousands of Scots and also
attracted thousands of navvies from Ireland. In the specially created
camps of more than 1000 men they mixed more than their Gaelic over drink
and dice. Norman MacLeod remembers Glen Quoich camp in the 1950s: ''In
one year here I was in greater mortal danger . . . than I was in all my
other years with the police.''
With work scarce in Ireland, navvies crossed to Scotland in their
hundreds to get a start on the schemes, and Ukrainian, Czech and Polish
displaced persons came from Europe.
Many of the dams were built in some of the wildest and most remote
areas of Scotland. In the three years it took to build the dam at Loch
Sloy (by Loch Lomond), there were only three dry weeks, and with the mud
they sometimes had to use horses instead of lorries. Murdo Macleod
remembers a bad winter at Glascarnoch, between Ullapool and Garve. ''We
were off for nearly three months because of snow. You couldn't get near
it. You couldn't tell where the dam site was.''
The tunnellers had the most dangerous and exhausting jobs, crouching
in dust-filled, confined spaces with their deafening drills. There are
more than 180 miles of tunnels and aqueducts in the Scottish dams, and
two tunnels meeting was cause for celebration.
Iain MacMaster from Acharacle has fond memories. ''The tool maker and
your employer used to send in drinks; whisky, gin, rum, with cigars and
cigarettes. Then the party started.''
The camps of men far from home, and with big money in their pay
packets after the long shifts attracted the professional gamblers with
their rolled-up Crown &amp; Anchor boards. The Cruachan scheme at Loch Awe
was huge. Seonaidh and Angus Alick MacInnes from North Uist claim:
''There was this Irishman there, a gambler who did nothing else but play
Crown &amp; Anchor. He didn't work and had a briefcase full of money. He
went round all the hydro camps, and then he carried on to Loch Awe, to
the three camps there, gambling all the time. He made a fortune.
''Gentleman Jim, they called him.'' The gambler, or so the story goes,
came to grief on a Saturday night out -- dragged along underneath a bus,
all the way to Oban.
Norman MacLeod sums up the impact of the schemes bitterly, ''Whatever
the Highlands got out of it, it was dearly bought. We were promised free
electricity before the end of the century, but we're still waiting for
it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
