<DOCNO>GH950323-000169</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000169</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bright sparksjoin forcesfor cheaperstreet lamps</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN MCCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS,FINAL ANALYSIS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255598</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ian McConnell casts lights on two Scots companies at the heart of a
muli-national project to light up European nights
TWO Scottish companies are using the research facilities of
universities at home and in Spain to pursue a bright idea on street
lighting with firms across Europe.
The #700,000 research project, which is 50% funded by the European
Union, will last two years, after which the seven companies involved
should have commercially exploitable products.
All of the firms have expertise in complementary fields, their joint
efforts coming together to produce an integrated control system to
improve the quality and efficiency of street lighting.
It is hoped the end-product could eventually become a world standard,
with Brussels having been particularly impressed by the
environmentally-friendly idea of energy savings through increased
efficiency.
The project aims to cut the 9p-a-night cost of lighting street lamps,
through energy savings, and reduce massive maintenance costs through the
eventual development of a research-based system which can predict
faults. It also aims to improve the quality of lighting, thereby helping
reduce crime.
Kilmarnock-based U-Aerials and Communications will work on the
telecommunications systems to ensure, for example, that a control centre
is alerted to faults at remote locations.
Dunsmore Data, of Edinburgh, will produce the system management
software which will translate the inspired insights of the boffins into
a user-friendly system.
Glasgow Caledonian University will help out with telecommunications,
integrated circuit design and software development, in what is by far
the biggest project in its recently established Intelligent Technologies
Research Centre.
Its Spanish counterpart, the University of Oviedo, has expertise in
the fields of lighting systems and power engineering. Kelman, based in
Lisburn, Northern Ireland, two Spanish, a German, and a Portuguese
company are also involved.
Funding for the ISCELIS, or Intelligent Supply and Control of External
Lighting Systems, project comes from Brite-EuRam, a European Union
science fund which buys research and development facilities for small
and medium-sized enterprises who could otherwise not afford them. The
companies themselves contribute the other half of the costs.
Project leader Barry Beggs, a lecturer in Glasgow Caledonian
University's department of engineering, said: ''I think what is unique
is the fact that we have a group of SMEs involved in a major European
project that has potentially got global implications.''
He added: ''The cost savings per lamp are a bit dubious but, when you
put that into a European context, 5% of 9p for every lamp in Europe is a
lot of money.''
The partners believe the system developed could also be applied to
signpost lighting, bollards and traffic lights.
When the project is finished, the companies could market their
innovative system by forming a European Economic Interest Group, which
makes it easier for small and medium-sized companies to overcome the
legal and fiscal difficulties of cross-border trade.
Alternatively, if they can each identify their contributions to the
system, they may market these products and services individually.
U-Aerials and Communications, which employs 45 people and hopes to
double its turnover to more than #2m in the year to end-August, is
already exploring the prospect of doing other business with one of the
Spanish companies.
Managing director Bill Strachan, who views the large-scale lighting
project as a great opportunity, said: ''It could give us a foothold in
Europe. As a small company, we see a lot of potential.''
In spite of the hi-tech nature of the firms involved, communication
difficulties have still been encountered in the pan-European project,
with nobody in the Portuguese company speaking English.
However, Spanish is the first language of Hernando Fernandez-Canque, a
member of the Glasgow Caledonian University research team, and he has
ensured ideas are communicated effectively.
</TEXT>
