<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000170</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000170</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wrong bet rakes in #33,000</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255599</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO bar workers placed a wrong bet yesterday, and won nearly #33,000
instead of #12,000.
Ms Maggie Biggins and Mr Iain McCalman hit their unwitting lucky
streak at a betting shop in Thornliebank, Glasgow.
Bookies William Hill said they thought they were placing a #1 bet on
the Tote Jackpot.
Instead, they put their money on the William Hill Jackpot Six, a
similar concept which required them to pick six winners at yesterday's
racing in Exeter.
Both work at the Rowallan Bar in Thornliebank and, for Ms Biggins, it
was only the second week that she had been betting on the horses.
She said last night: ''I was just dumbfounded. I still can't believe
it, and Iain's over the moon.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000171</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000171</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fisheries campaign intensifies</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255600</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FISHERMEN are stepping up their campaign to force the Government to
withdraw from the Common Fisheries Policy and to claim back Britain's
200-mile exclusive fishing zone.
They are staging a rally in London's Central Hall at the end of next
month and hundreds of vessels around the UK coast are expected to tie up
for that day to allow an anticipated 3000 to 4000 fishermen to attend.
Mr Roddy McColl, strategy group secretary of the Save Britain's Fish
Campaign, which is hoping to force British withdrawal from the CFP
within two years, said: ''The campaign recognises that the debate on
Europe is going to intensify and the fishing industry will feature
prominently in the parliamentary discussions because Parliament gave
away the water and the fish stocks and it is our belief and firm
conviction they can claim that back.
''We can accomplish this aim without leaving the European Union and we
are not anti-European, we are not militant, and we propose no violent
means of protest.
''However, we must persuade our politicians to act and save yet
another great British industry from being destroyed.''
The chairman of the Scottish White Fish Producers' Association, Mr Tom
Hay, said Britain's fishermen had been persecuted and humiliated. He
said they had no doubt that they could take back into British control
fishing grounds and fishing rights which were improperly given away.
Mrs Elizabeth Stevenson, an owner from Newlyn in Cornwall, said: ''We
have done nothing but give, give, give in terms of quotas, waters -- in
terms of everything.
''The Spanish accession agreement reached in Brussels just before
Christmas was the final straw. We have decided we cannot take it any
more.
''It would mean the end of our fishing industry and so we are backing
this campaign to force Parliament to regain control of our exclusive
fishing zone so it can be policed and monitored and maintained in line
with stocks for the benefit of the UK fishing industry.''
Mrs Stevenson, whose family owns 26 vessels, continued: ''It is not
just fishermen's jobs which are at stake. For every one man at sea there
are four or five on the shore relying on him.''
The Government has criticised the campaign for using fallacious
arguments and misrepresenting the facts.
Scottish Secretary Ian Lang has said that the campaign is based
entirely on an appeal to the emotions of fishermen and fails to
recognise the economic, legal, and political constraints which make the
objective of withdrawing from the CFP completely unrealistic and
damaging to the fishing industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000172</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000172</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gossip mill on Eigg jams as laird speaks</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS, HIGHLAND CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255601</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE 72 people who live on Eigg last night still had no idea whether
the ownership of the island was about to pass from Keith Schellenberg.
Rumours persist that the island has been sold or is about to be sold
to German artist Marlin Eckhard, who calls himself Maruma.
Indeed Maruma, 41, is reported to have already declared himself as the
new owner of Eigg, having paid #1.5m for the 7000-acre island.
Mr Schellenberg, however, said these reports were wrong. ''I am still
the owner of Eigg. That is the state of affairs. I can assure you that
if ever I sell it, I will announce it publicly. Mind you, anyone looking
at the papers would think twice about buying the island, given the
roasting I am always getting.''
Last night, Mrs Karen Helliwell, secretary of the Eigg Residents'
Association, said: ''Confusion and uncertainty reign here. None of us
knows what is going on. We just get our wonderful information from the
papers and then somebody says something different.
''The German artist says he visited last year but he didn't identify
himself, although some think they might remember him.
''Schelly (Keith Schellenberg) arrived today but nothing has happened.
There are no meetings or anything like that, although he is supposed to
have told the four people that work for the estate that they have
nothing to worry about.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000173</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000173</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wish list is a moving problem</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS,FINGER PULSE</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255602</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS month, Finger On The Pulse waves its magic wand over the tricky
topic of transport. It's set to be the major subject of debate at
Scotland's first-ever national transport conference next week, ''Getting
Scotland Moving,'' organised by the Scottish Chambers of Commerce.
All the main movers and shakers in Scottish transport will be there,
and Sir Alastair Morton, co-chairman of Eurotunnel, will make the
keynote speech. It also seems that transport will be one of the major
topics for political debate this spring.
With this in mind we decided to compile our own transport ''wish
list'' with the help of members of the Glasgow Chamber of Commerce --
with over 2000 members it's the authentic voice of West of Scotland
business today.
We asked them to tell us what improvements they want to see across the
entire spectrum of Scottish transport. The list is interesting,
sometimes amusing and surprising, and occasionally alarming.
Members all had their transport ''horror'' stories -- be it a
half-hour delay on 18.02 to Falkirk Grahamston, gridlock on the M8,
congestion in the Clyde Tunnel or shuttle shockers. The situations are
certainly frustrating but what are the solutions?
According to Scottish Chambers there is only one solution -- to go to
the top and actually drive government policy. The Chamber wishes to see
an integrated and cohesive transport policy for Scotland. At the moment
this doesn't exist. Chief executive of Glasgow Chamber of Commerce,
Geoff Runcie, believes that this is seriously damaging Scotland's
recovery from recession, and is at the root of the majority of transport
problems in Scotland:
''If Scotland is to trade competitively in the UK and world markets,
our position on the periphery must be supported by the optimum
infrastucture. At the moment, this doesn't exist and until it does, we
will be operating at a competitive disadvantage,'' he warns.
He also criticises the lack of funding for transport. Indeed a recent
study reveals that although the UK's roads and airports are amongst the
busiest in Europe, Britain invests far less in transport than her
European neighbours. For example, investment in rail in the UK is only
20-30 per cent of the levels per head of the Netherlands, France and
Germany.
Similarly, the UK invests only about 80% per head of that invested by
France and Germany in roads. Yet it would seem that our network is badly
in need of attention. According to Scottish Chambers, the main cause of
road congestion in Scotland is the growth of car traffic, with cars
accounting for 80% of all traffic on motorways, trunk and principal
roads. It predicts that this could double by the end of the century.
Curtailing personal mobility is a thorn yet to be grasped by Government,
but it surely must sometime soon.
A ''wish list'' of solutions to these problems might be endless.
However, we decided to offer Chamber members only one wish. If they
could chose to solve at a stroke a transport problem specifically
detrimental or frustrating to them, what would it be and why? First stop
was Jim Hunter, Managing Director, Caledonian Freight Forwarders, who is
looking for ''integration''.
''Kicking the Government when it's down has never given me any
satisfaction but this Government and most in living memory have never
been on top in transport terms in Scotland. There continues to be a
complete lack of an integrated transport policy and little sign of one
for the future. My wish would be to see this in place immediately.
''Certainly there are many initiatives underway such as Mossend and
the Channel Tunnel, Glasgow Airport expansion, A74 upgrading and another
Forth Road Bridge, but where's the balance? Where's the confidence
giving bigger picture? Not even Paul Daniels can make it appear because
it just doesn't exist.''
Meanwhile, Douglas Fairbairn, Managing Partner at Ernst and Young,
Glasgow, was particularly concerned about his lungs!
''There has been a great deal in the Press of late about the harmful
effects of vehicle emissions. Recent reports seem to be linking exhaust
pollution with the rapid increase in asthma attacks.
''In fact, a recent government air quality study, which measure the
levels of nitrogen dioxide, found breaches of European guidelines in
Glasgow, Dundee, Motherwell, Edinburgh and Aberdeen. Friends of the
Earth described Hope Street as one of Britain's most polluted streets.
''My wish would therefore be to find a way to cut down on the number
of cars for short-term journeys. We could look at adopting some American
ideas, for example, incentives for those people who share car journeys
during peak times.''
Public transport was high on the wish list of Tom Waddell, Manager of
The Recruitment Company the specialist driving employment agency:
''I would wish for a more efficient public transport network into the
city centre which would allow motorists to leave cars outside an already
heavily congested area. This would free-up the traffic clogged streets.
''This in turn would allow deliveries to be made quicker and alleviate
the need for hard-pressed distribution drivers to double park or leave
vehicles in dangerous places.''
Agnes Samuel, Executive Director, Glasgow Opportunities, was also
concerned about public transport.
''My wish would be for someone to tell me where to get on and where to
get off -- the buses that it! If we are to be encouraged to leave our
cars and use public transport, let's have some readily available
information. Nothing classified. Just route maps on bus stops and inside
buses, marked off in fare stages to that you know what the exact fare is
without asking the driver. Other European cities do it. Let's make it
easier for tourists and citizens alike.''
Finally, we asked Geoff Runcie, Chief Executive of the Glasgow Chamber
of Commerce and the driving force behind ''Getting Scotland Moving,'' to
give us his views.
''It does not take a rocket scientist to recognise that integration,
not only of infrastructure, but of public and private sector transport
systems is absolutely the key and the only way to address the congestion
and deficiencies of our existing system. We need to move more people on
to effective, attractive public transport, allowing freight to make more
balanced use of the road, rail, sea and air.''
''Private transport could then be used for the out of the ordinary
journey, the recreational journey where an element of freedom is
absolutely crucial. However, I contend that without infrastructure in
place this view is a romantic notion for the UK and for Scotland in
particular. We need to plan, implement and then support the balanced use
of personal and public sector transport.
''It is time for the people of the community, the people in industry,
to state clearly that enough is enough, and that some serious planning
is necessary for us to enjoy improved transport efficiency and,
therefore, quality of life.''
Getting Scotland Moving takes place at Glasgow's SECC on Thursday
March 30. Information and last-minute bookings from The Conference
Manager, Getting Scotland Moving, Alan Clark Associates, 4 Woodside
Place, Glasgow G3 70F: telephone 041 353 5040 or fax 041-332-2363.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
