<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000175</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000175</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>All mod cons plus marsh and castle</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255604</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A FIVE-PAGE document that looks like the brochure for a house sale
explains what the Royal Naval base at Rosyth has to offer prospective
buyers.
It includes a map of the site, the closing date for bids, and gives a
detailed guide of the buildings on it.
The document, prepared by property consultants Ryden, gives details of
the sale of the base which has been on the shores of the Firth of Forth
since 1903.
The main naval base extends to 148.7 acres. Included in the sale is
Woodend House, a mansion which is currently the base commander's house.
The oil fuel depot on site is said to be suitable for continued
commercial use.
HMS Cochrane is the main shore-based naval facility and provides an
office, ward room, residential accommodation, and medical facilities.
There is nearly one million square feet of accommodation on site.
There is also a 76-acre marsh.
Included in the sale is a deep-water berth 190ft long and 27ft deep.
There are three other basins with jetties.
Access to the site at present is through the dockyard security gates
but the intention is to grant a more direct access through the existing
visitors' centre car park. A railway line goes through the site.
Included in the base is an enclave extending to 30 acres which is to
be retained as a Royal Navy stores depot.
Also on the base is Rosyth Castle and a dovecot which would be the
subject of an access and maintenance agreement with Historic Scotland.
According to the document, the base ''provides an excellent commercial
opportunity to develop an industrial/office estate for port-related
activities which could also benefit from the railway links''.
It adds: ''Many of the buildings and facilities have recently been
refurbished but there is potential to carry out further improvements and
to develop a master plan for the re-use and redevelopment of the area.''
The front of the document states that HM Naval Base Rosyth is being
sold by order of the Secretary of State for Defence on the instructions
of the Defence Lands Service (Scotland).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000176</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000176</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Council rallies to support of social workers in abuse case</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN MACCALMAN, MUNICIPAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255605</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
STRATHCLYDE councillors rallied to the support of their beleaguered
social workers yesterday following a sheriff's criticism of their
handling of the Ayr child sex abuse case.
Based on the findings of two external assessors, councillors accepted
that the social work staff who gave evidence in the four-year-old case
acted ''honestly and in good faith''.
However, the assessors, Ms Alyson Leslie, a social work consultant,
and Mr Brendan Kearney, legal services manager of Dumfries and Galloway
Regional Council, concluded that in some instances the staff appeared to
have acted with ''an inordinate degree of naivety and credulousness'' in
their practice and in their reception of allegations from the children.
And the department itself accepted that some of the practice of social
workers in 1990 was ''flawed'' judged by present standards. A review is
being taken to improve procedures for investigative interviewing and
recording.
However, social work committee chairman, the Rev David Laing, reminded
his colleagues: ''Our social workers are trained as carers, they are not
trained as detectives. The people are expecting our social workers to go
and operate as if they were detective inspectors of police in the CID.
''Even with the best in-service training in the world we'll never
reach that kind of standard. That's why I'm concerned about the weight
Sheriff Colin Miller gave to the investigation techniques.''
He called on the Government to introduce national standards for
investigating such cases and said that in the United States social
workers and court officials received special training in dealing with
child abuse cases.
In her report to the committee yesterday, social work director Ms Mary
Hartnoll stated: ''The department accepts that a number of interviewing
practices adopted between June and August 1990 were flawed. In
particular, leading questions were asked.''
The department also accepted criticism of staff for inappropriate use
of equipment, such an anatomically correct dolls. However, this practice
related to a period of time when the department's staff had little
experience of the techniques that are now accepted to require additional
training.
Ms Hartnoll rejected Sheriff Miller's criticism that the staff had
closed their minds to the possibility that abuse had NOT occurred and
that they had pre-conceived views they were dealing with cases of
satanic abuse.
Senior Conservative member, Councillor Fergus Clarkson, was concerned
about the independent assessors' reference to case notes having been
amended, although the assessors had accepted that there was no evidence
of collusion and no apparent intention to deceive or mislead.
Mr Michael Johnston, solicitor for one of the families involved, later
condemned the social work department's response as a ''smokescreen'' and
a ''charade''.
He declared: ''This is a shameful attempt to cover up the inadequacies
of the social workers and the management procedures involved in this
case.
He said a great number of the social work management would sleep more
easily having heard Ms Hartnoll come to their rescue with this
smokescreen of a supposedly independent consultants' report.
''I would challenge Ms Hartnoll to clarify how the authors of the
report were selected and what was their remit.
''I believe they were asked to look at only 40 pages of Sheriff
Miller's 400-page judgment and interviewed only six of the social
workers who were involved.''
Mr Paul Burns, solicitor for another of the families, regretted that
the social work department had ''delivered a whitewash instead of an
apology''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000177</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000177</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Paddle-power set to take Scots venture abroad</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN EASTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255606</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LANGBANK businessman has come up with his own vision of the future
by registering a new company in Glasgow with the aim of designing and
operating a fleet of traditionally powered paddle steamers in tourist
areas throughout the world.
Mr Alistair Macleod, a self-confessed steamer buff, is now seeking
venture capital and institutional funding to allow the building of the
first paddler to proceed. This could cost around #9m and he says it is
hoped the first ship will be constructed at Fergusons Shipbuilders, Port
Glasgow.
He has even chosen a name -- the New Caledonia, re-kindling memories
of one of the smartest Clyde paddlers of all time, the 1934-Denny built
Caledonia which survived in service until 1969 and then as a static
restaurant on the Thames until 1980 when she was destroyed by fire.
His new company is called The Paddle Steamer Cruise Line and he says
negotiations are already taking place to operate new Clyde-built paddle
steamers in the Far East after he met contacts on a Strathclyde Business
Development mission to Hong Kong and China last year.
Mr Macleod declared yesterday: ''With considerable growth taking place
in the world cruise lesiure market this enterprise is well positioned to
create its own niche market.''
Though not much larger than the present Waverley, Mr Macleod's New
Caledonia and others that might follow would clearly have horizons
stretching much further than your average ''Doon the Watter'' day trip.
He says: ''From spring to autumn The New Caledonia would operate
cruises from the Clyde to the west coast of Scotland, southern Ireland
and the north of France. During the winter the ship would be based in
the Mediterranean and would operate in areas where conventional cruise
ships cannot navigate.''
The paddlers would have luxury two-berth cabins with en-suite
facilities and would accommodate up to 126 people including 10 deluxe
cabins with private verandas on the upper deck. A casino, cocktail bar,
dance floor and fitness centre would add that touch of elegance.
Mr Macleod says the New Caledonia, 90 metres in length and 20 metres
in overall beam, would be built to Class 2 international standard, be
fully stabilised with bow and stern thrusters and capable of operating
in open seas.
However, at least one important tradition would remain -- the engines
would be based on the triple expansion steam machinery used on the
Waverley. This was latterly the province of the Rankin and Blackmore
Eagle Foundry at Greenock, long-since demised.
''The traditional skills and technical expertise required to construct
the steam engines are being resourced in the West of Scotland area and
Captain David Neill, of the Waverley, has provided assistance to the
project,'' said Mr Macleod.
''The venture is also benefiting from the involvement of senior
figures in the shipping and hotel management industry, amongst whom are
Sir Ross Belch and James Smith, vice-president of Hilton Hotels in
Central Asia and general manager of the Hong Kong Hilton.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000178</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000178</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Firth in line to benefit from new cruise traffic</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANGUS MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>FEATURE</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255607</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE world cruise liner market is set for a huge growth up to the end
of the century, and presents a great opportunity to boost tourism in the
North of Scotland, according to a delegation just returned from the
annual Seatrade Cruise Shipping Conference and Exhibition in Florida.
One of the ports most likely to benefit from the growth is the
Cromarty Firth, where passenger liner traffic has been increasing
throughout the 1990s as a result of determined marketing of the port and
the shore-side attractions. In Miami and other tourism fairs, and
visitor numbers this year are expected to set new records.
So far 17 cruise liners have confirmed a visit to Invergordon in the
Cromarty Firth as part of their itinerary this year, with the highlight
being the Clyde-built Cunard Liner QE2, which arrives on September 4th,
the largest liner to call at the port so far. But according to Gordon
Ireland, Ross and Cromarty District Council's Tourism Development
Officer, even the QE2 will be dwarfed by liners to be built over the
next few years.
''A new generation of liners is being built, and there are $8.5
billion (dollars) worth of ships on the order books, for 1995 to 1998.
Royal Caribbean Cruise Lines is building two liners of 70,000 tonnes
each in France. One of these, the Splendour of the Seas, which will be
launched in 1996, will come to Invergordon in August 1996, its inaugural
year.''
Last year, eighteen liners, carrying 6761 passengers called at
Invergordon, with an estimated boost of quarter of a million pounds to
the local economy. But the Cromarty Firth will see an average increase
in liner size this year, and passenger numbers are expected to rise by
33%. Holland America Line's ''Statendam'' at 55,451 tons, which called
in at the port last year, was the largest passenger liner ever to call
at the port. That honour will pass to the QE2, at 69,000 tonnes in
September.
''We're having to make a lot of arrangements for parking, closing
roads and street entertainment,'' said Gordon Ireland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000179</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000179</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mr Happy fails to cheer architects</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255608</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LEADING architects and businessmen yesterday attacked the use of the
Mr Happy logo on Glasgow City Chambers.
They believe that the sight of the cartoon character on the
prestigious nineteenth-century building overlooking one of Europe's
greatest squares is tasteless and cheapens the city's image.
Mr Happy, used to promote the slogan Glasgow's Miles Better since the
early 1980s, is not sophisticated enough for the city which recently
beat off tough competition to become UK City of Architecture and Design
1999, they say.
Mr Gavin Stamp, one of Britain's leading architectural historians and
writers, said the spectacle of Mr Happy beaming down from the City
Chambers detracted from the building's standing.
The Chambers, he said, was an example of Glasgow's ability to erect
buildings of ''great intellectual distinction and dignity''.
''The Chambers is a wonderful monument of Glasgow's optimistic and
opulent years and people who visit the city are always terribly against
the 'Mr Happy' banner. It certainly takes away from the building's
prestige,'' he said.
Mr Happy represented the city from 1983 to 1989, only to be replaced
by the disappointing Glasgow's Alive slogan.
Last year, Glasgow council chiefs ordered Mr Happy to be dusted off to
highlight Glasgow's friendly image.
It was revealed yesterday that, by the end of the month, the
character's smile will be miles bigger with a 60ft by 40ft picture of
him on the Possilpark gasometer.
The Royal Incorporation of Architects in Scotland admitted the
majority of its members in Glasgow and throughout Scotland were
disappointed the slogan was not more in keeping with the city's recent
accolade.
However, a council spokeswoman dashed any hopes of the character's
disappearance.
She said: ''Have these people no sense of humour? Mr Happy is bright,
bold, down-to-earth, and encapsulates the fun side of the city. He
cheers people up.
''The Chambers is appropriate for the poster because of its
prominance.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000180</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000180</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Jammed bridge finally opens</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN EASTON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255609</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BELL'S Bridge over the Clyde in Glasgow swung open for the first time
in three months yesterday. The bridge had been jammed since flooding
from the River Kelvin damaged the retaining river wall in December.
Repair work, which initially had been the subject of argument between
the Glasgow Development Agency, which owns the bridge, and the
management of the Scottish Exhibition and Conference Centre, which has
responsibility for the quay wall, has taken only nine days.
The way is now clear for the world's last sea-going paddle steamer
Waverley, which has been trapped at her berth at Anderston Quay upriver
of the bridge, to sail down to Garvel dry dock at Greenock next week to
undergo essential re-fitting work in preparation for her coming season.
Mr Gordon Wilson, contracts manager for Lilley Construction who
carried out the work at an estimated cost of #20,000, said: ''The work
was very carefully thought out well before we moved on to site. As a
result, our team came up against no real problems when they came to
tackle the job.''
The general manager of Waverley Excursions, Mr David Duncanson, said
last night: ''We are delighted. The Waverley is expected to leave her
berth on Tuesday and we should have no difficulty meeting our schedule
of work at the dry dock in Greenock to allow us to make our first public
trips of the season on the Clyde over Easter weekend.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
