<DOCNO>GH950323-000181</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000181</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Commitment but no cash for rail plan</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS, INDUSTRIAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255610</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government and Railtrack yesterday reaffirmed their ''absolute
commitment'' to the modernisation of the West Coast Main Line which they
hope will result in high-speed tilting trains moving between London and
Glasgow in a little over four hours.
However, they are still reluctant to put any money up front and expect
industry to fund the project which, it is now revealed, could cost up to
#2000m excluding the cost of new rolling stock.
Railtrack yesterday invited ''expressions of interest'' from companies
wishing to tender for the #30m to #50m contract to develop the
revolutionary transmission-based cab train control system which would
replace existing track-side signals.
This week it will apply for European Union funding for up to 50% of
the development cost, and project director Nick Higson said he thought
there was a very strong chance of the project attracting EU funds.
The reward for the successful company or companies would be the
opportunity to have a major role in providing the system which forms the
base of the #1000m ''core investment programme''. They would have the
opportunity to sell their product on to WCML and then on to the
world-wide market.
A lot of interest already had been shown and it was hoped that the
industry would fund all or part of the development itself as the
potential rewards later were so great. Contracts should be awarded at
the ''back end of the year''.
Railtrack chief executive John Edmonds said he was confident the new
concept would work and that it would lead to tremendous financial and
operational benefits including greatly improved safety as the new system
includes the automatic train protection system which has been declared
too costly to ''bolt on '' to existing track and rolling stock.
Mr Higson stressed that in addition to safety improvements the key
benefits would be improved comfort and reduced journey times.
The problem of the British rail system having a different gauge to the
rest of Europe also would be solved within the modernisation of WCML
which would then be opened up to some of the larger continental freight
wagons currently unable to use much of the UK network.
The opportunities for trans-European rail traffic would be greatly
increased, declared Mr Higson, adding that this should improve the
chances of EU funding.
The state of the art signal system reduces cost and replaces 56 signal
boxes and puts four electrical control rooms into one location. It also
will make the rest of the modernisation far easier.
It can be developed off line and be constructed in tandem with the
existing system with the final changeover made only once the new system
has been tried and tested.
Radio-based, it allows speed and distance to be monitored and opens
the way for faster running, up to 155 mph, and a higher frequency of
services.
According to Mr Higson, the eight-year modernisation programme would
put the WCML into a very good state of repair, make it a major player
within the European rail network, and drive technological benefits that
should give British industry a major foothold in rail developments world
wide.
Railways Minister John Watts commented: ''The West Coast Main Line is
one of Railtrack's most important assets, and is critically important to
both passenger and freight services. The modernisation of the line will
be one of the largest railway investment projects in decades.''
* Scottish business organisations agreed yesterday to unite in a
campaign to protect Scotland's railways in the light of the threat to
sleepers to Fort William and Motorail.
All the main organisations participated in the meeting held in Glasgow
and Scottish Enterprise, Highland and Islands Enterprise, the STUC, and
Cosla sent observers.
A business liaison group was set up and is seeking urgent talks with
the Scottish Secretary and his Minister for Roads and Transport at which
to air business's ''grave concerns about the future of the Scottish rail
network''.
</TEXT>
