<DOCNO>GH950323-000182</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000182</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>143mph speeder says he is surprised he was not jailed</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255611</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SELF-CONFESSED speed fanatic last night voiced surprise at the
leniency of a sheriff's sentence after he admitted driving at 143mph --
more than double the speed limit -- on a stretch of road in the Borders.
Sales representative Charles Young, who was fined #250 and banned for
one year, said he had expected to be jailed.
The 27-year-old, who had appeared at Peebles Sheriff Court, was
driving his firm's #50,000 car when police clocked him using the Vascar
radar system.
It is thought to be one of the fastest speeds ever recorded on
Scotland's roads.
Young was caught driving a red Mercedes sports car at 143mph on the
60mph A703 Penicuik to Peebles road last September.
Traffic policemen had been unable to pull him over until he slowed
down to just 60mph.
Young, of Peebles Road, Penicuik, Midlothian, yesterday admitted
driving dangerously.
His defence agent, Mr Andy Crawley, claimed it was a fit of madness.
Sheriff Nigel Thomson, who also ordered Young to resit his test, told
him it was the highest speed he had ever dealt with and had been a
''quite appalling'' act of driving on ''a notoriously deceptive piece of
road''.
Young, who had no previous convictions, admitted later he had been
''unbelievably stupid'' to drive so fast.
He said he had been lent the car by his bosses to travel to England on
business and simply could not resist the temptation to test it out.
''Anyone who knows cars knows the Mercedes Benz sports car is one hell
of a powerful machine. My love of fast cars just got the better of me.''
Road safety campaigners yesterday reacted with fury to the #250 fine
and ban.
Mr Eddie McColm, whose father was killed in a road crash six years
ago, called for a minimum five-year driving ban for excessive speed
drivers.
Mr McColm, of Stevenston, Ayrshire, who is a member of the Scottish
Campaign against Irresponsible Drivers, said the Scottish courts were
not doing enough to deter drivers from speeding. And he accused the law
of being too ''driver friendly''.
Last night Young's boss at Mercedes dealers, Western Automobile
Company, Edinburgh, refused to comment.
</TEXT>
