<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chainsaws win the day with police on their side</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING, STEPHEN FRASER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255612</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SIXTEEN people were arrested yesterday in the most serious clashes so
far over opposition to the M77 motorway link in Glasgow on a day when
roadbuilders Wimpey claimed it ''successfully'' completed its
tree-felling programme.
One police officer and a protester were slightly injured and were
taken to hospital. Scottish Militant Labour convener Tommy Sheridan was
among those arrested.
The police officer sustained knee and back injuries after being
crushed against a fence. His condition is not thought to be serious. A
protester had a head injury after being hit by a falling branch during
tree felling.
The arrests of 14 men and two women for mainly ''disorder offences''
were made next to the so-called Pollok Free State camp, set up by
protesters. It is anticipated they will appear at Glasgow Sheriff Court
today.
Strathclyde Police had drafted in about 250 officers in an early
morning operation to ensure that road builders could continue to fell
trees. Wimpey, the contractor for the #56.3m link, also brought in about
200 security personnel to ''allow work to progress''.
Contractors moved in to ground next to the camp about 6am to fence an
area off and clear away about 40 trees. Police stood guard inside the
fences throughout the day. An outer cordon was provided by security
officers.
Ms Lesley Bolton, a veteran campaigner in protests at Greenham Common
and the M65, said about a dozen protesters secured themselves high in
trees by abseiling over the fencing via connecting ropes.
She claimed ''hordes'' of police had stormed an area next to the camp
in an attempt to ensure that the tree-felling operation proceeded
smoothly.
Throughout the afternoon, a number of protesters were persuaded down
from their positions until 6.30pm, when the police officers and security
guards were stood down.
At that point, one man, who would only give his name as Jack, remained
up a Scots pine several yards away from the main area of trees.
Despite several attempts by foresters to persuade him down, rebuffed
on one occasion when the man tipped a bucket containing what appeared to
be urine over a forester, it was decided to leave him in position whilst
the tree's lower limbs were stripped.
Mr Dan Pollard, roads director for Wimpey, said: ''After a further
survey of the line of a diversion road, we decided to leave that tree in
place. The limbs were stripped to ensure that drivers have a clear line
of sight round the curve.''
One campaigner, Ms Donna McAtamany, 29, from Pollok, claimed her
one-year-old daughter Deborah was probably saved from serious injury by
local man Glen Pollock, 30, who suffered a head injury after being hit
by a branch that fell during tree cutting. She said: ''The branch that
injured him just missed my baby's pram.''
Asked if she was being irresponsible in bringing her daughter to the
area during such operations, Ms McAtamany replied: ''It is my
one-year-old that is going to be living here and breathing in the
pollution that will result from this new motorway. She will have to live
with the environment that remains.''
Strathclyde Police later dismissed Ms McAtamany's claims, saying that
she ran towards the incident after the debris had fallen, placing her
child and herself in danger.
One protester taunted police and security staff by holding a
full-length mirror in front of them and urging them to ''see yourselves
for what you are'' while others danced nearby.
The protester also focused the mirror on police video cameras, which a
spokesman said were there to provide evidence in the event of complaints
against Strathclyde officers, whom he also applauded for their refusal
to react.
Wimpey's Mr Pollard claimed that work on the M77 extension was still
on schedule to be completed by the end of next year but conceded that
the protesters were costing the company money -- the complexity of the
operation had involved the company ''tying up a lot of senior staff''.
He said there were no plans to uproot the camp because it was not on
land designated for the extension.
</TEXT>
