<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hospital drops idea of burger outlet</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MACDERMID, MEDICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255613</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A HOSPITAL has dropped controversial plans to let the MacDonald's
burger chain open a branch in its grounds.
The board of Southern General Hospital Trust in Glasgow reached the
decision after consultation with staff, community representatives, local
MPs, and police.
The two parties had been unable to reach a business agreement. A
spokesman said last night there had been a number of factors, one of
them financial. He appreciated the professional way in which the chain
had negotiated.
The original proposal, to let MacDonald's open in the hospital's
retail shopping precinct in place of the existing Red Cross tearoom, led
to protests regarding the nutritional value of fast-food fare, and about
the security implications of having the restaurant open in the evening.
However, the board said they had set out to develop services in line
with responses from visitor and patient surveys which expressed a desire
for an extended range of catering facilities, with extended hours and
capable of handling promptly larger numbers of customers.
The hospital's own in-house catering unit will take over when the Red
Cross lease expires, pending further consideration by the trust of
future strategy for the retail food outlets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
