<HEADLINE>Hatton is cleared of stealing horsebox</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255614</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MR DEREK Hatton, the former deputy leader of Liverpool City Council,
was yesterday found not guilty of stealing a #45,000 horsebox.
Mr Hatton, 47, and his co-accused, Mr David Godsell, 39, who was also
cleared, were both discharged at Manchester Crown Court.
The jury cleared the pair after deliberating for more than five hours.
The foreman said they had reached verdicts on which at least 10 of
them were agreed following the direction earlier by Judge Rhys Davies,
QC.
Mr Hatton, of Wavertree Gardens Suburb, Liverpool, was found not
guilty of theft and attempting to obtain an insurance claim from the
Norwich Union.
Mr Godsell, of Crumpsall, Manchester, was found not guilty of theft
and aiding and abetting the insurance claim.
After the verdicts, Mr Hatton turned to the jury, smiled, and said
''thank you''.
During the eight-day trial, the prosecution said that after Mr Hatton
fell behind with payments for the horsebox, the finance company which
had provided it, Forward Trust, began steps to repossess the Ford
Iveco.It was alleged that the two men moved the vehicle to a secret
location so that agents working for the financiers could not find it.
Mr Hatton allegedly submitted a false claim for the horsebox after
reporting it stolen.
However, the court heard he had denied the allegations when
interviewed by police, claiming Mr Godsell hid the vehicle because he
was owed money by Mr Hatton for repairs carried out on it.
During the trial, counsel called no evidence on behalf of the two men.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
