<HEADLINE>Council set for court action to halt Highland cutbacks</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS, HIGHLAND CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255615</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HIGHLAND Regional Council is pursuing legal action to try to prevent
the withdrawal of Motorail and Fort William sleeper services before
there has been full public consultation.
ScotRail's incoming managing director John Ellis warned yesterday that
if the action was successful, and he was forced to run these services
without additional financial support, ''it would mean serious
difficulties for other Scottish services''.
Mr Ellis was in Inverness to address a meeting of the Institute of
Directors but his first call was at Highland Regional Council's
headquarters, where he met the convener, Mr Duncan McPherson, and
vice-convener Peter Peacock.
The councillors emerged from the meeting saying they could delay no
longer and would now pursue legal action.
Mr McPherson said: ''There were moves within Cosla to initiate legal
action but that would take time and we can't wait.
''We are the transport authority most affected and we are taking
counsel's opinion on the best way forward to ensure the continuance of
these services after May 27.''
They are seeking advice as to whether they should seek an interdict,
judicial review or try some other course.
Mr Peacock said they had impressed on Mr Ellis the difficulty that
people now had in dealing with the railway industry. ''When you ask a
question you are immediately told it is somebody else's
responsibility,'' he said.
Scottish Office Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton made it clear
yesterday that the Fort William sleeper service is unlikely to be saved.
The Government is still fighting a rearguard action but at Commons
Scottish Questions the best that could be done was to put a gloss on the
situation.
Lord James said the new Euro-sleeper service between Glasgow and
Paris, to be introduced next year, could be timetabled to connect with
daytime services to Fort William.
The Minister said: ''The franchising director has undertaken to look
at timetabling flexibility in daytime connections and that will be
important for day services to Fort William. These services will tie up
with other services, including the new sleeper service between Glasgow
and Paris to be introduced next year.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
