<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000189</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000189</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Business leader joins SNP with a call for followers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBBIE DINWOODIE, SCOTTISH POLITICAL CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255618</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LEADING member of the Scottish business community will today join
the SNP and urge others from industry and commerce to follow him in
backing the independence cause.
The former head of salmon farming giant Marine Harvest, Mr David
McCarthy, an Englishman, supported devolution but concluded it was an
unnecessary halfway house.
The party regards it as a major coup and a boost to its electoral
credibility across the country. SNP leader Alex Salmond said last night:
''The SNP have had some very well placed business supporters in the past
but none has been in a position to stick their heads above the parapet
and go public.
''None has felt able to nail their saltire to the mast, so David's
decision is very important. I hope it will be a rallying point for other
people in the business community who feel like him.''
Mr McCarthy, who describes himself as a former Labour voter, was born
57 years ago in Kent and educated at Winchester and Oxford. He has had a
high-flying career spanning more than 30 years with Unilever.
After heading its operations in Malaysia and Chile, he was posted to
Scotland as chairman and managing director of a subsidiary, Marine
Harvest, the world's largest salmon farming company.
He spent eight years in the job until a takeover last year.
Mr McCarthy retired in December and lives in Kinross, where he
recently decided to apply for membership of the SNP.
Asked what prompted him, he said: ''Partly it was the offence against
democratic principles of having Scotland run almost as a colony by the
Conservatives without democratic support.
''I was a 'soft' Labour voter and supporter of devolution but the more
I thought about it the more I thought it was an unnecessary halfway
house, a re-run of 1973 which had more to do with Westminster retaining
power than giving power back to the people of Scotland.''
Living in Scotland had made him conscious of its sense of nationhood
and that the energies and talents of the people were such that they
could go it alone in a much more mobile world in which people had
increasing cross-border links.
Another clinching factor for Mr McCarthy has been his experience
abroad and more recently in dealing with Ministers and officials at the
Scottish Office and in Brussels. The former admitted privately they were
hamstrung by London, the latter made clear that only sovereign nations
were listened to.
''I do think I am probably somewhat in the van here,'' he said.
''But I have noticed over the last few years that there has been a
change in attitude in the business community. Over the next couple of
years, I expect more and more people to think this way.''
Mr Salmond agrees and believes the ''Conservative hold on the business
community is loosening. David's stance will be an inspiration to others
to look more pro-actively at the issues and the possibilities.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
