<DOCNO>GH950323-000190</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000190</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>You can walk around with an aneurysm all your life and never know, Alan MacDermid is told. Weak spot that can fell the fittest.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MACDERMID</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255619</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE brain haemorrhage which left Davie Cooper fighting for his life
last night is likely to have been the result of an aneurysm -- a weak
spot in an artery which people can carry in their head for years like a
time-bomb.
A sudden bout of exertion, even jumping out of bed first thing in the
morning, can trigger a rupture which may leave the victim dead or
disabled.
Doctors are expected to decide today whether an operation is necessary
to stem or clear the flow of blood which burst into the inner lining of
Cooper's brain. They will be in no rush to do so unless the situation
demands it.
Last night, still unconscious, he had already undergone a series of
scans to determine the extent of the damage. Of vital importance will be
the pressure being put on his brain by the swelling in the bleed area,
and the danger of an early recurrence.
If he recovers he may still require extensive rehabilitation to
restore some of the functions -- movement, speech, or thought -- which
could be affected by his condition.
A subarachnoid haemorrhage is a bleed into the area between the middle
and inner of the three membranes, the meninges, which line the brain.
Whereas bleeds in the outer areas -- subdural or extra-dural -- are
usually the result of an injury, a subarachnoid bleed tends to occur
spontaneously.
Professor David Graham, a consultant neuropathologist at the Southern
General Hospital, said: ''An aneurysm forms at a point of weakness,
often where an artery in the brain forks in two.
''Over time they get bigger, and at 5mm-6mm, for haemodynamic reasons,
the risk is greatest. Physical exertion tends to raise blood pressure
and then it would burst.
''Exercise or atheroma can weaken the wall and predispose it to burst.
Sudden exertion, like leaping out of bed as soon as you waken, can be
enough to burst it.
''In many instances investigation and treatment gives some hope. The
prognosis is more favourable if the patient is conscious, and can move
his limbs, but he could require an operation.''
A massive bleed leading to prolonged unconsciousness is more
dangerous, and a third of people who suffer cerebral anuerysms die at
the scene or within a week of the initial bleed.
For those who survive, the prognosis is good. They may suffer
after-effects akin to those left by brain injury, but specialist help in
rehabilitation has become more widely available in recent years.
Ms Lynn McLeish, manager of the Scotcare Brain Injury Rehabilitation
Unit in Bonkle, Lanarkshire, said: ''The treatment we give is tailored
to each individual patient and their condition; there might be weakness
down one side, speech and memory impairment, loss of planning ability
and concentration, and physical or psychological problems.
''The treatment could include physiotherapy, speech or occupational
therapy, and psychological and psychiatric report; the aim is to get the
patient back to as independent a life as possible.
''Cerebral aneurysms are so unpredictable -- you can walk around with
one all your life and never know.''
More than 8000 Scots die every year from cerebrovascular disease, but
60% are ischaemic strokes in which a blood vessel is blocked by a clot
brought on by atherosclerosis or high blood pressure. Mortality rises
steeply from the mid-40s on, whereas haemorrhage extends more widely to
younger age groups.
A subarachnoid haemorrhage ended the playing career of Welsh rugby
star Mervyn Davies, then 29, when he collapsed during a scrum in 1976.
He recovered but not sufficiently to return to the game.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000191</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000191</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Diet message not getting through, report confirms</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES MCKILLOP</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255620</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN the health-conscious nineties Scottish parents are continuing to
ignore the advice of experts by passing on to their children all the bad
diet habits of the past, a new report published yesterday confirms.
Chips, junk food, and sweets are tops amongst the underfives in
Scotland. Their intake of vitamin C and carotene, from fruit and
vegetables, is less than anywhere else in the UK.
Tooth decay is a more serious problem for toddlers in Scotland than
anywhere else in Britain -- even though Scottish dentists are more
likely to recommend fluoride drops or tablets than their colleagues
elsewhere in the UK.
So what is new? Yet another survey has shown that Scottish dietary
habits are appalling compared with the rest of the country.
Thanks to the James report, published last year, this is a
well-recognised phenomenon in Scotland and steps are being taken by the
Scottish Office and others in an attempt to address the problem.
However, yesterday's findings -- concentrating as it does on children
aged between 18 months and four-and-a-half years -- highlights the fact
that Scottish parents are ignoring all the publicity concerning the
importance of diet.
They are carrying on feeding their children the same kinds of food
that they themselves like despite its likely contribution to the high
level of heart diesease in Scotland.
It would appear the message is not getting through.
''Children in Scotland were most likely to be eating chips, beef and
beef products, canned fruit in syrup and drinking soft drinks and were
least likely to be eating cheese, most types of vegetables, and drinking
fruit juice,'' the report declares.
Despite the findings, the report concludes that today's toddlers are
well nourished, taller, and -- perhaps less surprisingly -- in some
groups heavier than in the sixties.
The National Diet and Nutrition Survey was commissioned by the
Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries, and Food and the Department of
Health. It was carried out by the Office of Population Census and
Surveys and the MRC Dunn Nutrition Unit.
''The results of this excellent survey will be used to develop
long-term strategies for improving the health of children and setting
good eating habits for life,'' Baroness Cumberlege, a junior Health
Minister declared.
''I am certain that general practitioners, health visitors,
paediatricians, and others responsible for advising about health and
development of pre-school children will be able to make good use of this
data.''
The appended dental report, highlighting the high level of tooth decay
in Scotland amongst the under fives, left dentists more than slightly
annoyed. ''Parents should realise that dentistry is free for
under-fives,'' one of them said.
''They should also restrict sweets and confectionary to meal times and
make sure the children brush teeth regularly.''
* National Diet and Nutrition Survey: Children aged 1.5 to 4.5 years.
Volume 2: Report of the Dental Survey. HMSO. Price #14.50.
</TEXT>
