<HEADLINE>Author sues solicitors</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255621</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AUTHOR Douglas Sutherland yesterday sued two firms of solicitors over
their alleged negligent handling of a royalties dispute with his
publishers, Debrett Peerage Ltd.
Major Sutherland claims that #81,764 in royalties was due to him for
the years 1978-84 for his humorous series, The English Gentleman, The
English Gentleman's Wife, The English Gentleman's Mistress and The
English Gentleman's Child.
His counsel, Mr Mark Living, told Judge Young at the High Court in
London that between 1983 and 1988, Mr Richard Sykes, of Halkin Street,
Victoria, London, handled Major Sutherland's action against Debrett.
At the end of 1988, Tucker Turner Kingsley Wood and Co, of Chancery
Lane, London, took over the matter until 1990.
Major Sutherland, of Bridge House, South Queensferry, West Lothian,
then engaged another firm but they were unable to do much before the
action was struck out for want of prosecution.
Mr Living said Mr Sykes showed a very ''lackadaisical'' attitude and
it was that firm's greater negligence which set up what followed.
The firms deny negligence and claim they were not provided with
sufficient information or funds to pursue the claim at the material
times.
They say it was not an action worth pursuing because Debrett had an
answer to Major Sutherland's claim and would not have been liable.
The hearing continues.
</TEXT>
