<HEADLINE>Blair puts duty first. Challenge to the Tories. Labour leader puts duty first in challenge to the Tories.</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>GEOFFREY PARKHOUSE, POLITICAL EDITOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255622</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR leader Tony Blair put a dagger at the Prime Minister's heart
last night in a watershed speech based on the concept of duty.
Mr Blair, in a lecture set up by the right-wing Spectator magazine,
also focused on the prospect of pragmatic politics to match the
philosophy of a new generation. He claimed: ''The mood for change now in
Britain is more than about opinion polls or feel-good factors. It is a
belief that, as a country, we can be better than we are.''
He proposes that parents should be prosecuted for their children's
truancy as should citizens who make themselves objectionable by their
bad neighbourly behaviour such as loud noise, violence, intimidation or
racism.
He concedes the Marxist strand of Labour thinking was dangerous and
misleading and ill-founded.
He challenges the Tories to match his vision in the run-up to the
Scottish local elections next month and those in England in May. He had
already warned his Shadow Cabinet to be prepared for a General Election
this autumn as, as he puts it, the Tory Government disintegrates.
The Labour leader intended it as a watershed speech in the
philosophical political debate for these election contests to come.
It sidelined the Tory troubles over their nine MPs who are still off
the Government whip. They met last night for an hour in the Commons but
came to no decision over rejoining.
Mr Blair cut through this argument as a peripheral matter. ''The
Conservatives believe their problem is one of division. It is not. The
fundamental problem is lack of direction.
''They don't know where they are going. Until the direction is
resolved, the division will remain.''
The Blair vision outlined in The Spectator Lecture entitled, The
Rights We Enjoy Reflect the Duties We Owe, was delivered in the
knowledge that he will have solved the Clause 4 reform debate on
nationalisation at his special conference next month, and was addressed
to stealing the remainder of Mr Major's political clothes.
Duty was his keynote. Duty of the individual to the society in which
he lives -- which, delivered, gives the citizen a right of a duty from
the society to him.
''This is much more than a debate about words or rhetoric,'' he said,
despatching the Bennite Marxist left. ''In this sense, those opposed to
change are right when they say it goes to the very soul of the party.
But, so far from destroying our soul, it retrieves it.
''It rescues the left of centre from a false historical perspective
which linked it to a Marxist intellectual analysis. It broadens its
appeal beyond producer or class interests.
''It reaffirms the Labour Party as the keeper of the faith in certain
key social and political values, which define it from the left and
distinguish it from the right.'' Rewriting Clause 4 is an essential part
of the transformation of the Labour Party for Government.
Mr Blair was moving his personal performance as party leader up
several notches with the confidence of a man who is in full control of
his party and ready for Government.
His lecture last night pinpointed the Prime Minister's problems in not
being able to speak with quite the same authority. Mr Blair had already
confided to his Shadow Cabinet that an autumn election was still
unlikely but they must be ready for it with policy and presentation to
attract the disenchanted Tory voters.
It was a personal challenge to Mr Major to put his stamp on his own
party, right and left, Euro-sceptic or Europhile, and take the
consequences.
''For far too long, the Labour Party allowed the Conservatives to own
vast expanses of political territory to which they had no prior claim
and whose resources they largely squandered. It is time to reclaim the
ground and send the Conservatives into the nomadic existence they
deserve.''
The key challenges to a Labour Government he defined as: ''How we
modernise the country's economy to equip it for today's market and
tomorrow's. And how we move people from welfare to work, eliminating the
social evil of welfare dependency amongst able-bodied peoples.''
This stated, he declared that he is obsessed, not about people's
personal lives (ie the sleaze factor in Tory politics), but about their
duties to one another as citizens.
In a powerful passage, he condemned crime and vandalism, children's
access to drugs in school playgrounds, teachers assaulted by pupils, and
youngsters wandering homeless on the streets.
He contrasted this with the ''massive salaries paid to the few at the
top, whose income seems little related to company performance or
merit''.
For the last two decades, the Conservatives regarded the notion of
duty as their own but now neither seemed to understand it nor to act
upon it. Duty was an essential Labour concept at the heart of creating a
strong community or society.
Without it, freedom turned to ashes.
On that theme, he said : ''Parents have a duty, to their children and
to others affected by their children.'' He supported local authorities
who are taking action against parents on truancy.
</TEXT>
