<HEADLINE>Klondikers stay on board after judge turns down eviction order</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRUCE MCKAIN, LAW CORRESPONDENT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255623</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWENTY-FIVE striking Bulgarian seamen were sitting tight on board a
Klondiker last night after a judge refused to order their eviction.
Lord Clyde decided at the Court of Session that he would need further
and more clear information before taking the extreme step of ordering
the men off the MV Rotalia which is berthed in Lerwick Harbour,
Shetland.
Continuing the case for a week, the judge said: ''I take the view that
it would be too violent to throw out the crew today without being
satisfied of their being aware of their legal position.''
The court was told that Bourgwells (Bulgaria) Ltd, shipowners and
charterers based in London's docklands, bought the Rotalia, a stern
trawler and fish factory, from its previous Bulgarian owners, Okeanski
Ribolov.
There was a dispute with the previous owners over wages, with the
result that the crew had gone on strike and taken possession of the
vessel at Lerwick.
Bourgwells has already obtained a court order to prevent the 25 men
from obstructing a new crew from taking control of the Rotalia.
Mr Robert Howie, counsel for Bourgwells, said his information was
that, last weekend, the new crew had made three attempts to board the
vessel but these efforts had been repulsed by the strikers.
The view had been taken that discretion was the better part of valour
in the face of what might have been violent opposition and Bourgwells
was now asking the court for an order to have the 25 removed from the
vessel.
The Rotalia was needed urgently for a contract to catch and process a
substantial quantity of fish off Namibia.
Mr Howie disputed a claim by Mr Ralph Smith, counsel for the crewmen,
that under the sale of the vessel, Bourgwells was to pay the outstanding
wages owed to the crew.
Mr Smith explained that because of language difficulties it had been
difficult to obtain clear information.
Lord Clyde said he was not persuaded that the facts of the case were
sufficiently clear to enable him to take the relatively extreme remedy
of granting the eviction order at this stage.
He continued the case for seven days in the hope that communication
could be established between the two sides.
No doubt it could be explained to the 25 crewmen that there was
already an interdict in place and unpleasant consequences could follow
any breach of such a court order.
</TEXT>
