<HEADLINE>Queen asked for return of diamond</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255625</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BLACK township leaders in South Africa yesterday called on the Queen
to give back the Great Star of Africa diamond which is set in the Crown
jewels' sceptre.
The Azanian People's Organisation claims the diamond was ''stolen from
the treasures of the African soil''.
Azapo spokesman Zithulele Nxawe said: ''She must be reminded that the
diamond belongs to the black people of this country, and to them alone.
''The imperialistic Queen should know she is persona non grata until
she has corrected all previous and current wrongs.''
He was speaking ahead of the Queen's visit to New Brighton, a
sprawling black township near Port Elizabeth in Eastern Province.
Security for the visit has been stepped up after chaotic scenes on
Tuesday at Langa, a township outside Cape Town, where the Queen was
mobbed by excited youths.
The Great Star of Africa was bought by the Transvaal Republic from the
Premier Mine and presented to King Edward VII in 1907.
A Buckingham Palace official said the diamond was a gift, Crown
property, and ''part of the inalienable heritage of the nation''.
</TEXT>
