<HEADLINE>Renewed confidence turns Cumnock economy around</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROBERT MACLEOD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255626</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KEEN interest is being expressed by several companies concerning the
future of a new 20,000 sq ft factory building at Cumnock in Ayrshire,
intended to be one of the centrepieces of the town's new Business Park
development.
It is another aspect of the renaissance way in which Cumnock has
changed almost beyond recognition in mich less than a decade.
''Anyone who has been away from Cumnock for even a few years would
find it hard to believe how much of a change has taken place,'' said
John Walker, Director of Property and Land Development with Enterprise
Ayrshire. ''Forget the old image of a depressed and worn-out former
mining town left with only a legacy of high unemployment.''
Cumnock has been turned around, thanks to recent and massive
programmes of economic development. In the past seven years around #100m
has been spent in Government funding, topped by EU assists. Ten
sponsoring partners, including, Enterprise Ayrshire, the Cumnock and
Doon Valley Initiative and Strathclyde Region have been hard at work in
a co-ordinated programme ever since 1989.
''Our overall target has been to regenerate the local economy,
integrated with social objectives,'' said John Walker at Enterprise
Ayrshire headquarters at Kilmarnock. ''Today's Cumnock has a lot going
for it and for any organisation that decides to locate there. It has a
high quality and skilled workforce, it is within half an hour of key
motorway links and air and rail connections, and considerable strides
have been taken towards increasing the prosperity of local people and
businesses.''
The Business Park, Cumnock's latest asset, is located on the south
side of the town overlooking the Cumnock-Auchinleck bypass. A 15-acre
site, already fully serviced, it adjoins the established Caponare
Industrial Estate.
''The new Business Park has been developed by Enterprise Ayrshire and
the local district council at a cost of #1.5m,'' said John Walker. ''It
already houses a similar size of factory for Afton Spring Plc, producers
of bottled spring water, who will move into a shortly from other
premises in Cumnock.
''The key 25,000 sq ft unit that is attracting so much interest is an
excellent building with quality finish and a glass frontage, and is
fully landscaped. Enquiries we have received so far have included some
from electronics supply companies and firms associated with the textile
industry.''
The quality of Cumnock's workforce is another attraction. Since the
Initiative's conception, the amount of industrial sites in the area has
been expanded with over 50 units being let or re-let and more than 500
jobs being attracted or safeguarded.
''All the new companies now located in Cumnock have been delighted
with the quality and reliability of their new workforces,'' said John
Walker. ''One reason is that there has been a heavy investment in
training. Ayr College has established an annexe in the town providing
training in various branches of textile production. We have also
established comprehensive training in electronics. Young people are
among the many taking full advantage of these courses and looking
towards the future.''
Cumnock, fighting back against a 17% unemployment rate, is fast
recovering from the scars left from its mining past. Only occasional
reminders now persist from that time -- one is the A frame structure
from the former Barony Pit, which is to be retained as a listed
structure.
In and around the town a series of major changes reflect the
development programme which has already been carried out, with other
work still in progress. Another proposed future development will be a
major refurbishment of the main shopping centre area.
''There are other obvious attractions for new businesses thinking of
coming to Cumnock,'' said John Walker. ''Cumnock is a development area,
with maximum Government incentives available for any project. Looking
further ahead, plans for the Business Park include further development
on about 10 acres of adjacent land, offering ideal locations for
individual companies.
''New arrivals already in Cumnock have been delighted with what they
have discovered from enthusiastic local authority support and the skills
of local workers to the wide range of amenities that are on offer in the
area. The latter range from fishing on stocked reservoirs to golf at New
Cumnock and at Mauchline -- and remember that Cumnock is only half an
hour away from the major shopping centres of Kilmarnock and Ayr and the
other attractions, including theatres, that both can offer.
''From a business viewpoint, that same half hour of travel will take
drivers to the M74 and the way to the markets of the south. Prestwick
and Glasgow Airports with their freight or passenger links are also
within easy reach. ''
From its location on the A76 Kilmarnock-Dumfries road, the former
mining town has built itself new foundations for a very different
future.
''Much of the work to date has been about putting into place the
various building blocks required for economic regeneration,'' said John
Walker. ''Private and public sectors have worked closely together to
achieve a common objective, a future of real economic growth built on
partnership.
''Cumnock has very definitely changed. Now it is going forward.''
</TEXT>
