<DOCNO>GH950323-000198</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000198</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Actress 'robbed by teenage girls'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255627</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ACTRESS and model Elizabeth Hurley told a court yesterday how she was
robbed at knifepoint by four teenage girls as she walked home on her
own.
Miss Hurley, 29, said she was ''stunned'' to find herself surrounded
by the girls, one of whom held a six-inch knife an inch away from her
stomach.
She gave them #10 but one of them sneered: ''Is that all you've got?
That's not enough . . . we can't even get some Big Macs with that,''
Southwark Crown Court heard.
She said she found herself ''fenced in'' by the girls, who formed a
semi-circle around her, forcing her back against a pillar.
Ms Christina Guerrina, 18, of Bethnal Green, east London; Ms Carlene
Irving, 18, of Shepherd's Bush, west London, and a 17-year-old girl, who
cannot be named for legal reasons, deny robbing Miss Hurley of #10 and
some photographs.
A fourth girl, also 17, has pleaded guilty to robbing her and will be
sentenced later.
The girlfriend of Four Weddings and A Funeral star Hugh Grant was
mobbed by photographers as she arrived in a red BMW to give evidence.
She looked flustered as she struggled through the melee to the court
but quickly composed herself in the witness box, looking relaxed and
confident as she gave evidence for 90 minutes.
She flew in earlier from New York where she had been on a photo shoot
for Estee Lauder after signing a #3m contract with the cosmetics
company.
Miss Hurley told how she had been walking home from her office in
South Kensington when she was attacked last November.
She told the jury her route home from work took her along the Old
Brompton Road towards Earl's Court.
As she turned left into The Little Boltons, close to the flat she
shares with Mr Grant, she heard loud female voices behind her.
Turning, she saw four girls walking close behind. She stood aside to
let them pass but when she crossed the road into Redcliffe Square, they
suddenly veered towards her.
Miss Hurley said she later darted behind a car and ran into the road.
Then she saw a large white van coming towards her, and caused it to
stop. The driver ''leapt out'' leaving the engine running.
He sprinted towards the girls while Miss Hurley stayed by the van. She
said a woman, seeing what was going on, came out from a nearby house and
gave her a cup of coffee.
0 Prosecuting counsel Richard Onslow alleged that all the girls had
behaved aggressively towards Miss Hurley. They were arrested and taken
to Chelsea police station, where they made no comment.
Mr Robert Coloves, defending Guerrina, put it to her that when she
made a 999 call on a mobile phone given to her by a woman from a nearby
house, she described her attackers as two white girls and two black
girls.
Miss Hurley said: ''Maybe I did in the heat of the moment. I was in a
blind panic by then. The adrenalin hit me and I was shaking like a
leaf.'' He also said she told police her purse had been stolen and she
had been threatened with a penknife.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
