<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000199</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000199</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Wide range of support for the newcomer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SEAN FRANCIS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>979255628</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ALMOST exactly two years ago, Brian Duffy was, in his own words, ''a
young, naive and very inexperienced would-be business person''.
Today he is the technical director of his own thriving electronics
firm.
Dakon Electronics, designs, develops, manufactures and distributes
electronic products. To begin with, all it had was a series of product
ideas. ''At the time, we thought our business ideas were a 'sure
thing','' he said.
''Every new or young business needs expert help or advice if it is to
survive in this world. Support is required, not only in financial terms,
but in terms of good solid business advice in all the areas it needs
it.''
For him, this support came from Glasgow Opportunities, one of the
organisations which form part of the newly launched Glasgow Business
Shop Network. It will provide the necessary help and advice to get
fledgling businesses off to a good start.
The Glasgow Network is part of the Scottish Business Shop Network,
launched last year, which with Glasgow Opportunities, helped Mr Duffy
formulate and stick to a business plan, and obtain the financial advice
and assistance he needed.
''Through the huge wealth of experience available through all the
support agencies in the city, Dakon has been able thoroughly to examine
and form its plans in great detail,'' he said.
''At Dakon Electronics, through the benefit of all this advice and
experience, we have been able to look objectively at our business, with
the result that we now know we're on a sure thing.''
For the new business man or woman the list of questions they need
answers to may seem endless and to cover almost every subject from
accounts to grants to VAT. This is well understood, as Crawford
Beveridge, chief executive of Scottish Enterprise, pointed out in a
business start-up guide prepared by the Scottish Business Shop Network.
''In the early days it can be challenging and downright difficult,
especially if you've been used to an employer looking after tax,
National Insurance, legal requirements, VAT and a thousand and one other
details that must be attended to,'' he said.
''The Scottish Business Shop and the network of local enterprise
companies can't keep your books for you, but we can help make your
journey to being a successful small business much smoother.''
It is easy to be distracted from these essential administrative duties
for the best of motives. ''When you start your own business your
enthusiasm and energy is often directed at the actual business,'' he
said.
''While this is the central point of going into business, you must
devote much of your time, at least at the beginning, to attending to the
details of accounts, legal requirements, finance, marketing, premises,
staff and so on.''
The Business Shops offer a wide range of support for the business
newcomer, and can put them in touch with the right people in local
government, the professions, libraries, chambers of commerce, Government
departments, and any other relative organisation.
As Brian Duffy concluded, ''It is only by working together that we can
achieve all our goals and ambitions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000200</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000200</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Homeward bound: first major withdrawal of troops from Northern Ireland since IRA ceasefire. Sinn Fein claim meeting 'this week'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255629</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SINN Fein could be involved in ministerial talks with the Government
by the weekend, its senior party strategist Martin McGuinness claimed
last night.
As unprecedented disarmament talks between loyalists and Northern
Ireland Office Minister Michael Ancram ended in Belfast, Mr McGuinness
said he believed his party could be in discussions as early as Friday.
He said: ''There is an international expectation we move foward to the
next stage. There must be meetings between political representatives of
the British Government and Sinn Fein.''
He added: ''Sinn Fein is prepared to discuss anything -- including the
decommissioning of weapons.''
Although the Government insisted last night that Sinn Fein had not
given sufficient assurances to clear the way for ministerial dialogue,
it now seems the two sides are getting closer to reaching agreement for
the next stage of the peace process to begin.
Mr Ancram, following four-and-a-half hours of exploratory discussions
with representatives of the Progessive Unionist Party and the Ulster
Democratic Party, also hinted that an end to the deadlock with
republicans might not be far off.
He said: ''They (Sinn Fein) are moving towards giving us assurances
but, as of this time, we have not received clear assurances, which we
have made abundantly clear we require before a Minister enters
exploratory dialogue with them.''
Yesterday's talks with loyalists went ahead after the Northern Ireland
Office said they were satisfied with assurances about the
decommissioning issue, despite the fact representatives made clear their
position on the decommissioning of weapons had not changed -- no guns
would be surrendered until they were satisfied the environment was right
and there was trust on all sides.
Mr Ancram's decision to move into ministerial contact with the two
loyalist fringe organisations was announced just over an hour before the
sides were due to hold a scheduled meeting at Stormont.
It was taken up almost entirely by the decommissioning issue but the
Minister was left in no doubt that the Protestant paramilitaries are not
even considering handing in weapons.
Instead there were discussions about the logistics of such moves.
Mr Ancram said later that the whole basis of exploratory dialogue was
to achieve a method which is going to secure trust -- not just between
Sinn Fein and the loyalists, but across the community in Northern
Ireland.
He said: ''We are looking at a process which can achieve concrete
results. The loyalists have provided us with those assurances. They said
they would discuss constructively and positively the elements of
decommissioning. We await to hear similar clear assurances from Sinn
Fein before a Minister can become involved with them.''
Sinn Fein's Northern Ireland chairman, Mr Mitchel McLaughlin, said he
was confident his party would be in ministerial talks soon, adding: ''We
are not the obstacle.''
Reiterating Mr McGuinness's assertion that talks could start as early
as Friday, he told BBC Radio 4's PM programme he welcomed the Government
discussions with loyalists.
''I think they should have happened some time ago, and similarly with
Sinn Fein,'' he said. ''It's a question of when the British Government
recognises the right of those people who vote for Sinn Fein to have
their voices heard.''
Meanwhile, 440 soldiers flew out of Northern Ireland yesterday in the
first major withdrawal of troops since the IRA ceasefire began seven
months ago.
It is expected that the highly symbolic withdrawal of the 5th Regiment
Royal Artillery will be followed shortly by a second battalion, if the
ceasefire holds.
Commensurate reductions in the RUC and the Royal Irish Regiment will
become inevitable.
The troops later arrived at RAF Leeming, North Yorkshire, and boarded
coaches to take them to their home base at Marne Barracks, Catterick, to
be reunited with their families.
The regiment, which had been based at Drummad Barracks, in Armagh,
left a month ahead of schedule because of the scaled-down security
threat in Tyrone and Armagh.
* Irish police have uncovered 20lb of Semtex explosive during a search
in a borderside county.
The find was made on Tuesday night near the County Cavan village of
Mount Nugent. A detonator and a pistol were discovered at the same time.
A man held for questioning about the find was released yesterday.
The Semtex and other weapons were thought to have been stored in the
area by the IRA ahead of their ceasefire declaration last summer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH950323-000201</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH950323-000201</DOCID>
<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Kray tells of doubts over brother's death</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255630</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
REGGIE Kray claimed last night there was ''conflicting'' evidence
about the cause of his twin brother Ronnie's death.
He suggested he may have died after a ''struggle'' as he resisted a
hospital test involving the insertion of a tube down his throat.
Kray, who rang a radio station last night to talk about his doubts, is
demanding a second post-mortem examination on the body of his brother.
''I'm not saying that this did take place but there is always a
probability when people don't like things being put down their throats,
so a struggle could have ensued,'' he told Talk Radio UK.
''This is an assumption but I feel that I have reason to doubt.''
Ronnie Kray, 61, suffered a heart attack and died last Friday after
being rushed to hospital from Broadmoor where he was serving life for
murder.
East Berkshire coroner Robert Wilson held his inquest a day later
without telling the press and public and reached his verdict of death by
natural causes in less than three minutes.
Reggie Kray, who is also serving life for murder, claimed last night
the full facts have yet to emerge.
In a telephone call from Maidstone prison, he said his brother's
doctor at Broadmoor, Dr Jose Romero, had told him Ronnie was physically
strong and his death had come as a shock.
''He said he had seen him shortly before the date of death and this
made him more shocked as he didn't visualise him dying from any known
cause.
''So there is a lot of doubt in my mind and then I heard about this
inquest that only took three minutes and was very rushed . . . (that)
put even more doubt in my mind,'' Kray said.
The gangland killer claimed he had been told by another doctor that
his brother received a massive blood transfusion, which he said had been
kept secret until now.
He said Ronnie had no history of heart trouble and added that there
was also a suggestion that his brother had an ulcer and had suffered
internal bleeding, which had not been ''mentioned''.
''There is a conflict in my mind and in the facts as I've been given
(them),'' he said.
He has already announced that he is postponing his brother's funeral
until ''the situation has been sorted''.
</TEXT>
