<HEADLINE>Chancellor defends Pennant-Rea</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255631</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Chancellor, Mr Kenneth Clarke, tried to persuade Mr Rupert
Pennant-Rea to stay on as Deputy Governor of the Bank of England, it was
revealed yesterday.
Mr Clarke put up a staunch defence of Mr Pennant-Rea and said it was
''absurd'' he had been hounded out of office by stories about his
private life.
However, the Chancellor, who has ultimate responsibility for the post,
failed to hold sway over Mr Pennant-Rea, who announced his resignation
on Tuesday after his mistress revealed their three-year extra-marital
affair.
Mr Clarke said: ''I personally did not see any reason for him to leave
public life. I made it quite clear to him as far as I was concerned he
could stay -- absolutely clear.
''It's absurd to lose a Deputy Governor of the Bank of England because
some newspaper wishes to print stories about his private life.''
Downing Street stressed later that the Government had not asked Mr
Pennant-Rea to quit and all resignations were a matter of regret.
However, its tone towards Mr Pennant-Rea, 47, was distinctly cooler
than the Chancellor's vigorous support.
The former deputy governor remained tight lipped as he returned to the
Bank to clear his desk. As the search began for a successor to his
#180,000-a-year post, bank officials insisted he would not receive a
''golden handshake'' -- despite reports of a settlement which could
reach #500,000. He will get a maximum payment of #45,000.
The woman involved in his downfall -- Mary Ellen Synon -- denied she
was motivated by personal gain in going public over their affair.
Her kiss-and-tell confessions in a Sunday newspaper led to the
resignation.
American-born Miss Synon, 44, said yesterday: ''I have neither asked
for, nor received, any money for talking to any newspaper.''
Miss Synon, an Irish-based freelance journalist, said: ''Despite what
has been written in the newspapers, I did not much want Rupert to lose
his job.''
</TEXT>
