<HEADLINE>Forces join in business shop network</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SEAN FRANCIS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>SCOTLANDS BUSINESS</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255632</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
The Scottish business shop network was launched last year with a
purpose to bring together those involved in developing the Scottish
economy. Sean Francis reports on the initiative that gives Scottish
businesses access to a wide range of business and commercial
information.
KNOWING whose door to knock on when you need help with your business
is easier if there is only one door. Making all the help available
behind one door is effectively what happened this week when a new
business initiative was launched.
The initiative brings together sources of advice which are all too
often spread out and, as The Herald reported on Tuesday, the purpose is
to provide information on all aspects of business, from start-up to
finance.
''It brings together the three main funders of economic development in
the city: Glasgow Development Agency, the City Council, and Strathclyde
Region, and adds the Chamber of Commerce with its unique access to the
private sector,'' said the GDA's Russell Simpson.
''These organisations have joined together not to create another
organisation but to enhance and develop the existing organisation's
abilities to assist our business clients.''
It is, however, only part of a bigger network. The Scottish Business
Shop network was launched in April last year to link all organisations
involved in developing the Scottish economy. The aim was to give
business a service which was both cost-effective and consistent.
Regional partnerships were formed between the economic development
bodies responsible for supporting companies in their area. More that 100
public sector organisations are involved, including regional councils,
district councils, chambers of commerce and local enterprise companies.
These partnerships help to ensure the service provided in each region
reflects local needs and to reassure customers that all the main
business service providers are involved.
The Scottish Network will be represented by individual business shops
operating within host organisations. Every business shop which wants to
join the network must be accredited to ensure consistent service.
Accreditation will be granted only after the shops have proved they
have the necessary systems and standards, and are committed to
continuous improvement. The sign of accreditation is the SBS Gateway
symbol.
Mr Simpson described this week's launch as ''a Glasgow response to a
Scottish-wide initiative''. There are nine shops in Glasgow, hosted by
organisations with roots in their local business communities, including
Glasgow Opportunities, Glasgow North Ltd, East End Partnership, Gorbals
Initiative and the Govan Initiative.
So that everybody who wants to can have access to a business shop, the
network has been extended so that it will also provide services via
Greater Easterhouse Development Agency, Castlemilk Economic Development
Agency and Drumchapel Opportunities. These agencies will become fully
accredited shops as demand for their services increases.
What distinguishes the business shop network is the fact that it is a
network. It draws from all sources to provide concise information from
just one location. The client gets the right information and advice
without having to contact each individual provider.
Those providing assistance will receive clients who know more about
the type of help they need and will receive fewer inquiries from people
they cannot help. It will mean scarce resources, including time, will be
used more efficiently.
The business shops have access to Companies House and the Patents
Office, and via the hub shop in Bothwell Street they can access services
from the Government Business Shop, including help on VAT, health and
safety, arbitration and conciliation services.
There is another advantage. ''It will give us, the organisations
charged with economic development in the city, information on what the
customer needs,'' said Mr Simpson. ''This information will enable us
accurately to develop solutions accordingly.''
He said it would add significantly to their ability to help businesses
in Glasgow.
Professor Donald Mackay, chairman of Scottish Enterprise, added: ''The
network offers existing and potential Scottish businesses
quality-assured and consistent access to a wide range of business and
commercial information.
''I believe that in this way, the network is an invaluable link
between the customer and the many sources of information and assistance
in Scotland.''
Herald editor George McKechnie, who officially launched the new
network, stressed the importance of matching the information to the
inquiry.
''The new business shop network in Glasgow embraces the improvement of
support for all sections of business from start-up to small, moderately
successful companies seeking growth and even more spectacular firms
hammering out plans for expansion,'' he said.
''The main idea is to cut out confusion and save the business person
time and effort when making any kind of inquiry, whether it's about
start-up funding or guidance on exporting. It is also a good example of
the way in which public and private sector can work together for the
benefit of everyone.''
</TEXT>
