<HEADLINE>MP claims 'intimidation' by abuse case lawyers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>ILLUS</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>979255634</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LAWYERS representing families in the Ayrshire child abuse case were
accused in the Commons yesterday of trying to ''intimidate'' MPs.
Labour MP George Foulkes (Carrick, Cumnock and Doon Valley) protested
in a point of order that an attempt was being made to stop him looking
after the interests of social workers who were his constituents.
He told Speaker Betty Boothroyd: ''Some of the lawyers representing
families in the Ayrshire child abuse case have been quoted in the press
as saying that MPs should not raise matters on behalf of their
constituents.
''I represent seven of the social workers involved.
''I consider the action taken by these lawyers is intimidation to me
-- trying to stop me performing my role as their MP.''
Mr Foulkes asked: ''I would hope you would make it clear that not even
the most distinguished Scots lawyers can stop MPs from looking after the
interests of their constituents.''
Miss Boothroyd told him: ''I am sure you aren't intimidated by any
such comment made outside the House.
''All Members here have a duty to carry out their responsibilities on
behalf of their constituents and they will certainly do so while I am
Speaker of this House.''
The case concerned eight children taken into care five years ago amid
allegations of ritual sex abuse. They were told last month they were to
be returned home after a High Court ruling.
</TEXT>
