<DATE>950323</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Milk not E-coli source, says lawyer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>979255635</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOP-QUALITY milk from a farm has been dumped for the past 10 months
after it was wrongly branded the source of a fatal food poisoning
outbreak, it was claimed yesterday.
Solicitor Ken Hogg told Linlithgow Sheriff Court that Redhouse Farm,
at Blackburn, West Lothian, was now in serious financial trouble.
He said: ''The consequences have been extreme. Nobody will take milk
from this farm. They fear it is implicated in the E-coli outbreak -- and
that is rubbish.''
Mr Hogg was speaking after the farm's owners, Robert Findlay &amp;
Company, admitted failing to bury three cattle carcasses which were
found on the farm last May. Two of the carcasses had been partially
eaten by animals, and one was lying under a collapsed shed. There was
nothing left but the skeleton.
Mr Hogg said: ''They were waiting for the knackers' lorry to arrive.''
The company was fined #750 by Sheriff Anella Cowan.
Mr Hogg told how the Scottish Milk Marketing Board started dumping
Redhouse Farm milk after cattle were found dead on the farm by council
health experts, searching for the original source of last summer's
outbreak of food poisoning in West Lothian.
However, after November, when the board was scrapped by the
Government, the company could find nobody else to buy its milk.
Mr Hogg said the board had been paying a premium for Redhouse Farm
milk because of its high quality.
He added: ''My clients are producing milk every day. It is being put
into the manure and spread on the lands. There is a farm somewhere else
that has this E-coli problem. It is not my client's. That can be proved.
''But it is the Findlays who are paying the financial penalty. Milk is
their main source of income.''
After the case, farmer John Findlay, 43, claimed that he had lost
three-quarters of his income because of the milk scare.
He added: ''We have done nothing wrong and yet we are being
victimised.''
</TEXT>
